insert into document (documentID, lang, content) values (default, engels, 'NodeBox OpenGL draw performance','<p>Research question: can we improve the draw performance of NodeBox by porting it to OpenGL?</p>\r\n<p>NodeBox is an open-source application that lets you create 2D visuals (static, animated or interactive) using Python programming code and export them as a PDF or a QuickTime movie. NodeBox is free and well-documented.</p>\r\n<p>NodeBox is currently written as a Mac OS X application, using the Quartz graphics API. Multiple ports exists, for example to Qt in Linux. It is our belief that a port to OpenGL can improve performance. OpenGL provides a set of modern API\'s related to vertex arrays, Vertex Buffer Objects, etc. The project would study the impact of each of these features on the performance, while keeping the current NodeBox drawing API intact.</p>\r\n<p>http://nodebox.net/ http://www.cityinabottle.org/nodebox/</p>');
insert into document (documentID, lang, content) values (default, engels, 'NodeBox scene graph: raw performance','<p>Research question: can we improve raw performance by moving to different data structures?</p>\r\n<p>NodeBox is an open-source application that lets you create 2D visuals (static, animated or interactive) using Python programming code and export them as a PDF or a QuickTime movie. NodeBox is free and well-documented.</p>\r\n<p>NodeBox provides a drawing API that converts commands into a scene graph, which is then rendered. The scene graph is constructed traditionally, using objects for paths and points. Big scenes can contain thousands of paths, each containing hundreds of points. This means that objects have a potentially massive overhead. The project would study if moving to non-traditional data structures could improve the performance of the scene graph. This means looking into storage and handling characteristics of arrays and primitives in Python.</p>\r\n<p>http://nodebox.net/</p>');
