insert into document (documentID, lang, content) values (default, engels, 'Empirical Study on Test Refactoring','<h2>Introduction</h2>\r\n<p><span style=\"letter-spacing: 0.02px;\">Refactoring is the process of changing a software system in such a way that it does not alter the external behavior of the code yet improves its internal structure. van Duersen et al. provided formal definitions for some common refactorings on the test code and investigated the relationship between test code and refactoring. However, this study was mainly based on anecdotal evidence. process of refactoring is generally studied in the context of production code, namely all formally identified refactorings are regarding the production code. Test code, even if it can be refactored as well, has not been investigated as much as the production code.&nbsp;</span></p>\r\n<p>The goal of this thesis is to analyze the phenomena of test refactoring based on empirical analysis.</p>\r\n<h2>Details</h2>\r\n<p><span style=\"letter-spacing: 0.02px;\">In this thesis, the student has to:</span></p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Create a dataset of refactored test suites</li>\r\n<li>Create a tool for classification of test refactoring</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p>During the development of the thesis the student will improve his/her knowledge of:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Refactoring</li>\r\n<li>Testing</li>\r\n<li>The BOA repository (A Language and Infrastructure for Analyzing Ultra-Large Scale Software Repositories) [ <a href=\"http://boa.cs.iastate.edu\" target=\"_blank\">http://boa.cs.iastate.edu</a> ]</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<h2>Requirements</h2>\r\n<p>The skills required for the Master Thesis are:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Good programming skills (better if she/he knows Java/Python)</li>\r\n<li>Prior knowledge about software testing, and refactoring</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<h2>Related work</h2>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Refactoring Test Code Safely. Guerra</li>\r\n<li>Refactoring Test Code. Van Deursen</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<h2>&nbsp;</h2>\r\n<h2>Tech:</h2>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li><span style=\"letter-spacing: 0.02px;\">Create RefFinder for Test Refactoring (templates)</span></li>\r\n</ul>');
insert into document (documentID, lang, content) values (default, engels, 'Mutation Testing of C++ Programs ','<h2>Introduction</h2>\r\n<p>Mutation testing is a known method to assess the quality of a test suite. The process for mutation testing is as follows: First, buggy versions of the software are created by introducing a single bug into the system (Mutation). This is done by applying a known transformation on a certain part of the code (Mutation Operator). After generating the buggy versions of the software (Mutants), the test suite is executed on each one of these mutants. If there is an error or failure during the execution of the test suite, the mutant is regarded as killed (Killed Mutant). On the other hand, if all tests pass, it means that the test suite could not catch the bug and the mutant has survived (Survived Mutant). The final score (Mutation Coverage) is calculated by dividing the number of killed mutants to the number of all mutants. Because of the complexities of the C++ language, no mutation testing tool is available for this language. We try to fix this problem by repurposing a tool (LittleDarwin) to perform mutation testing on C++ programs.</p>\r\n<h2>Requirements</h2>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>A good knowledge of software testing</li>\r\n<li>Experience with Python, and C++</li>\r\n<li>Experience with C++ compilers such as g++ and clang++</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<h2>Steps</h2>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Understanding LittleDarwin code</li>\r\n<li>Creating a semi-parser to gather required info from C++ files</li>\r\n<li>Creating mutation operators for C++ version of LittleDarwin</li>\r\n<li>Checking the compliance of generated mutants using a C++ compiler</li>\r\n<li>Conducting experiments with the new system</li>\r\n</ul>');
insert into document (documentID, lang, content) values (default, engels, 'Gamification of Test Development Using Mutation Testing','<h1>Introduction</h1>\r\n<p>Testing software systems is one of the important steps in software development cycle. The higher the quality of the test suite for a system is, the sooner the bugs are caught, saving time and resources. Therefore it is important to have a high quality test suite. By gamifying the process of test development, the developers are encouraged to test their software more thoroughly, resulting in a better test suite. Mutation testing is a proven method to measure the quality of a test suite and to find its weaknesses. Mutation testing has been used before as a stopping criterion for augmenting a test suite. <br />For this research we will use mutation testing as a scoring technique as well as a guide to find classes in need of more testing. We use a game system inside an IDE to provide feedback on the status of the test suite and the points each developer has earned by developing new tests.</p>\r\n<h1>Details</h1>\r\n<p>In this thesis, the student has to:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li><span style=\"letter-spacing: 0.02px;\">Create a scoring system based on different types of mutants.&nbsp;</span></li>\r\n<li><span style=\"letter-spacing: 0.02px;\">Create a gamification system with a client inside an IDE, and a server to keep track of scores.&nbsp;</span></li>\r\n<li><span style=\"letter-spacing: 0.02px;\">Incorporate or adapt a mutation testing plugin to use in the client IDE.&nbsp;</span></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p><span style=\"letter-spacing: 0.02px;\">During the development of the thesis the student will improve his/her knowledge of:</span></p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li><span style=\"letter-spacing: 0.02px;\">Software testing&nbsp;</span></li>\r\n<li><span style=\"letter-spacing: 0.02px;\">Test development&nbsp;</span></li>\r\n<li><span style=\"letter-spacing: 0.02px;\">Mutation testing</span></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<h1>Requirements</h1>\r\n<p>The skills required for the Master Thesis are:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li><span style=\"letter-spacing: 0.02px;\">Good programming skills (better if she/he knows Java/Python)&nbsp;</span></li>\r\n<li><span style=\"letter-spacing: 0.02px;\">Prior knowledge about software testing&nbsp;</span></li>\r\n<li><span style=\"letter-spacing: 0.02px;\">Familiarity with plugin development</span></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<h1>Related work</h1>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li><span style=\"letter-spacing: 0.02px;\">On guiding the augmentation of an automated test suite via mutation analysis by Smith and Williams.</span></li>\r\n<li><span style=\"letter-spacing: 0.02px;\">Mutation analysis vs. code coverage in automated assessment of students\' testing skills by Aaltonen, Ihantola, and Sepp&auml;l&auml;.</span></li>\r\n</ul>');
insert into document (documentID, lang, content) values (default, engels, 'OpenFlow-based multi-homed hybrid home networks','<p style=\"letter-spacing: 0.02px;\">A home network often consists of multiple access technologies: ethernet, WiFi, powerline, &nbsp;etc. It is often not possible to automatically switch between these networks: if your wireless network is suffering from connectivity issues you cannot easily switch to one of the other access technologies without breaking the cconnection.<span style=\"letter-spacing: 0.02px;\">&nbsp;</span></p>\r\n<p style=\"letter-spacing: 0.02px;\">Network virtualization is a new paradigm that allows introducing an increased level of abstraction to today\'s networks. This is similar to how server virtualization has introduced the concept of cloud computing. Network virtualization could solve the above connectivity challenges as you can maintain connectivity by performing an automatic migration from one network to another network. In this case, the virtualized network remains the same but the mapping to the physical network changes transparently.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p style=\"letter-spacing: 0.02px;\">Network virtualization is becoming more and more popular and several mature prototypes already exist. The goal of this internship is to use these prototypes for building a multi-homed network: a network consisting of multiple access technologies and allowing auto migration scenarios.&nbsp;</p>');
insert into document (documentID, lang, content) values (default, engels, 'Deep learning MHC binding preferences','<p style=\"line-height: 1.38; margin-top: 0pt; margin-bottom: 0pt; text-align: justify;\" dir=\"ltr\"><span style=\"font-size: 14.666666666666666px; font-family: Arial; color: #000000; background-color: transparent; font-weight: 400; font-style: normal; font-variant: normal; text-decoration: none; vertical-align: baseline; white-space: pre-wrap;\">Deep learning is one of the latest breakthrough in the field of machine learning. Although based on the concept of neural networks, it can solve complex problems with a much higher accuracy thanks to several novel techniques. Deep learning is heavily being used by several large data mining driven companies, including Google Deepmind and Facebook. </span></p>\r\n<p><span id=\"docs-internal-guid-f3959232-e927-0187-6f0f-1e4540f77930\"><span style=\"font-size: 14.666666666666666px; font-family: Arial; background-color: transparent; vertical-align: baseline; white-space: pre-wrap;\">In this project we wish to assess if deep learning is a viable approach to tackle the problem of predicting MHC binding preferences. The MHC proteins are an important part of the human immune system that can bind small molecules derived from pathogens. Accurate prediction of which molecules they can bind and with which strength is therefore a relevant research topic for biomedical research. Large databases exist that can be used for training such models. Currently the state-of-the-art is a regular single-layer neural network, however we believe that deep learning should be able to outperform these methods.</span></span></p>\r\n<p style=\"line-height: 1.38; margin-top: 0pt; margin-bottom: 0pt;\" dir=\"ltr\"><span style=\"font-size: 14.666666666666666px; font-family: Arial; color: #000000; background-color: transparent; font-weight: 400; font-style: normal; font-variant: normal; text-decoration: none; vertical-align: baseline; white-space: pre-wrap;\">Audience:</span></p>\r\n<p style=\"line-height: 1.38; margin-top: 0pt; margin-bottom: 0pt;\" dir=\"ltr\"><span style=\"font-size: 14.666666666666666px; font-family: Arial; color: #000000; background-color: transparent; font-weight: 400; font-style: normal; font-variant: normal; text-decoration: none; vertical-align: baseline; white-space: pre-wrap;\">Computer science students</span></p>\r\n<p style=\"line-height: 1.38; margin-top: 0pt; margin-bottom: 0pt;\" dir=\"ltr\"><span style=\"font-size: 14.666666666666666px; font-family: Arial; color: #000000; background-color: transparent; font-weight: 400; font-style: normal; font-variant: normal; text-decoration: none; vertical-align: baseline; white-space: pre-wrap;\">Master thesis</span></p>\r\n<p style=\"line-height: 1.38; margin-top: 0pt; margin-bottom: 0pt;\" dir=\"ltr\"><span style=\"font-size: 14.666666666666666px; font-family: Arial; color: #000000; background-color: transparent; font-weight: 400; font-style: normal; font-variant: normal; text-decoration: none; vertical-align: baseline; white-space: pre-wrap;\"><br /></span></p>\r\n<p style=\"line-height: 1.38; margin-top: 0pt; margin-bottom: 0pt;\" dir=\"ltr\"><span style=\"font-size: 14.666666666666666px; font-family: Arial; color: #000000; background-color: transparent; font-weight: 400; font-style: normal; font-variant: normal; text-decoration: none; vertical-align: baseline; white-space: pre-wrap;\">Necessary background:</span></p>\r\n<p style=\"line-height: 1.38; margin-top: 0pt; margin-bottom: 0pt;\" dir=\"ltr\"><span style=\"font-size: 14.666666666666666px; font-family: Arial; color: #000000; background-color: transparent; font-weight: 400; font-style: normal; font-variant: normal; text-decoration: none; vertical-align: baseline; white-space: pre-wrap;\">Basic understanding of machine learning algorithms and their evaluation. Coding skills in a language with deep learning support (i.e. Python, Lua or C++).</span></p>\r\n<p style=\"line-height: 1.38; margin-top: 0pt; margin-bottom: 0pt;\" dir=\"ltr\"><span style=\"font-size: 14.666666666666666px; font-family: Arial; color: #000000; background-color: transparent; font-weight: 400; font-style: normal; font-variant: normal; text-decoration: none; vertical-align: baseline; white-space: pre-wrap;\"><br /></span></p>\r\n<p style=\"line-height: 1.38; margin-top: 0pt; margin-bottom: 0pt;\" dir=\"ltr\"><span style=\"font-size: 14.666666666666666px; font-family: Arial; color: #000000; background-color: transparent; font-weight: 400; font-style: normal; font-variant: normal; text-decoration: none; vertical-align: baseline; white-space: pre-wrap;\">Techniques:</span></p>\r\n<p style=\"line-height: 1.38; margin-top: 0pt; margin-bottom: 0pt;\" dir=\"ltr\"><span style=\"font-family: Arial; font-size: 14.666666666666666px; white-space: pre-wrap; background-color: transparent; letter-spacing: 0.02px;\">Deep learning</span></p>');
insert into document (documentID, lang, content) values (default, engels, 'Metric for determining test refactoring candidates','<h2>Introduction</h2>\r\n<p>Refactoring is the process of &nbsp;changing a software system in such a way that it does not alter the external behavior of the code yet improves its internal structure. There are multiple tools available to detect refactoring candidates in production code. However, the same is not true for test code. Knowing which tests require refactoring can make the test maintenance activity an easier job, and it can ease the development of new tests. To create such a tool, first we need to define a metric to quantify test smells. van Duersen et al.[1] provided formal definitions for some common refactorings on the test code and investigated the relationship between test code and refactoring. These can be used as a basis to create the metric we need.</p>\r\n<h2><span style=\"letter-spacing: 0.02px;\">Details</span></h2>\r\n<p>In this thesis, the student has to:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li><span style=\"letter-spacing: 0.02px;\">Create a metric based on known test smells&nbsp;</span></li>\r\n<li><span style=\"letter-spacing: 0.02px;\">Create a tool to compute this metric</span></li>\r\n<li><span style=\"letter-spacing: 0.02px;\">Use an actual data set judged by experts to fine tune and validate the metric</span></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p><span style=\"letter-spacing: 0.02px;\">During the development of the thesis the student will improve his/her knowledge of:&nbsp;</span></p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li><span style=\"letter-spacing: 0.02px;\">Refactoring</span></li>\r\n<li><span style=\"letter-spacing: 0.02px;\">Test smells</span></li>\r\n<li><span style=\"letter-spacing: 0.02px;\">Metrics and tuning algorithms</span></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<h2><span style=\"letter-spacing: 0.02px;\">Requirements</span></h2>\r\n<p>The skills required for the Master Thesis are:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li><span style=\"letter-spacing: 0.02px;\">Good programming skills (better if she/he knows Java/Python)</span></li>\r\n<li><span style=\"letter-spacing: 0.02px;\">Prior knowledge about software testing, and refactoring</span></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<h2>Related work</h2>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li><span style=\"letter-spacing: 0.02px;\">Refactoring Test Code Safely. Guerra</span></li>\r\n<li><span style=\"letter-spacing: 0.02px;\">Refactoring Test Code. Van Deursen</span></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p>________________</p>\r\n<p>[1] Arie Deursen, Leon M.F. Moonen, A. Bergh, and Gerard Kok. 2001. Refactoring Test Code. Technical Report. CWI, Amsterdam, The Netherlands, The Netherlands.</p>');
insert into document (documentID, lang, content) values (default, engels, 'BLE localization in smart homes','<p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span lang=\"EN-US\">One of the most promising use cases of the Internet of Things &ndash; where we connect all kinds of devices to the internet &ndash; is the smart home context. In the homes and buildings of the future we expect that the infrastructure can do a large amount of tasks without human interaction. Examples of such tasks are energy management, security, remote controlling, improved network connectivity. A key challenge for many of these applications, is the accurate estimation of the location of the persons in such a smart building.<br /> In this internship or thesis we will start from previous work on location estimation using Bluetooth Low Energy (BLE) and cover three different challenges:</span></p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li><span style=\"letter-spacing: 0.02px; text-indent: -18pt; font-family: Symbol;\" lang=\"EN-US\"><span style=\"font-stretch: normal; font-size: 7pt; line-height: normal; font-family: \'Times New Roman\';\">&nbsp;</span></span><span style=\"letter-spacing: 0.02px; text-indent: -18pt;\" lang=\"EN-US\">First of all, we want to improve the accuracy of existing techniques. An interesting option is the usage of other technologies in cooperation with BLE, like Wi-Fi, ZigBee, accelerometer, gyroscope, &hellip;</span></li>\r\n<li><span style=\"text-indent: -18pt; letter-spacing: 0.02px; font-family: Symbol;\" lang=\"EN-US\"><span style=\"font-stretch: normal; font-size: 7pt; line-height: normal; font-family: \'Times New Roman\';\">&nbsp;</span></span><span style=\"text-indent: -18pt; letter-spacing: 0.02px;\" lang=\"EN-US\">In a second phase we want to take into account the fact that humans have regular reoccurring patterns to get a better location estimation. In other words, we want to incorporate a learning aspect to the algorithm, that takes into account the real-time constraints of the localization.</span></li>\r\n<li><span style=\"text-indent: -18pt; letter-spacing: 0.02px;\">A third aspect that should be addressed, is the behavior with multiple users. In a home or work environment there is normally more then one person present. In current solutions this is often not taken into account.</span></li>\r\n</ul>');
insert into document (documentID, lang, content) values (default, engels, 'Wi-Fi / LTE loadbalancer for Android devices','<p>In the modern world, we all use our smartphone or tablet to stay connected in an almost 24/7 fashion. While the devices of today support multiple technologies it is not possible to use them together. Let&rsquo;s consider the following two situations:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>A device has both Wi-Fi and LTE enabled and is using Wi-Fi to transmit some data. When the user moves further away from the Wi-Fi access point, the quality of the connection will drop, while the quality of the LTE connection might be better. Currently, the device will keep on trying to transmit data over Wi-Fi, instead of performing a handover to the other technology.</li>\r\n<li>A second situation that might occur is that both Wi-Fi and LTE are available, but only one of them is used. However, it might be the case that there are applications that need more bandwidth then is possible with only one connection.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p>This thesis or internship wants to address these issues and has the following goal: the design and development of a load balancer for Android devices. This application should operate on the MAC layer be able to do the following things:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>The load balancer should be able to schedule traffic flows over the two different interfaces at the same time.</li>\r\n<li>The load balancer should be able to perform a handover from one technology to another.</li>\r\n</ul>');
insert into document (documentID, lang, content) values (default, engels, 'Security in Smart Cities','<p>One of the most important trends in the digital landscape is the Internet of Things (IoT), where we connected all kinds of devices with the internet. This new environment opens the doors to many new economical, technological and sociological innovations. An example of such a use case is a smart city. However, there are also big risks: for instance, sensitive data might become compromised or devices might be hacked by malicious persons. A key issue in the security of such IoT networks, is the fact that we do not know what the typical network traffic flows will be. Thus making it hard to distinguish normal and malicious behavior on the network.</p>\r\n<p>The MOSAIC research group is involved in the City of Things project (<a href=\"https://www.uantwerpen.be/en/rg/mosaic/city-of-things/\">https://www.uantwerpen.be/en/rg/mosaic/city-of-things</a>), where a large amount of sensors, gateways and other infrastructure have been deployed in the city of Antwerp. &nbsp;A detailed logging system will be deployed on these network devices, allowing us to get an overview of how such an IoT network will behave in the real world. &nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>The goal of this thesis or internship is to analyze the captured data and define a set of rules that describe the typical networking behavior. In a second phase it might be possible to design an intrusion detection system that uses those rules in order to detect malicious activities.</p>');
insert into document (documentID, lang, content) values (default, engels, 'Feasibility study of Time Series Databases for Newtec Dialog','<p>Newtec (www.newtec.eu) is a company located in Sint-Niklaas that designs, develops and produces technology for satellite communication.</p>\r\n<p><span style=\"letter-spacing: 0.02px;\">One of Newtec\'s biggest products is the Dialog system. It is an integrated system providing bi- directional services over satellite. The system can be split into a HUB system, deployed at a ground station and the various remote terminals, depending on the use case ranging from several modems to some thousands. The HUB part consists of a mix of networking equipment, general purpose servers hosting virtual machines (primarily Linux servers) and specialised Newtec RF equipment (modulators and demodulators). A 3rd party monitoring is used to monitor both platform level resources (bandwidth, CPU usage, disk usage) of the HUB systems as well to monitor the operational aspects of the provided services and the status of the remotes.</span></p>\r\n<p><span style=\"letter-spacing: 0.02px;\">In their efforts to further grow and scale the Dialog system, Newtec would like to investigate the use of Time Series Databases (Carbon, InfluxDB,OpenTSDB, ...). The main change in this model would be a change from a poll based system where typically SNMP is used by a central entity to gather statistics, to a push based model where all entities push their relevant statistics to a (distributed) time series database. Some possible challenges or unknowns which could be addressed are already identified:</span></p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li><span style=\"letter-spacing: 0.02px;\">Dimensioning: how to characterise the required resources needed to process and store a selected set of parameters. Depending on the aggregation strategies and retention strategies, how long can we keep a certain dataset on a limited amount of storage. How much processing and memory resources are needed to gather and store a certain set of data.</span></li>\r\n<li><span style=\"letter-spacing: 0.02px;\">Scalability: What architecture can be used in order to ensure that with the dynamic growth of the system (more terminals, additional capacity, ...) sufficient monitoring capacity can be added. This is related to the previous task. If we could deploy a Virtual Machine, dimensioned to be able to cope with X metrics, how would we be able to add additional backend VMs and how would we direct traffic to the right backends? Message brokers or queues could be a solution here.</span></li>\r\n<li><span style=\"letter-spacing: 0.02px;\">Reliability: failure of a monitoring node should not impact the availability of the entire service. How can data be duplicated across entities to ensure the needed data is always available. Message brokers could come into the picture here as well.</span></li>\r\n<li><span style=\"letter-spacing: 0.02px;\">Overall performance: what would be the overall impact on introducing the push based model on to our system. Does it have more or less impact than the current mode? How does the networking load compare to the SNMP traffic?</span></li>\r\n<li><span style=\"letter-spacing: 0.02px;\">Interfaces and APIs: SNMP is widely supported, but not all metrics we collect are available by SNMP. Some of the metrics are today stored in files and read by consumers which eventually ship it to our monitoring system. What would be the impact to alter some of our applications to directly send metrics in to the TSDB? Are sufficient libraries available for the used programming languages and what would be the impact on time critical applications of writing to the TSDB instead of writing to file?</span></li>\r\n<li><span style=\"letter-spacing: 0.02px;\">Data visualisation: what options do exist to visualise the stored data? Tools like graphite and grafana support already some TSDBs. How doe they cope with reliability and scalability?</span></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p><span style=\"letter-spacing: 0.02px;\">Overall, this project covers both in part a literature study, in which the various products are assessed based on their advertised specifications and should result in a feasibility study with a proposed architecture and a PoC with a selected product set from the literature study.</span></p>');
insert into document (documentID, lang, content) values (default, engels, 'Anomaly detection in a telecommunication system','<p>Newtec (www.newtec.eu) is a company located in Sint-Niklaas that designs, develops and produces technology for satellite communication.</p>\r\n<p><span style=\"letter-spacing: 0.02px;\">One of Newtec\'s biggest products is the Dialog system. It is an integrated system providing bi- directional services over satellite. The system can be split into a HUB system, deployed at a ground station and the various remote terminals, depending on the use case ranging from several modems to some thousands. The HUB part consists of a mix of networking equipment, general purpose servers hosting virtual machines (primarily Linux servers) and specialised Newtec RF equipment (modulators and demodulators). In such a system, lots of data streams are present which give some insight on the operational state of the system</span></p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li><span style=\"letter-spacing: 0.02px;\">logs reporting on the state of systems or specific applications, including error reports</span></li>\r\n<li><span style=\"letter-spacing: 0.02px;\">accounting data reporting on the amount of network data processed by the system</span></li>\r\n<li><span style=\"letter-spacing: 0.02px;\">performance readings of deployed applications, e.g. hawt.io, jmx</span></li>\r\n<li><span style=\"letter-spacing: 0.02px;\">(SNMP) alerts</span></li>\r\n<li><span style=\"letter-spacing: 0.02px;\">system parameters (CPU/memory usage, load, ...)</span></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p><span style=\"letter-spacing: 0.02px;\">A first step in using this data is in collecting and triggering alarms on certain fixed thresholds. However, it would be more interesting to do some more analysis on this data set, allowing you to do anomaly detection on single streams or even detect correlations on multiple streams. With anomaly detection, the dynamic nature of a system can be taken into account in order to detect system events. By correlating lots of information we will be able to better interpret the detected events and decide if an engineer should check out our system or not. The system would be able to more fine grained decide if he would need some human attention or not.</span></p>\r\n<p><span style=\"letter-spacing: 0.02px;\">The goal of this project is to</span></p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li><span style=\"letter-spacing: 0.02px;\">study the available tooling in the field of anomaly detection (like, e.g., skyline from project kale) , its capabilities and applicability into our ecosystem.</span></li>\r\n<li><span style=\"letter-spacing: 0.02px;\">study the applicability of datamining techniques on the specific data set of telecom measurements</span></li>\r\n<li><span style=\"letter-spacing: 0.02px;\">create a PoC of a (selection) tool(s)</span></li>\r\n</ul>');
insert into document (documentID, lang, content) values (default, engels, 'Auditing system to efficiently capture user actions on a system','<p>Newtec (www.newtec.eu) is a company located in Sint-Niklaas that designs, develops and produces technology for satellite communication.</p>\r\n<p><span style=\"letter-spacing: 0.02px;\">One of Newtec\'s biggest products is the Dialog system. It is an integrated system providing bi- directional services over satellite. The system can be split into a HUB system, deployed at a ground station and the various remote terminals, depending on the use case ranging from several modems to some thousands. The HUB part consists of a mix of networking equipment, general purpose servers hosting virtual machines (primarily Linux servers) and specialised Newtec RF equipment (modulators and demodulators). This system is controlled and configured by an NMS (Network Management System) for operational changes and a configuration management system (Puppet) for administrative changes. As such, the system is self contained and should never be manually altered.</span></p>\r\n<p><span style=\"letter-spacing: 0.02px;\">Reality is often different from design and manual interventions in the field are sometimes still needed. However, these are typically not logged in our centralised logging system, as is the case for all automated changes. The purpose of this project is to design and implement an efficient way to capture all command line activities into a centralised logging framework (logstash/elasticsearch). Existing tooling using auditd will need to be evaluated and specific filtering will need to be done in order to only capture relevant data and to efficiently ship it.</span></p>');
insert into document (documentID, lang, content) values (default, engels, 'Resource allocation and network performance in a containerised environment','<p>Newtec (www.newtec.eu) is a company located in Sint-Niklaas that designs, develops and produces technology for satellite communication.</p>\r\n<p><span style=\"letter-spacing: 0.02px;\">One of Newtec\'s biggest products is the Dialog system. It is an integrated system providing bi- directional services over satellite. The system can be split into a HUB system, deployed at a ground station and the various remote terminals, depending on the use case ranging from several modems to some thousands. The HUB part consists of a mix of networking equipment, general purpose servers hosting virtual machines (primarily Linux servers) and specialised Newtec RF equipment (modulators and demodulators).</span></p>\r\n<p>In this project, we like to explore the option of replacing our current KVM-based virtualisation approach with containers, e.g. LXC and/or Docker. These sort of tools are commonplace in modern application deployment stacks, but the focus of this project is on their applicability for telco usage. As a first attempt, we\'d like to stay as close as possible to our current VM-based architecture, which involves running multiple services within a single container. Later on, we might align with the generally recommended \"one service per container\" concept.</p>\r\n<p>The main points we\'d like to see covered include for example:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li><span style=\"letter-spacing: 0.02px;\">Resource allocation: how can we guarantee that some containers receive the needed resources to operate? This includes CPU and memory usage limitations, as well as more strict resource assignments such as CPU pinning, both on the entire container as its content.</span></li>\r\n<li><span style=\"letter-spacing: 0.02px;\">Network interconnects: different containers could co-exist on a single physical server, whereby some but not necessarily all local containers are hosting services for the same customer network. On our virtual machines we restrict VM network access by applying VLAN restrictions, where each VM only runs services for a single customer. How can their traffic be efficiently separated on containers, whilst allowing acceptable packet throughput?</span></li>\r\n<li><span style=\"letter-spacing: 0.02px;\">Realtime behaviour: some of our applications are time-critical, even though calling real-time (typically implies sub-ms scheduling latencies) is an exaggeration: our applications generally provide proper service when they are scheduled to run every ~10ms. Can this sort of constraints be met and/or enforced?</span></li>\r\n<li><span style=\"letter-spacing: 0.02px;\">Network latency: combining the realtime behaviour and the network separation, to provide an overview of the reachable (bridged) packet latencies of traffic being processed on a container running on a physical machine. Currently we are using physical servers with an Intel SR-IOV compatible network card, though DPDK-based software switch solutions may also be evaluated.</span></li>\r\n<li><span style=\"letter-spacing: 0.02px;\">PTP support: some of our time-critical applications are kept in sync with our external Newtec modulator equipment using the precision time protocol (PTP). Normally slaving on this clock source is done in hardware by the network card. Will this work in a containerised environment?</span></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p><span style=\"letter-spacing: 0.02px;\">Overall, this project covers both in part a literature study, in which the various products are assessed based on their advertised specifications and should result in a feasibility study with a proposed architecture and a PoC with a selected product set from the literature study.</span></p>');
insert into document (documentID, lang, content) values (default, engels, 'IO performance comparison of various optimisation options on a specific Hardware set','<p>Newtec (www.newtec.eu) is a company located in Sint-Niklaas that designs, develops and produces technology for satellite communication.</p>\r\n<p><span style=\"letter-spacing: 0.02px;\">One of Newtec\'s biggest products is the Dialog system. It is an integrated system providing bi- directional IP services over satellite. The system can be split into a HUB system, deployed at a ground station and the various remote terminals, depending on the use case ranging from several modems to some thousands. The HUB part consists of a mix of networking equipment, general purpose servers hosting virtual machines (primarily Linux servers) and specialised Newtec RF equipment (modulators and demodulators).</span></p>\r\n<p>IP data from the customer is processed by the virtual machines on the servers before it is sent over satellite. The same is true for IP data received over satellite. This is processed before it is sent to the customer. There are several possible strategies when it comes to networking virtual machines in a Linux environment and many performance tuning options. Most of the studies focus on raw throughput in terms of bitrate or packet rate. They report on how many bytes/packets were successfully processed, but they don\'t mention the lost packets. Few studies focus on error free performance results.</p>\r\n<p>This project will study the performance of error free network packet forwarding on Linux virtual machines which includes</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li><span style=\"letter-spacing: 0.02px;\">Literature study of available approaches for high performance networking of Kernel-based Virtual Machines (KVM) on Linux.</span></li>\r\n<li><span style=\"letter-spacing: 0.02px;\">Literature study of similar performance tests and their published test results.</span></li>\r\n<li><span style=\"letter-spacing: 0.02px;\">Implement and tune a solution for high performance VM networking. More than one solution can&nbsp;</span><span style=\"letter-spacing: 0.02px;\">be implemented to compare the performance characteristics.</span></li>\r\n<li><span style=\"letter-spacing: 0.02px;\">Test and report the error free network performance of the implemented solution.</span></li>\r\n</ul>');
insert into document (documentID, lang, content) values (default, engels, 'Realtime behaviour in a virtualised environment','<p>Newtec (www.newtec.eu) is a company located in Sint-Niklaas that designs, develops and produces technology for satellite communication.</p>\r\n<p><span style=\"letter-spacing: 0.02px;\">One of Newtec\'s biggest products is the Dialog system. It is an integrated system providing bi- directional IP services over satellite. The system can be split into a HUB system, deployed at a ground station and the various remote terminals, depending on the use case ranging from several modems to some thousands. The HUB part consists of a mix of networking equipment, general purpose servers hosting virtual machines (primarily Linux servers) and specialised Newtec RF equipment (modulators and demodulators).</span></p>\r\n<p><span style=\"letter-spacing: 0.02px;\">Some of the virtualised functions contribute to control plane activities (over satellite) and need to comply to strict timing requirements. Although virtualisation is becoming commonplace on application deployments, the realtime behaviour is most of the time not such a big requirement. The time allowed to handle a web request is important, but not mission critical. Our control plane services on the other hand do require a very strict timing.</span></p>\r\n<p><span style=\"letter-spacing: 0.02px;\">Realtime extension exist for both the linux kernel as the KVM hypervisor. The goal of this project is to study the available patches/settings, compare reference architectures (like e.g., Intel\'s Open Network Platform server) and create a PoC where the performance impact of the proposed changes is evaluated.</span></p>\r\n<p><span style=\"letter-spacing: 0.02px;\">Baseline: How to enforce realtime behaviour for (control plane) applications when using VMs for service deployment?</span></p>');
insert into document (documentID, lang, content) values (default, engels, 'Lightweight network tester','<p>Newtec (www.newtec.eu) is a company located in Sint-Niklaas that designs, develops and produces technology for satellite communication.</p>\r\n<p><span style=\"letter-spacing: 0.02px;\">One of Newtec\'s biggest products is the Dialog system. It is an integrated system providing bi- directional IP services over satellite. The system can be split into a HUB system, deployed at a ground station and the various remote terminals, depending on the use case ranging from several modems to some thousands. Dialog includes optimizations for different traffic types e.g. VoIP, UDP, TCP and HTTP. Each of these will stress the performance in a different way.</span></p>\r\n<p>To test Dialog in terms of network data performance, hundreds to thousands of terminals are simulated on general purpose X86 servers. Traffic needs to be generated for each simulated terminal. This can be done using tools like iperf and wget, but these tools can only send traffic for a single terminal. Which means one instance is needed for each simulated terminal. With several hundred simulated terminals on one server, this means several hundred traffic generators. This becomes a burden both to manage and for the server performance. In this project you will develop a new traffic generation tool or enhance an existing tool to support many simulated terminals in an efficient way.</p>\r\n<p>The project consists of</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li><span style=\"letter-spacing: 0.02px;\">A study of available open source tools to test network performance</span></li>\r\n<li><span style=\"letter-spacing: 0.02px;\">The development of a new tool or the enhancement of an existing tool to</span></li>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li><span style=\"letter-spacing: 0.02px;\">Support traffic generation for many simulated terminals. Each terminal will have its own IP address and traffic to and from this IP will be handled by the simulated terminal.</span></li>\r\n<li><span style=\"letter-spacing: 0.02px;\">Support smooth generation of the requested traffic pattern for each terminal. A 50 packet per second VoIP stream or a 800 packet per second video stream should be possible on hundreds of simulated terminals distributing the packets evenly in time. TCP streams should be able to send a combination of small and large packets (imix distribution).</span></li>\r\n<li><span style=\"letter-spacing: 0.02px;\">Scale from one to several hundred simulated terminals on a single server o Produce statistics like bitrate, packet rate, packet loss, delay, jitter.</span></li>\r\n<li><span style=\"letter-spacing: 0.02px;\">Provide an easy interface to configure the requested traffic profile.</span></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n</ul>');
insert into document (documentID, lang, content) values (default, engels, 'Energy consumption modeling in OpenWSN: An open source protocol stack for the Internet of Things ','<p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span style=\"text-align: justify; letter-spacing: 0.02px;\">The Internet-of-Things revolution is based upon the premise of having a plethora of everyday devices being online and sharing information over the Internet. Many of those devices are sensors, such as temperature sensors, humidity sensors, gyroscopes or cameras. These sensors generate huge datasets that can be used to improve our knowledge of the environment and the environment itself.<br /></span><span style=\"letter-spacing: 0.02px; text-align: justify;\"><br />However, one of the biggest challenges of these sensors is their energy-efficiency: you do not want to be the person that has to replace the batteries of hundreds of sensors every week. A state of the art sensor device, running on a simple AA battery, can run for many years using extremely optimized wireless communications protocols.<br /></span><span style=\"letter-spacing: 0.02px; text-align: justify;\"><br />One such widely used protocol is IEEE802.15.4e, which is implemented in the OpenWSN project. It contains both firmware for real hardware (e.g., OpenMote) as well as a network simulator. Many people conducting research into Internet-of-Things are using the OpenWSN software to evaluate their research. Ironically, at this moment the OpenWSN simulator does not support any energy consumption models. The goal of this internship is to implement the energy consumption model proposed in [1] in the OpenWSN project. This would allow researchers to evaluate the energy efficiency of their work in the OpenWSN simulator.<br /><br /></span><span style=\"letter-spacing: 0.02px; text-align: justify;\">In this internship, you will be programming in Python and C directly into the MAC layer of the IEEE802.15.4e protocol stack. You will have the opportunity to implement the energy model into the simulator and also validate your results and perform measurements with real OpenMote hardware. The ultimate goal is to integrate your code into an official OpenWSN release, allowing you to contribute to a widely used piece of open source software.<br /></span><span style=\"text-align: justify; letter-spacing: 0.02px;\"><br />[1] Vilajosana, Xavier, et al. \"A realistic energy consumption model for TSCH networks.\"&nbsp;</span><em style=\"text-align: justify; letter-spacing: 0.02px;\">Sensors Journal, IEEE</em><span style=\"text-align: justify; letter-spacing: 0.02px;\">&nbsp;14.2 (2014): 482-489.</span></p>\r\n<p class=\"MsoNormal\">&nbsp;</p>');
insert into document (documentID, lang, content) values (default, engels, 'Software security engineering for financial institutions','<p>Are you obsessed with finding security problems? Are you interested in helping out big financial institutions getting their software bug free? Our solution provides software developers with the right information at the right time to avoid making security mistakes in the first place.</p>\r\n<p>Sensei Security is a stealth-mode software security startup out of Belgium. Sensei Security provides solutions to help software developers build secure software. We are currently working on our minimal viable product which is tested by our beta-customers which consist of large Belgian and US based financial institutions.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>Our ideal candidate is passionate about security and has decent programming skills. Someone who is eager to learn how software security is done for real at companies facing threats on a day-to-day basis.</p>\r\n<h2>What you will learn:</h2>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li><span style=\"letter-spacing: 0.02px;\">Which security problems financial institutions face today.</span></li>\r\n<li><span style=\"letter-spacing: 0.02px;\">Create solutions to technical security problems.&nbsp;</span></li>\r\n<li><span style=\"letter-spacing: 0.02px;\">Learn how to transform your manual process into an automated one so it scales for larger projects.</span></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<h2>What we require:</h2>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li><span style=\"letter-spacing: 0.02px;\">Ability to deal with confidential and sensitive information</span></li>\r\n<li><span style=\"letter-spacing: 0.02px;\">Good verbal and written English communication skills</span></li>\r\n<li><span style=\"letter-spacing: 0.02px;\">Good hands-on experience with Java and XML</span></li>\r\n<li><span style=\"letter-spacing: 0.02px;\">Software security knowledge like OWASP top 10.</span></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p>We value all of our interns and go the extra mile to make sure you receive a learning experience that fits your career goals. &nbsp;You will become extremely knowledgeable in finding security problems in code, developing Java applications, and solving software security problems.</p>\r\n<div>\r\n<h2>Details</h2>\r\n<div>The internship can be performed between June 15 and December 31, 2016. If you live within 50km from Bruges, you are expected to travel to Bruges (office is easily accessible when coming by train). People living further away are handled on a case-by-case basis (remote work).&nbsp;</div>\r\n</div>');
insert into document (documentID, lang, content) values (default, engels, 'Power management Implementation in NS-3 for Wi-Fi HaLow dense IoT networks','<p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span lang=\"EN-GB\">The Internet of Things (IoT) consists of millions of power constrained devices addressable over the Internet. However, existing low power wireless network technologies either are incapable of long range transmission (e.g., ZigBee, Bluetooth Low Energy) or support limited throughput (e.g., LoRaWAN, Sigfox, DASH-7). Aiming to address this gap, the new IEEE 802.11ah standard, marketed as Wi-Fi HaLow, was finished in early 2017 supporting connectivity among many power-constrained stations deployed over a wide area. HaLow supports up to 8000 nodes connected to a single access point, operates in the unlicensed sub-1Ghz frequency bands, and provides communications over distances up to 1 km, while maintaining a data rate of over 150 Kbps, offering a greater reach and high throughput for battery-powered sensors.</span></p>\r\n<p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span style=\"letter-spacing: 0.02px;\">Since HaLow is a quite new wireless technology, companies are still working on the implementation of the hardware and currently doing research based on network simulation to decide the best hardware-design choices. Our group is the first to have implemented HaLow in simulation and make it available as open source for other researchers to experiment with </span><a style=\"letter-spacing: 0.02px;\" href=\"https://github.com/MOSAIC-UA/802.11ah-ns3\">https://github.com/MOSAIC-UA/802.11ah-ns3</a><span class=\"MsoHyperlink\" style=\"letter-spacing: 0.02px;\">.</span><span style=\"letter-spacing: 0.02px;\"> However, there&rsquo;re still some important features related to power management pending to be finished. For example, IEEE 802.11ah introduces the TIM (traffic indication map) segmentation mechanism to split information transmitted in the TIM into several segments and transmit them separately. It allows stations to sleep much longer, which is of critical importance in low-power IoT applications.</span></p>\r\n<p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span style=\"letter-spacing: 0.02px;\">The goal of this project is to implement power management features of HaLow in the ns-3 network simulator (</span><a style=\"letter-spacing: 0.02px;\" href=\"https://www.nsnam.org/)\">https://www.nsnam.org/)</a><span style=\"letter-spacing: 0.02px;\">, and make it publicly available to researchers worldwide. </span><span style=\"letter-spacing: 0.02px;\">Some research and a scientific paper could also be possible based on your implementation. </span><span style=\"letter-spacing: 0.02px;\">This project will give you the opportunity to work with a radically new wireless technology, and gain in-depth knowledge about the inner-workings of Wi-Fi protocols.</span></p>');
insert into document (documentID, lang, content) values (default, engels, 'Analysis, diagnosis and monitoring of 6LoWPAN networks','<p style=\"margin-bottom: 0cm; line-height: 100%;\">Since the paradigm of the Internet of things (IoT) was set, an infinite number of new possibilities have been shown for connecting small and embedded devices with the Internet. As the IoT vision is starting to become reality, new technologies are appearing that fulfil the requirements of these applications. The networks that support them vary from long-range low-power networks (few kilobits per second but kilometre range) to high-throughput low-latency personal area networks (megabits up to gigabits per second but only a few meters of range).</p>\r\n<p style=\"margin-bottom: 0cm; line-height: 100%;\">Some of the most relevant IoT applications are Industrial Automation, Building Automation or Smart Grid Applications and due to their contexts they mainly have three requirements:</p>\r\n<p style=\"margin-bottom: 0cm; line-height: 100%;\">- High reliability and deterministic performance</p>\r\n<p style=\"margin-bottom: 0cm; line-height: 100%;\">- Low power consumption</p>\r\n<p style=\"margin-bottom: 0cm; line-height: 100%;\">- High scalability</p>\r\n<p style=\"margin-bottom: 0cm; line-height: 100%;\">One of the most promising technologies that accomplishes these three requirements is 6TiSCH, an open source IPv6-enabled stack on top of the standard IEEE 802.15.4e standard, which focuses on low-rate low-power wireless personal area networks. It is based on TSCH, a channel hopping mode of IEEE 802.15.4e that is highly robust to external interferences and multi-path fading, two of the more serious problems in LR-WPANs. [1]</p>\r\n<p style=\"margin-bottom: 0cm; line-height: 100%;\">It can be foreseen that this kind of networks will be deployed in a high number in the future, specially in urban areas. Thus, it is relevant to have a strict control of them, in terms of physical location, security, topology and interference. In order to perform critical tasks such as network management and monitoring, specific tools exist to audit and analyse. However most of this tools do not provide complete information about topology, resource allocation, scheduling or have a decent packet tracing.</p>\r\n<p style=\"margin-bottom: 0cm; line-height: 100%;\">This internship proposes to directly dive into the IoT by learning the in and outs of one of the most promising technologies, 6TiSCH. Specifically, you will work implementing tools in Python and C for building wireless networks, getting involved in gathering information from the network, process and analyse it and then displaying the most relevant data. This means you will have the opportunity to work along a whole IoT stack, starting from the physical layer configuring hardware, the MAC layer and security layers sniffing packets in different channels and time slots, IPv6 layer through RPL, and finally in the application layer using the graphic interface QT.</p>\r\n<p style=\"margin-bottom: 0cm; line-height: 100%;\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p style=\"margin-bottom: 0cm; line-height: 100%;\">[1] - 6TiSCH: Deterministic IP-enabled Industrial Internet (of Things). Diego Dujovne, Thomas Watteyne, Xavier Vilajosana, Pascal Thubert. IEEE Communications Magazine, Communications Standards Supplement, to appear.</p>');
insert into document (documentID, lang, content) values (default, engels, 'using machine learning Techniques For Proactive Network Management','<h2 class=\"SLCShortDocTitle\"><span style=\"color: #9d1447; font-family: garamond, georgia, serif; font-size: 36px; font-weight: bold; line-height: 46px; letter-spacing: 0.02px;\">1<span style=\"font-weight: normal; font-stretch: normal; font-size: 7pt; line-height: normal; font-family: \'Times New Roman\';\">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; </span></span><span style=\"color: #9d1447; font-family: garamond, georgia, serif; font-size: 36px; font-weight: bold; line-height: 46px; letter-spacing: 0.02px;\">Problem Description</span></h2>\r\n<p style=\"mso-list: l0 level1 lfo1;\"><span style=\"font-family: SegoeUI; line-height: normal; color: #000000; font-size: 12px; letter-spacing: 0.02px;\">Telecom operators are confronted with an ever more demanding customer, requiring continuous broadcast and data services, with an impeccable quality of service. DataMiner, awarded as best network management solution, is the core operational platform of many leading companies. Networks of Telenet, Proximus, Aljazeera, Eutelsat, AT&amp;T and even the ISS are managed with DataMiner. This thesis fits within the context of a far-reaching automation system for the future DataMiner. Pattern recognition is currently a manual and tedious task. For instance, detecting certain patterns in a spectrum trace such as ingress or laser clipping is currently a reactive task performed by the operator watching a spectrum analyzer.</span></p>\r\n&nbsp;\r\n<h1 style=\"mso-list: l0 level1 lfo1;\"><!--[if !supportLists]--><span style=\"mso-fareast-font-family: \'Segoe UI\'; mso-bidi-font-family: \'Segoe UI\';\"><span style=\"mso-list: Ignore;\">2<span style=\"font: 7.0pt \'Times New Roman\';\">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; </span></span></span><!--[endif]-->Subject and Approach</h1>\r\n<p class=\"MsoNormal\" style=\"margin-bottom: .0001pt; line-height: normal; mso-layout-grid-align: none; text-autospace: none;\"><span style=\"font-family: SegoeUI; mso-bidi-font-family: SegoeUI; mso-ansi-language: EN-US;\">In order to advance a proactive network management, this thesis consists of mainly two parts: a) the extraction of interesting patterns that may help in identifying issues in the network, and b) an efficient and high-performance detection system to process thousands of traces in real-time. Therefore appropriate machine learning techniques to automatically extract and detect interesting patterns in real-time streams, are evaluated and matched with the requirements. The most promising technique(s) will be used to build a proof-of-concept application demonstrating its value for the tasks at hand.</span></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p class=\"SLCBodytext\">&nbsp;</p>');
insert into document (documentID, lang, content) values (default, engels, 'Building Expert system for SIzing servers to fit an estimated load','<p class=\"SLCShortDocTitle\"><span style=\"color: #9d1447; font-family: garamond, georgia, serif; font-size: 36px; font-weight: bold; line-height: 46px; letter-spacing: 0.02px;\">1<span style=\"font-weight: normal; font-stretch: normal; font-size: 7pt; line-height: normal; font-family: \'Times New Roman\';\">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; </span></span><span style=\"color: #9d1447; font-family: garamond, georgia, serif; font-size: 36px; font-weight: bold; line-height: 46px; letter-spacing: 0.02px;\">Problem Description</span></p>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-family: SegoeUI; letter-spacing: 0.02px; line-height: normal;\">Skyline Communications is the global leader in end-to-end multi-vendor network management and OSS solutions for the satellite, broadcast, IPTV and HFC broadband industries. The DataMiner network management platform enables end-to-end integration of the most complex technical ecosystems and has been deployed by leading operators around the world. With ever growing networks and an ever growing amount of managed elements in these networks, the DataMiner software is constantly facing more challenging tasks. Ensuring the requested performance of the network management system requires the hardware in the different DataMiner servers (called DataMiner Agents) to be in line with the responsibilities of the software. A better up-front estimation of the hardware requirements will lead to a more cost-efficient deployment of the network management system.</span></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<h1 style=\"mso-list: l1 level1 lfo1;\"><!--[if !supportLists]--><span style=\"mso-fareast-font-family: \'Segoe UI\'; mso-bidi-font-family: \'Segoe UI\';\"><span style=\"mso-list: Ignore;\">2<span style=\"font: 7.0pt \'Times New Roman\';\">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; </span></span></span><!--[endif]-->Subject and Approach</h1>\r\n<p class=\"MsoNormal\" style=\"margin-bottom: .0001pt; line-height: normal; mso-layout-grid-align: none; text-autospace: none;\"><span style=\"font-family: SegoeUI; mso-bidi-font-family: SegoeUI; mso-ansi-language: EN-US;\">The expert system will allow to find a good estimation with as little information as possible and allow to gradually refine this estimation by asking the right questions. The work in this thesis consists of the following parts:</span></p>\r\n<p class=\"MsoListParagraphCxSpFirst\" style=\"margin-bottom: .0001pt; mso-add-space: auto; text-indent: -18.0pt; line-height: normal; mso-list: l0 level1 lfo2; mso-layout-grid-align: none; text-autospace: none;\"><!--[if !supportLists]--><span style=\"font-family: SegoeUI; mso-hansi-font-family: Calibri; mso-hansi-theme-font: minor-latin; mso-bidi-font-family: SegoeUI;\"><span style=\"mso-list: Ignore;\">-<span style=\"font: 7.0pt \'Times New Roman\';\">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; </span></span></span><!--[endif]--><span style=\"font-family: SegoeUI; mso-bidi-font-family: SegoeUI;\">Extract and structure the performance dataset on which the expert system will be based. There is an automated performance test setup available.</span></p>\r\n<p class=\"MsoListParagraphCxSpMiddle\" style=\"margin-bottom: .0001pt; mso-add-space: auto; text-indent: -18.0pt; line-height: normal; mso-list: l0 level1 lfo2; mso-layout-grid-align: none; text-autospace: none;\"><!--[if !supportLists]--><span style=\"font-family: SegoeUI; mso-hansi-font-family: Calibri; mso-hansi-theme-font: minor-latin; mso-bidi-font-family: SegoeUI;\"><span style=\"mso-list: Ignore;\">-<span style=\"font: 7.0pt \'Times New Roman\';\">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; </span></span></span><!--[endif]--><span style=\"font-family: SegoeUI; mso-bidi-font-family: SegoeUI;\">Deduce estimation rules and questions based on this performance dataset, using concepts and tools from machine learning and datamining. </span></p>\r\n<p class=\"MsoListParagraphCxSpLast\" style=\"margin-bottom: .0001pt; mso-add-space: auto; text-indent: -18.0pt; line-height: normal; mso-list: l0 level1 lfo2; mso-layout-grid-align: none; text-autospace: none;\"><!--[if !supportLists]--><span style=\"font-family: SegoeUI; mso-hansi-font-family: Calibri; mso-hansi-theme-font: minor-latin; mso-bidi-font-family: SegoeUI;\"><span style=\"mso-list: Ignore;\">-<span style=\"font: 7.0pt \'Times New Roman\';\">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; </span></span></span><!--[endif]--><span style=\"font-family: SegoeUI; mso-bidi-font-family: SegoeUI;\">Construct a proof-of-concept expert system capable of determining the requirements on a DataMiner Agent and benchmark this to a real DataMiner Agent. There are several virtual machines available for this benchmarking test. </span></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p class=\"MsoNormal\" style=\"margin-bottom: .0001pt; line-height: normal; mso-layout-grid-align: none; text-autospace: none;\"><span style=\"mso-ansi-language: EN-US;\">&nbsp;</span></p>');
insert into document (documentID, lang, content) values (default, engels, 'Load-balancing in high density large-scale Wi- Fi environments','<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<div class=\"page\" title=\"Page 1\">\r\n<div class=\"layoutArea\">\r\n<div class=\"column\">\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size: 10.000000pt; font-family: \'CMR10\';\">With today&rsquo;s popularity of wireless networks, they are being deployed every- where. This can be at home, at public spaces like in a city, or on special events like festivals or conferences where dozens up to hundreds of access points are being deployed. While it works at home pretty well, in dense environments it can lead to problems as some access points will be overloaded and can not pro- vide service any more. To prevent this from happening, the clients need to be distributed in a transparent way, because in Wi-Fi, the client takes the decision to which access point to connect to.</span></p>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size: 10.000000pt; font-family: \'CMR10\';\">In this project you will be working with a framework that allows transparent management of clients. In this framework you will implement a load-balancing algorithm and test it empirically, as well as improve it. This will lead to better performance of Wi-Fi in dense environments and improve the user experience.&nbsp;</span></p>\r\n</div>\r\n</div>\r\n</div>');
insert into document (documentID, lang, content) values (default, engels, 'Distributed SDN based controller for client management in Wi-Fi','<div class=\"page\" title=\"Page 1\">\r\n<div class=\"layoutArea\">\r\n<div class=\"column\">\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size: 10.000000pt; font-family: \'CMR10\';\">We can see Wi-Fi deployments getting bigger and bigger. Those deployments intend to provide internet to a large number of users in a rather small area, resulting in a dense environment of wireless devices. While interference is a large issue in these situations, another one is management of the clients. Frameworks were presented to handle the management of the clients in a transparent fashion. An SDN based controller manages everything, but this controller is also the bottleneck. To make this deployment more flexible the controller has to be&nbsp;</span><span style=\"font-family: CMR10; font-size: 10pt; letter-spacing: 0.02px;\">distributed to avoid too long delays in responses and achieve a faster response time.</span></p>\r\n</div>\r\n</div>\r\n</div>\r\n<div class=\"page\" title=\"Page 2\">\r\n<div class=\"layoutArea\">\r\n<div class=\"column\">\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size: 10.000000pt; font-family: \'CMR10\';\">In this project you will work with and extend an existing framework for transparent client management. The controller will be distributed and will have several instances. Those instances handle a zone by themselves, but will also communicate with among each other to allow clients to move from one zone to the other. With the distribution, we can achieve faster responses and also higher reliability of the controllers.&nbsp;</span></p>\r\n</div>\r\n</div>\r\n</div>');
insert into document (documentID, lang, content) values (default, engels, 'Visualisation of client behaviour in managed Wi-Fi network','<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<div class=\"page\" title=\"Page 2\">\r\n<div class=\"layoutArea\">\r\n<div class=\"column\">\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size: 10.000000pt; font-family: \'CMR10\';\">With the popularity of wireless networks and the ubiquitous availability, espe- cially in dense environments, management of clients became necessary. Frame- works are available that can handle it transparently. To observe what is ongoing, a visualisation is necessary. This is not only important for observation, but also to find out undesired behaviour of an algorithm. </span></p>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size: 10.000000pt; font-family: \'CMR10\';\">In this project you will implement a GUI for an existing management frame- work. The GUI will include information such as client movement, traffic per client and overall traffic for an access point.&nbsp;</span></p>\r\n</div>\r\n</div>\r\n</div>');
insert into document (documentID, lang, content) values (default, engels, 'Evaluating coordinated coexistence and access management for sub Ghz protocols','<p class=\"MsoNormal\" style=\"margin-top: 24.0pt; margin-right: 0cm; margin-bottom: 6.0pt; margin-left: 0cm; line-height: normal; mso-pagination: widow-orphan lines-together; page-break-after: avoid; mso-outline-level: 1;\"><span style=\"line-height: 24px; text-align: justify; letter-spacing: 0.02px;\">The Sub-1GHz ISM band has two important strengths. Firstly, it has a better range than 2.4 GHz with the same output power and current consumption. Secondly, compared to 2.4 GHz, lower frequencies have better penetration through steel and concrete.&nbsp;</span><span style=\"text-align: justify; letter-spacing: 0.02px;\">Nowadays, many low power network technologies such as Dash 7, SigFox, LoRaWAN, IEEE 802.11ah and LTE Cat-M are commonly used within sub-1GHz ISM bands.</span></p>\r\n<p class=\"MsoNormal\" style=\"text-align: justify; page-break-after: avoid;\">In sub-1GHz ISM bands, a number of potential overlaying wireless networks can be established because (i) the sub-1GHz narrow-bands (e.g., 1 MHz) allow a number (e.g., 26 of 1 MHz) of non-overlapping channels. And (ii) the sub-1GHz certified duty-cycle (duty cycle restrictions in some regions &lt;1%/h) that limits a wireless device to use actively the wireless media for data transmission. However, similar to the coexistence problems of WLAN and WPAN devices in the 2.4 GHz ISM radio-band, identical coexistence symptoms are still found in the sub-1GHz band between these overlaying wireless networks.</p>\r\n<p class=\"MsoCaption\" style=\"text-align: left;\" align=\"center\"><span style=\"letter-spacing: 0.02px; text-align: justify;\">The main goal of the project is to study the implementation of coordinated coexistence mechanisms for sub Ghz protocols.&nbsp;</span><span style=\"letter-spacing: 0.02px; text-align: justify;\">The coordinated coexistence should support two models by assuming (1) that the edge router doesn\'t have the information about traffic/load of those networks. Or by assuming (2) that the edge router is informed about the possible traffic of each network.</span></p>\r\n<p class=\"MsoNormal\" style=\"text-align: justify;\">&nbsp;</p>');
insert into document (documentID, lang, content) values (default, engels, 'Distributed clock synchronization for ultra-low power wireless sensor networks','<p class=\"MsoNormal\"><strong><span style=\"line-height: normal;\">Brief project overview</span></strong></p>\r\n<p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span style=\"line-height: normal;\">IMEC- Holst center is currently rolling out a Wireless Sensor Network (WSN) within the IoT framework, capable of measuring air-quality of the environment and communicating this information to a consumer accessible cloud. &nbsp;Time synchronization is one of the fundamental challenges in such a WSN and all the independent clocks aboard these sensor nodes must be aligned to maintain coherent communication and data collection. Given two-way communication between the nodes, distributed clock synchronization algorithm(s) must be developed, which not only accurately synchronize the nodes, but also be a reliable and energy-efficient solution.</span></p>\r\n<p class=\"MsoNormal\"><strong><span style=\"line-height: normal;\">Tasks</span></strong></p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li><span style=\"line-height: normal; letter-spacing: 0.02px;\">&middot; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;Literature survey on the current state of the art for clock synchronization</span></li>\r\n<li><span style=\"line-height: normal; letter-spacing: 0.02px;\">&middot; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;Developing algorithm(s) for distributed clock synchronization</span></li>\r\n<li><span style=\"line-height: normal; letter-spacing: 0.02px;\">&middot; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;Simulations to validate the proposed algorithm(s)</span></li>\r\n<li><span style=\"line-height: normal; letter-spacing: 0.02px;\">&middot; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;(Option) Implementing the solution(s) on the IMEC IoT sensor network</span></li>\r\n<li><span style=\"line-height: normal; letter-spacing: 0.02px;\">&middot; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;(Option) Testing and analyzing the performance of the implemented algorithm</span></li>\r\n</ul>');
insert into document (documentID, lang, content) values (default, engels, 'Implementation, evaluation and comparison of LoRaWAN transmission modes','<p><span style=\"font-size: x-small;\">LoRaWAN&trade; is a Low Power Wide Area Network (LPWAN) specification intended for wireless battery operated Things in regional, national or global network. LoRaWAN target key requirements of internet of things such as secure bi-directional communication, mobility and localization services. This standard will provide seamless interoperability among smart Things without the need of complex local installations and gives back the freedom to the user, developer, businesses enabling the roll out of Internet of Things.</span></p>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size: x-small;\">Communication between end-devices and gateways is spread out on different frequency channels and data rates. The selection of the data rate is a trade-off between communication range and message duration. Due to the spread spectrum technology, communications with different data rates do not interfere with each other and create a set of \"virtual\" channels increasing the capacity of the gateway. LoRaWAN data rates range from 0.3 kbps to 50 kbps. To maximize both battery life of the end-devices and overall network capacity, the LoRaWAN network server is managing the data rate and RF output for each end-device individually by means of an adaptive data rate (ADR) scheme.</span></p>\r\n<div>\r\n<div><span style=\"font-size: x-small;\">LoRaWAN has several different classes of end-point devices to address the different needs reflected in the wide range of applications:</span></div>\r\n<div>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li><span style=\"letter-spacing: 0.02px; font-size: x-small;\"><strong>Bi-directional end-devices (Class A):</strong> End-devices of Class A allow for bi-directional communications whereby each end-device\'s uplink transmission is followed by two short downlink receive windows. The transmission slot scheduled by the end-device is based on its own communication needs with a small variation based on a random time basis (ALOHA-type of protocol). This Class A operation is the lowest power end-device system for applications that only require downlink communication from the server shortly after the end-device has sent an uplink transmission. Downlink communications from the server at any other time will have to wait until the next scheduled uplink.</span></li>\r\n<li><span style=\"letter-spacing: 0.02px; font-size: x-small;\"><strong>Bi-directional end-devices with scheduled receive slots (Class B):</strong> In addition to the Class A random receive windows, Class B devices open extra receive windows at scheduled times. In order for the End-device to open its receive window at the scheduled time it receives a time synchronized Beacon from the gateway. This allows the server to know when the end-device is listening.</span></li>\r\n<li><span style=\"letter-spacing: 0.02px; font-size: x-small;\"><strong>Bi-directional end-devices with maximal receive slots (Class C):</strong> End-devices of Class C have nearly continuously open receive windows, only closed when transmitting.</span></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<div><span style=\"font-size: x-small;\"><img style=\"vertical-align: text-top;\" src=\"https://www.lora-alliance.org/portals/0/images/whatis/networkBW.png\" alt=\"\" width=\"520\" height=\"250\" /></span></div>\r\n<div><span style=\"font-size: x-small;\"><span style=\"letter-spacing: 0.02px;\">The goal of this internship is to implement the modes B and C (which are currently not implemented in existing open source LoRaWAN software), as well as evaluate and compare the three modes. An exact quantitative evaluation and comparison of these modes in terms of energy-efficiency, latency, throughput and complexity currently does not exist. This internship consists of three concrete steps:</span></span></div>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li><span style=\"letter-spacing: 0.02px; font-size: x-small;\">Deploy an existing open source LoRaWAN stack on sensor and gateway hardware (e.g., <a href=\"https://github.com/Lora-net\">https://github.com/Lora-net</a>).</span></li>\r\n<li><span style=\"letter-spacing: 0.02px; font-size: x-small;\">Extend the implementation to support transmission modes B and mode C.</span></li>\r\n<li><span style=\"letter-spacing: 0.02px; font-size: x-small;\">Quantitatively compare the three modes in terms of latency, energy efficiency and throughput for both upstream and downstream traffic.</span></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<span style=\"font-size: x-small;\">This internship is a collaboration with Nokia and the work will in part be performed at the Nokia premisses in Antwerp.</span></div>\r\n</div>');
insert into document (documentID, lang, content) values (default, engels, 'Individu-gebaseerd model voor de verspreiding van griep en mazelen in Vlaanderen');
insert into document (documentID, lang, content) values (default, engels, 'Duplicate detection in business term descriptions','<h1><span lang=\"NL-BE\">Duplicate detection in business term descriptions</span></h1>\r\n<p><span lang=\"NL-BE\">Project in collaboration with the company Collibra</span></p>\r\n<p class=\"MsoNormal\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span lang=\"EN-US\">Many companies create an internal glossary to formalize their business terminology as part of their Data Governance efforts. When multiple people &amp; departments work on this together, there is a big risk of duplication.</span><span style=\"letter-spacing: 0.02px;\">&nbsp;</span></p>\r\n<p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span lang=\"EN-US\">In this master thesis/research internship you will have to experiment with different methods and algorithms to efficiently detect duplicates/similarities in a set of business terms and their description.</span><span style=\"letter-spacing: 0.02px;\">&nbsp;</span></p>\r\n<p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span lang=\"EN-US\">With this you will need to investigate, evaluate and possibly combine a wide variety of techniques:</span></p>\r\n<p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span lang=\"EN-US\">&nbsp;</span><span style=\"text-indent: -0.25in; letter-spacing: 0.02px; font-family: Symbol;\" lang=\"EN-US\">&middot;<span style=\"font-stretch: normal; font-size: 7pt; line-height: normal; font-family: \'Times New Roman\';\">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; </span></span><span style=\"text-indent: -0.25in; letter-spacing: 0.02px;\" lang=\"EN-US\">Machine learning</span></p>\r\n<p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span style=\"text-indent: -0.25in; letter-spacing: 0.02px; font-family: Symbol;\" lang=\"EN-US\">&middot;<span style=\"font-stretch: normal; font-size: 7pt; line-height: normal; font-family: \'Times New Roman\';\">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; </span></span><span style=\"text-indent: -0.25in; letter-spacing: 0.02px;\" lang=\"EN-US\">Natural Language Processing and linguistic algorithms (like stemming)</span></p>\r\n<p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span style=\"text-indent: -0.25in; letter-spacing: 0.02px; font-family: Symbol;\" lang=\"EN-US\">&middot;<span style=\"font-stretch: normal; font-size: 7pt; line-height: normal; font-family: \'Times New Roman\';\">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; </span></span><span style=\"text-indent: -0.25in; letter-spacing: 0.02px;\" lang=\"EN-US\">String distance algorithms (like Levenshtein)</span></p>\r\n<p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span style=\"text-indent: -0.25in; letter-spacing: 0.02px; font-family: Symbol;\" lang=\"EN-US\">&middot;<span style=\"font-stretch: normal; font-size: 7pt; line-height: normal; font-family: \'Times New Roman\';\">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; </span></span><span style=\"text-indent: -0.25in; letter-spacing: 0.02px;\" lang=\"EN-US\">Considering common synonyms, abbreviations, &hellip;</span></p>\r\n<p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span style=\"text-indent: -0.25in; letter-spacing: 0.02px; font-family: Symbol;\" lang=\"EN-US\">&middot;<span style=\"font-stretch: normal; font-size: 7pt; line-height: normal; font-family: \'Times New Roman\';\">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; </span></span><span style=\"text-indent: -0.25in; letter-spacing: 0.02px;\" lang=\"EN-US\">&hellip;</span></p>\r\n<p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span style=\"letter-spacing: 0.02px;\">This project can, if desired, also accommodate 2 students.</span></p>');
insert into document (documentID, lang, content) values (default, engels, 'Reducing bug handling overhead via machine learning [industrial partner]','<h3>Context</h3>\r\n<p>Handling bugs in production code is considered an expensive process. Various reasons can be attributed to this like the erosion of knowledge, little room for changes, &hellip; although these reasons are fundamentally hard it should be possible to provide more guidance to a developer. Comparable to book suggestions on Amazon, a system could for example propose good candidates to look at the problem or even likely starting points for debugging. This way the cost of bug fixing is further reduced.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<h3>Goal &amp; Research Questions:</h3>\r\n<p>The goal of this thesis is to build a prototype to evaluate the effect of a suggestion system at OM Partners. Three types of suggestions, with increasing difficulty are considered for this thesis. Ideally all three of them are covered but depth and complexity might reduce the scope. The evaluation will be done in close collaboration with the company.</p>\r\n<p>The first guidance is the detection of likely duplicates. End-users are typically unaware of similar bugs or not capable of detecting similar bug reports. By inspecting the bug logger&rsquo;s information the bug tracker can propose to merge the bug with an existing bug. Depending on the quality and speed of the evaluation the result may even be presented to the original logger.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>Second the assignment of bugs to both modules and persons can be improved. &nbsp;End-users have no idea how errors or functionality maps onto the internal organization (developers and code). Based on existing and new data the system could propose developers that are likely to be able to solve the issue. Furthermore it could improve the assignment to the correct functional module.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>The ultimate form of guidance is of course suggesting fixes or at least steps to get to a fix. Although this is definitely challenging, it should be possible to provide guidance in specific cases. In case of crashes due to null-pointers, the system could take in static code analyzers to determine the likely places of&nbsp;missing initialization.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<h3>References</h3>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li><span style=\"letter-spacing: 0.02px;\">Comparing Mining Algorithms for Predicting the Severity of a Reported Bug, Lamkamfi et al.</span></li>\r\n<li><span style=\"letter-spacing: 0.02px;\">Predicting Bugs\' Components via Mining Bug Reports, Wang et al.</span></li>\r\n<li><span style=\"letter-spacing: 0.02px;\">Recommendation systems in software engineering, Robillard et al.</span></li>\r\n</ul>');
insert into document (documentID, lang, content) values (default, engels, 'Onderzoek en ontwerp van een Single Page App designer','<p><strong>Opdracht:</strong> het uitwerken van een Single Page App designer die toelaat om zowel de User Interface als het gedrag van een kleine toepassing vast te leggen. De output van de App Designer dient zo bruikbaar mogelijk te zijn in de verdere fasen van een project: bij de ontwikkeling, het bouwen, het testen en het deployen van de toepassingen.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;<span style=\"letter-spacing: 0.02px;\">Details:</span></p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li><span style=\"letter-spacing: 0.02px;\">De app designer zal als tool gebruikt worden in analyse en ontwerp fase in samenwerking met de klant en vertegenwoordigers van de uiteindelijke gebruikers.&nbsp;</span></li>\r\n<li><span style=\"letter-spacing: 0.02px;\">De app designer dient zich toe te leggen op twee aspecten van een kleine toepassing:</span></li>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li><span style=\"letter-spacing: 0.02px;\">De UI (Bij Digipolis wordt er gewerkt op basis van Tink, een Google bootstrap ge&iuml;nspireerd framework in AngularJS). Keuze van de toolset en bepalen van de werkwijze.</span></li>\r\n<li><span style=\"letter-spacing: 0.02px;\">Het gedrag: want dient de app &lsquo;te doen&rsquo; bij bepaalde gebruikers-acties, geinspireerd door elementen van BDD (Behaviour Driven Developpment): hoe documenteren we deze specificaties op ondubbelzinnige wijze?</span></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<li><span style=\"letter-spacing: 0.02px;\">De specificaties van een app dienen bruikbaar te zijn:</span></li>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li><span style=\"letter-spacing: 0.02px;\">Als ontwerp bij de uiteindelijke ontwikkeling van de app. Het moet vermeden worden dat de ontwikkelaar code moet schrijven die eigenlijk al vastligt uit de analyse/ontwerp fase. (Idee: code genereren?)</span></li>\r\n<li><span style=\"letter-spacing: 0.02px;\">Als input om acceptatietesten op te zetten in een BDD framework (bijv. SpecFlow?) Met geslaagde testen dient aan de gebruikers het gevraagde/gespecifieerde gedrag aangetoond kunnen worden.</span></li>\r\n<li><span style=\"letter-spacing: 0.02px;\">Hoe kunnen we deze doelstellingen realiseren?</span></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<li><span style=\"letter-spacing: 0.02px;\">DevOps: Hoe implementeren we periodiek builden van deze apps, inclusief testing en deployment?</span></li>\r\n</ul>');
insert into document (documentID, lang, content) values (default, engels, 'The Monuments Men  Actionable data from indoor air quality analysis','<h3>Key words</h3>\r\n<p>Indoor air quality (IAQ), data mining</p>\r\n<h3>Context</h3>\r\n<p><img style=\"float: right; margin: 5px;\" src=\"http://www.two-views.com/images/mona_lisa_xray.jpg\" alt=\"\" />Today, almost all museums monitor temperature and relative humidity. Unfortunately, collection caretakers are quickly overwhelmed by the huge volumes of measurement data obtained from their monitoring system. Thus most of the collected information is not completely analysed. Furthermore, for a more accurate IAQ assessment additional environmental parameters should also be considered (particulate matter, UV radiation, contaminant gases, etc.) increasing the volume of data to handle and the complexity of the models used to predict the possible the occurrence of damage.</p>\r\n<p>In the specific field of preventive cultural heritage conservation data mining techniques might provide an alternative solution to a long held challenge, the IAQ assessment.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;Big data technologies are a new generation of algorithms and architectures, designed to capture information automatically and extract knowledge from huge volumes of heterogeneous data, through high-speed processing, detection and/or analysis. These technologies are becoming increasingly important as more data becomes available in various fields, such as city sensor networks (air quality, temperature), home/office automation, social networks (Facebook, Twitter), green energy (smart meters, home automation), mobility and transport (TomTom GPS data), etc.</p>\r\n<p>Although an abundance of data is generated and there are several open source packages available to handle this (Apache Hadoop), the data is still not fully exploited by companies and institutions. This is due to the scope of the data, or the lack of the right knowledge (new architectures, algorithms for machine learning and data mining) to analyze the data.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<h3>Objective</h3>\r\n<p>The objective of this master is the identification of suitable data mining and machine learning algorithms, which will be implemented and evaluated in the domain of indoor air quality.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li><span style=\"letter-spacing: 0.02px;\">Assessing the IAQ-index in order to identify structural patterns.</span></li>\r\n<li><span style=\"letter-spacing: 0.02px;\">Real-time trend and anomaly detection in order to identify trends (e.g. seasonal) and situations/events (draft due to open door) that deviate from these trends.</span></li>\r\n<li><span style=\"letter-spacing: 0.02px;\">Predicting the IAQ-index and state of the art in order to align it better with each other.&nbsp;</span></li>\r\n<li><span style=\"letter-spacing: 0.02px;\">Proactive risk assessment in order to predict when a work of art is suffering long term damage as result of the IAQ trend.</span></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p>Concrete examples of algorithms are reinforcement learning, Bayesian networks, clustering, support vector machines, neural networks.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>');
insert into document (documentID, lang, content) values (default, engels, 'The Monuments Men  formal modelling of indoor air quality in view of preventive and proactive cultu','<h3>Key words</h3>\r\n<p>Indoor air quality (IAQ), formal models, semantics, ontologies, inference, reasoning, data analysis</p>\r\n<h3>Context</h3>\r\n<p>Environmental conditions have a critical impact on the degradation process and rate of any material. Therefore, in the specific field of preventive cultural heritage conservation, controlling the IAQ has become of uttermost importance to avoid further damage to historic artefacts and works of art.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p><img style=\"float: left; margin: 5px;\" src=\"http://derekwinnert.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/02/546.jpg\" alt=\"\" height=\"225\" /></p>\r\n<p>The awareness that heritage objects should be provided with appropriate environmental conditions boomed after the World Wars. For safety reasons, many objects were moved to railway tunnels, secret tunnels or quarries. These temporarily new conditions appeared either disastrous or superior to the earlier museum and gallery conditions. The considerable damage caused by unsuitable conditions triggered the development of standards and guidelines for a climate that would be &lsquo;safe&rsquo; for the collections.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>Today, almost all museums monitor temperature (T) and relative humidity (RH). In addition, many museums execute considerable investments in air conditioning systems to stabilize the environmental conditions. Unfortunately, collection caretakers are quickly overwhelmed by the huge volume of measurement data obtained from their monitoring system. Therefore, there is the necessity to provide heritage caretakers a user-friendly tool that allows them to manage the IAQ.</p>\r\n<h3>Objective</h3>\r\n<p>The objective of this master thesis is experimenting with the use of semantic technologies such as ontologies for modelling the context and rules in the field of risk management of cultural heritage artefacts.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<ol>\r\n<li><span style=\"letter-spacing: 0.02px;\">Firstly, an initial literature study on the existing approaches will be executed. An analysis and description will be made of the different semantic techniques in the context of indoor air quality in view of cultural heritage.&nbsp;</span></li>\r\n<li><span style=\"letter-spacing: 0.02px;\">In addition, the type and the sources of the context information relevant for the risk management will be identified. The ultimate goal is the development of an application consisting of formal context (semantic) models and rules to enable reasoning about the condition of the cultural heritage artefacts&rsquo;.</span></li>\r\n</ol>\r\n<p><span style=\"border-radius: 2px; text-indent: 20px; width: auto; padding: 0px 4px 0px 0px; text-align: center; font: bold 11px/20px \'Helvetica Neue\',Helvetica,sans-serif; color: #ffffff; background: #bd081c url(\'data:image/svg+xml;base64,\') no-repeat scroll 3px 50% / 14px 14px; position: absolute; opacity: 1; z-index: 8675309; display: none; cursor: pointer;\">Save</span></p>');
insert into document (documentID, lang, content) values (default, engels, 'Developing  a performant geographical distribution algorithm  [Industrial Partner]','<p>Over the course of the past six years Geowacht VZW (<a href=\"http://www.geowacht.be\" target=\"_blank\">www.geowacht.be</a>) &nbsp;and KAVA &nbsp;(<a href=\"http://www.kava.be\" target=\"_blank\">www.kava.be</a>) have built out an innovative GIS system for optimizing the geographic distribution of on duty pharmacies.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>Geowacht has evolved from a local &nbsp;area to an ever larger area. It covers now the whole of Flandres and soon it will cover the entire Belgian territory. &nbsp;As we have to scale this algorithm to serve larger and larger areas and have to take into account different local particularities, &nbsp;performance issues become apparant.</p>\r\n<p>To generate on duty services numerous permutations need to be evaluated. The number of permutations increases exponentially with number of pharmacies serviced. For each permutation the fitness of all on duty pharmacies needs to be reevaluated and this is an expensive operation. Based on early performance tests we predict that, should we scale to service the entirety of Belgium, this part of the algorithm will take up over 95% of total calculation time.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>Your task will be to:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li><span style=\"letter-spacing: 0.02px;\">evaluate and identify deficiencies in the current algorithm&nbsp;</span></li>\r\n<li><span style=\"letter-spacing: 0.02px;\">research and experiment with various strategies for tackling this performance bottleneck, weighing performance against accuracy when needed.</span></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p>Some viable research avenues are listed here but own research and experimentation is highly encouraged:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li><span style=\"letter-spacing: 0.02px;\">The chance of a permutation on a specific location affecting an other pharmacy\'s fitness decreases with distance. By predicting in advance which portion of the map will be affected by a permutation we can significantly reduce the number of pharmacies for which fitness needs to be reevaluated. If the affected areas are small enough we may even be able to evaluate multiple permutations in parallel and experiment with divide and conquer algorithms.</span></li>\r\n<li><span style=\"letter-spacing: 0.02px;\">The selection of viable permutations is not very intelligent, resulting in a rather more brute force approach to tackling the optimization than is ideal. Based on analysis of the success rate of certain kinds of permutations the number of attempted permutations may be significantly reduced or better permutations could be constructed.</span></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<h3>&nbsp;<span style=\"letter-spacing: 0.02px;\">Company Information</span></h3>\r\n<p>&nbsp;<span style=\"letter-spacing: 0.02px;\">KAVA (Koninklijke Apotekersvereniging van Antwerpen ) is the biggest professional &nbsp;association of pharmacies in the country. KAVA offers a lot of</span><span style=\"letter-spacing: 0.02px;\">services to its members: post-university courses, fiscal services, price setting of medical prescriptions, supply of profession specific information,&nbsp;</span><span style=\"letter-spacing: 0.02px;\">company support, management advice,...</span></p>\r\n<p>From within the profession association the software company FarmaFrame has also been created, which was &nbsp;responsible for the automatisation of the&nbsp;<span style=\"letter-spacing: 0.02px;\">pharmacies. It evolved over the years to a new company Farm@d which offers &nbsp;services to over 1.400 customers, what makes it one of the biggest software companies in the sector.&nbsp;</span><span style=\"letter-spacing: 0.02px;\">IT is an important component of the strategy of KAVA. KAVA was the first company in the sector (from 1995 on) to make use of the internet to improve&nbsp;</span><span style=\"letter-spacing: 0.02px;\">the service: forwarding software, updating medicine files and for internal and external communication. The search for possibilities to apply new&nbsp;</span><span style=\"letter-spacing: 0.02px;\">technological developments is crucial for the IT-policy. The investment policy - both when it comes to investments in hardware as for the usage of the IT - confirms the wish of KAVA to stay a leading actor in the sector.</span></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>');
insert into document (documentID, lang, content) values (default, engels, 'A GIS-based multi-criteria decision planning model [Industrial Partner]','<p>Over the course of the past six years Geowacht VZW and KAVA have built out an innovative GIS system for optimizing the geographic distribution of on duty pharmacies.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>A significant chunk of this algorithm involves an incremental planning problem: The solution for a planning problem serves as the input for a GIS algorithm whose output serves as additional input for a new planning problem. Finding good solutions for planning problems is difficult even in ordinary circumstances. This incremental nature probably makes the problem borderline insolvable. In fact, past research has already shown that an all-encompassing algorithm can not solve the problem in a reasonable timeframe.</p>\r\n<p>We predict that a good solution for a single iteration of the planning problem has at least some attributes that can be identified and measured without the need to incur the incremental algorithm penalty. If we can identify these attributes then we can build a model that solves only a single iteration of this planning problem yet can also give accurate results for the incremental version of the planning problem.</p>\r\n<p>Your task will be to:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li><span style=\"letter-spacing: 0.02px;\">Identify attributes</span></li>\r\n<li><span style=\"letter-spacing: 0.02px;\">build a model that can solve a single iteration of the planning problem in a reasonable amount of time.</span></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<h3><span style=\"letter-spacing: 0.02px;\">Company Information</span></h3>\r\n<p><span style=\"letter-spacing: 0.02px;\">KAVA (Koninklijke Apotekersvereniging van Antwerpen ) is the biggest professional &nbsp;association of pharmacies in the country. KAVA offers a lot of&nbsp;</span><span style=\"letter-spacing: 0.02px;\">services to its members: post-university courses, fiscal services, price setting of medical prescriptions, supply of profession specific information,&nbsp;</span><span style=\"letter-spacing: 0.02px;\">company support, management advice,...</span></p>\r\n<p>From within the profession association the software company FarmaFrame has also been created, which was &nbsp;responsible for the automatisation of the&nbsp;<span style=\"letter-spacing: 0.02px;\">pharmacies. It evolved over the years to a new company Farm@d which offers &nbsp;services to over 1.400 customers, what makes it one of the biggest software companies in the sector.</span></p>\r\n<p>IT is an important component of the strategy of KAVA. KAVA was the first company in the sector (from 1995 on) to make use of the internet to improve&nbsp;<span style=\"letter-spacing: 0.02px;\">the service: forwarding software, updating medicine files and for internal and external communication. The search for possibilities to apply new&nbsp;</span><span style=\"letter-spacing: 0.02px;\">technological developments is crucial for the IT-policy. The investment policy - both when it comes to investments in hardware as for the usage of the IT - confirms the wish of KAVA to stay a leading actor in the sector.</span></p>');
insert into document (documentID, lang, content) values (default, engels, 'A theoretical study of repair-based detection of errors in data','<p>Error detection in data is often constraint-based, i.e., domain experts specify data quality rules and the pieces of data that do not adhere to these rules are considered to be dirty. Once the errors are found, repairing algorithms are in place that modify the data such that all data quality rules are satisfied. These repairing algorithms, however, make ad-hoc decisions as to which pieces and how these pieces are modified. In a recent paper [1], a theoretical model is proposed to distinguish between different errors. More specifically, a set of minimal causal \"cells\" (pieces of data) is defined such that when these are modified, one is guaranteed that the repairing algorithm is successful, and furthermore, a minimal amount of cells have been modified.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>A further exploration of the properties of this model is needed, however, both from a theoretical and practical point of view, and this is what is the topic of this master thesis. The expected outcome of the thesis are two-fold: establishing theoretical properties of the cell-based model for data repairs (complexity analysis, identification of tractable cases), extensions of the model to accomodate for a variety of data repairing algorithms (not only chase based as in [1]), and an experimental evaluation.</p>\r\n<p><span style=\"letter-spacing: 0.02px;\">Skills needed for this project are: interest in theoretical aspects of computer science and databases in particular, knowledge of complexity theory and query languages (or intention to learn this on the side), implementation skills, and good research attitude. To see whether this project is something for you, take a look at the paper below.</span></p>\r\n<p>[1] Cell-based causility for data repairs. M. Debosschere &amp; F. Geerts. h<span style=\"letter-spacing: 0.02px;\">ttps://www.usenix.org/system/files/tapp15-debosschere.pdf</span></p>');
insert into document (documentID, lang, content) values (default, engels, 'Experimental assessment of the quality of error detection and repairing methods.','<p>In [1] an&nbsp;<span style=\"font-family: Helvetica; letter-spacing: normal;\">error detection and reparing method is proposed based on pattern&nbsp;</span><span style=\"font-family: Helvetica; letter-spacing: normal;\">mining techniques. More specifically, e</span><span style=\"font-family: Helvetica; letter-spacing: normal;\">rrors are identified &nbsp;by mining the data for so-called forbidden&nbsp;</span><span style=\"font-family: Helvetica; letter-spacing: normal;\">itemsets. Such itemsets tell which value combination are unexpected&nbsp;</span><span style=\"font-family: Helvetica; letter-spacing: normal;\">and unlikely (age &lt;10 &amp; married=yes, etc). Given these forbidden itemsets,&nbsp;</span><span style=\"font-family: Helvetica; letter-spacing: normal;\">data is then modified such that no new forbidden itemsets can be found&nbsp;</span><span style=\"font-family: Helvetica; letter-spacing: normal;\">in the data.</span></p>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-family: Helvetica; letter-spacing: normal;\">In this research internship, you will assess the quality of these methods. In particular, you will experimentally validate&nbsp;</span><span style=\"font-family: Helvetica; letter-spacing: normal;\">how good these methods are on data that is used for classification. We want to see how</span><span style=\"font-family: Helvetica; letter-spacing: normal;\">&nbsp;repairing of the data impacts the classification error and get guidance in this way as what the best repair is.</span></p>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-family: Helvetica; letter-spacing: normal;\">This project involves running the detection and repairing methods on various&nbsp;</span><span style=\"font-family: Helvetica; letter-spacing: normal;\">datasets (with different parameters), comparing accuracy quality of some</span><br style=\"font-family: Helvetica; letter-spacing: normal;\" /><span style=\"font-family: Helvetica; letter-spacing: normal;\">classification methods before and after repairing, and possibly implementing&nbsp;</span><span style=\"font-family: Helvetica; letter-spacing: normal;\">an alternative (association rule based) detection method for comparison.</span></p>\r\n<p>[1] Data cleaning with forbidden itemsets.&nbsp;<span style=\"letter-spacing: 0.02px;\">http://adrem.uantwerpen.be/sites/adrem.uantwerpen.be/files/ForbiddenItemsetsICDE.pdf</span></p>');
insert into document (documentID, lang, content) values (default, engels, 'Lightweight OpenFlow','<p><span style=\"font-family: \'Times New Roman\'; font-size: 16px; letter-spacing: normal;\">In a lot of cases, there is a need to have an SDN-based management of end devices. An example is the load-balancing between different technologies. However, deploying a full-fledged OpenFlow-based program (e.g., OpenvSwitch) is often overkill for these end devices as an OpenvSwitch has a very high footprint in terms of resources. However, these end devices only require a limited set of &ldquo;OpenFlow-type&rdquo; of functionality as they are not required to &ldquo;forward&rdquo; data. The goal of this thesis is therefore to design a minimal and lightweight OpenFlow compliant building block for end devices. Depending on the interest you can choose to go for an implementation on a Raspberry PI or Android phone.</span></p>');
insert into document (documentID, lang, content) values (default, engels, 'Discovering Local Statistical Distributions using R','<p>The aim of this project is two-fold: (a) to investigate the capabilities of the R software package [1] to extract statistical distributions from data; (b) to combine these distribution with frequent pattern mining algorithms [2].</p>\r\n<p>Combined, one should be able to obtain LSDs, local statistical distributions specified by rules of the form [X-&gt;Y, (fp, dist(Y)], meaning that for those data tuples &nbsp;t such that t[X]=fp (frequent pattern fp), the distribution of the corresponding the t[Y]-values matches well with the dist(Y). Here, t[X] denotes the attribute values of tuple t in the X-attributes, and similarly for t[Y].</p>\r\n<p>With these LSDs in place, one is then interested to detect errors in the data, i.e., value combinations that can be regarded as outliers, with respect to the LSD rules.</p>\r\n<p>This internship involves the formalisation (and study) of LSDs rules, a substantial implementation part for discovering LSDs, and obtaining familiarity with R. Implementations should be carried out (preferably) in C++.</p>\r\n<p><span style=\"letter-spacing: 0.02px;\">[1]&nbsp;https://www.r-project.org/about.html</span></p>\r\n<p>[2]&nbsp;https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Association_rule_learning</p>');
insert into document (documentID, lang, content) values (default, engels, 'Evaluation of future Wi-Fi technologies','<p>Over the past years, more and more people are connected to the Internet by means of wireless technologies instead of the traditional cable.<span style=\"mso-spacerun: yes;\">&nbsp; </span>Consequently, people expect a better quality of their wireless connection and push existing technologies to the limit. For instance, we want to be able to watch high quality Netflix or YouTube videos on our tablets and smartphones.</p>\r\n<p>Different new Wi-Fi standards have been proposed and these technologies are beginning to become available for the pubic. One of these technologies is 60 GHz Wi-Fi (802.11ad). This technology operates in a much higher frequency then the traditional WI-Fi (2.4 and 5 GHz band) and allows to transmit very high volumes of data (like video streams). Due to the fact that multiple directed antennas are being used, the technology lacks mobility. If a user device is receiving a beam from the AP, it will lose connectivity as it moves outside of the small range of the beam. These specific characteristics urge the need for algorithms that, for instance, decide when to send a beam to a device or when to use this new technology instead of the traditional Wi-Fi.</p>\r\n<p>The goal of this thesis or internship is to evaluate the technology by using the NS-3 network simulator and real hardware. More in detail, the following things will need to happen:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Compare the behaviour of 60 GHz Wi-Fi in reality with the implementation in the NS-3 simulator.</li>\r\n<li>The evaluation of existing solutions for beam steering and the reproducing of their results.</li>\r\n<li>Investigating the impact of handing over flows between this new technology and the more traditional Wi-Fi.</li>\r\n<li>Try to find patters in the mobility of the user and predict when this technology should be used or not.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p><img src=\"https://i.kinja-img.com/gawker-media/image/upload/s--SEHhc06F--/c_scale,fl_progressive,q_80,w_800/xk8qi00vgkkluyg3gt5y.jpg\" alt=\"A 802.11ad Wi-Fi access point\" width=\"400\" height=\"225\" /></p>\r\n<p class=\"MsoListParagraphCxSpLast\" style=\"text-indent: -18.0pt; mso-list: l0 level1 lfo1;\">&nbsp;</p>');
insert into document (documentID, lang, content) values (default, engels, 'Providing network security in a resource-constrained cyclist network','<p class=\"MsoNormal\">Sports and data go hand in hand. In recent years, we have seen an increasing importance of monitoring data to take strategic decisions at professional sports events. This monitoring is especially prevalent in cycling as show by the popularity of smartphone applications like Strava. But real-time monitoring of cyclists is often not supported in this applications or the applications are fully dependent on a (not reliable) 4G connection. Therefore, we are building a long-range wireless network technology that uses the cyclists as the hops of a network to deliver monitored data in real-time to the team cars of professional cyclists. However, a major concern of these cyclist teams is that the monitored data of their cyclist should not be hacked by other teams: the data should be encrypted and secured.<br />&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p class=\"MsoNormal\"><img style=\"display: block; margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto;\" src=\"https://student.mosaic.uantwerpen.be/~gdaneels/DeKrookDemo_ReSF_internship.jpg\" alt=\"\" width=\"453\" height=\"311\" /></p>\r\n<p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span style=\"letter-spacing: 0.02px;\">In order to build this multi-hop network made up of cyclists, we use the IEEE802.15.4e MAC standard that supports IPv6 over timeslotted channel hopping (6TiSCH) mode. The standard on 6TiSCH is however still under development and the amendments on security are still in their early stages. Therefore, your task would be to (1) find out which security techniques are proposed for 6TiSCH networks, (2) how these can be applied in our cyclist 6TiSCH network and (3) implement these on the real resource-constrained hardware that is used for the 6TiSCH cyclist network. So, this internship will give you the chance to immerse yourself in resource-constrained network security and also apply this knowledge in a real-world application.<br /><br />This research is conducted in partnership with UGent, VUB, Rombit, EnergyLab and VRT in the CONAMO (Continuous Athlete Monitoring), a project funded by imec and IWT [1].<br /><br />[1] https://www.iminds.be/nl/projecten/conamo</span></p>');
insert into document (documentID, lang, content) values (default, engels, 'Security in the Internet of Things','<p>In the city of Antwerp, a joint project between imec and the University of Antwerp,&nbsp;<span style=\"letter-spacing: 0.02px;\">called \"City of Things\", is currently ongoing. This project is</span><span style=\"letter-spacing: 0.02px;\">&nbsp;supported by the city of Antwerp . The goal of City of Things is to offer a \"playground\" or \"testing ground\" for IoT applications in a real-life, large-scale environment: a city. The ultimate goal is to become a reference lab for IoT applications, focusing both on users and on technology, where anyone can come and create, test and validate IoT applications and technologies.</span></p>\r\n<p>As part of this \"testing ground\", our research group is rolling out a city-wide wireless testbed consisting of so-called \"IoT gateways\", devices that contain many different wireless technologies (WiFi 2.4GHz and 5GHz, BLE, Sigfox, LoRaWAN, DASH7, ...). These devices can be used by external experimenters for all kinds of experiments ranging from testing of new networking protocols to testing new sensor devices or applications.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>There are two main aspects that make this testbed challenging from a security perspective: the first is the fact that the testbed can be used by anyone, which implicates that anyone can run any application on these gateways they desire. This might lead to potentially malafide applications running on certain gateways, trying to damage the network or even the end-user devices communicating with the gateways.</p>\r\n<p>The second is the fact that the gateways are spread all over the city and are specifically built to use all kinds of wireless technologies. Thus, malicious people could try to hack into one of these gateways by being in the proximity and somehow hacking into one of the wireless channels. Physical tampering with a gateway is also a possibility, but this is out of scope for this internship.</p>\r\n<p>To detect malicious behaviour, continuous monitoring of the gateways is needed and also a notion of what is \"normal\" and what is \"abnormal\" behaviour is necessary. In this internship, you will focus on two different things:</p>\r\n<ol>\r\n<li>Detecting abnormal behaviour on the network. All information sent to and from the Internet from the City of Things gateways passes via routers under our control, so it is possible to monitor all network traffic between the Internet and the gateways. This way, it might be possible to detect anomalies using a tool such as Snort (https://www.snort.org), an open source intrusion prevension system. Here, you will need to take two things into account: specific behaviour relating to the normal operation of the testbed and specific behaviour relating to IoT applications. This might be substantially different from a \"normal\" network, so possibly Snort needs to be enhanced with new rules specifically catered to IoT applications.</li>\r\n<li>You will need to take a look at what tools could be used to locally monitor the IoT gateways to detect local hacking attempts.</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n<p>The main focus of this internship will be on the first point. In order to validate the solution you are working out for detecting abnormal network behaviour, you will start out with a \"mini-version\" of the IoT testbed, situated locally at the university. When your solutions are mature anough and have proven themselves to work on this mini-testbed, they can be tested on the real City of Things testbed to evaluate their effectiveness.</p>');
insert into document (documentID, lang, content) values (default, engels, 'Prototyping a resource-constrained cyclist network','<p class=\"MsoNormal\">Sports and data go hand in hand. In recent years, we have seen an increasing importance of monitoring data to take strategic decisions at professional sports events. This monitoring is especially prevalent in cycling as shown by the popularity of smartphone applications like Strava. But real-time monitoring of cyclists is often not supported in this applications or the applications are fully dependent on a (not reliable) 4G connection. Therefore, we are building a long-range wireless network technology that uses the cyclists as the hops of a network to deliver monitored data in real-time to the team cars of professional cyclists.&nbsp;<span style=\"font-size: small; letter-spacing: 0.02px;\">This research is conducted in partnership with UGent, VUB, Rombit, EnergyLab and VRT in the CONAMO (Continuous Athlete Monitoring), a project funded by imec and IWT [1].</span><br /><br /><span style=\"letter-spacing: 0.02px;\">In order to build this multi-hop network made up of cyclists, we use the IEEE802.15.4e MAC layer in combination with the IEEE802.15.4g PHY layer that sums up to doing IPv6 timeslotted channel hopping (6TiSCH) in a subGHz frequency band. This allows us to hop cycling data from bike to bike to teamcar covering several hundred and even kilometers of distance.</span></p>\r\n<p class=\"MsoNormal\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p class=\"MsoNormal\"><img style=\"display: block; margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto;\" src=\"https://student.mosaic.uantwerpen.be/~gdaneels/DeKrookDemo_ReSF_internship.jpg\" alt=\"\" width=\"453\" height=\"311\" /></p>\r\n<p class=\"MsoNormal\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p class=\"MsoNormal\">We&rsquo;ve recently built a basic prototype device. However, this prototype is still lacking a lot of functionality. Needed improvements are (i) a more user-friendly interface to configure the devices e.g., using the NFC chip on the devices (ii) integration of (already existing) advanced scheduling algorithms which decrease data delay and power consumption (iii) the implementation of security measures such as encryption in order to protect data from competing teams. So, in this internship you gain hands-on experience with a real IoT network stack (i.e., the OpenWSN open-source IoT stack), have the possibility to work with different hardware platforms and wireless standards (i.e., the OpenMote and Nordic nRF boards and IEEE802.15.4e/g, BLE, NFC and ANT+ as wireless standards respectively) and implement new IoT scheduling algorithms. The goal at the end of this internship is to have an improved prototype in terms of user-friendliness, stability, security and performance that is ready to be used in real-world cycling events.<br /><br /><span style=\"letter-spacing: 0.02px;\">[1] https://www.iminds.be/nl/projecten/conamo</span></p>');
insert into document (documentID, lang, content) values (default, engels, 'Scheduling in a resource-constrained cyclist network','<p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span style=\"font-size: small;\">Sports and data go hand in hand. In recent years, we have seen an increasing importance of monitoring data to take strategic decisions at professional sports events. This monitoring is especially prevalent in cycling as shown by the popularity of smartphone applications like Strava. But real-time monitoring of cyclists is often not supported in this applications or the applications are fully dependent on a (not reliable) 4G connection. Therefore, we are building a long-range wireless network technology that uses the cyclists as the hops of a network to deliver monitored data in real-time to the team cars of professional cyclists. This research is conducted in partnership with UGent, VUB, Rombit, EnergyLab and VRT in the CONAMO (Continuous Athlete Monitoring), a project funded by imec and IWT [1].<br /><br /></span><span style=\"letter-spacing: 0.02px; font-size: small;\">In order to build this multi-hop network made up of cyclists, we use the IEEE802.15.4e MAC layer in combination with the IEEE802.15.4g PHY layer that sums up to doing IPv6 timeslotted channel hopping (6TiSCH) in a subGHz frequency band. This allows us to hop cycling data from bike to bike to teamcar covering several hundred and even kilometers of distance.<br /></span></p>\r\n<p class=\"MsoNormal\"><img style=\"display: block; margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto;\" src=\"https://student.mosaic.uantwerpen.be/~gdaneels/DeKrookDemo_ReSF_internship.jpg\" alt=\"\" width=\"453\" height=\"311\" /></p>\r\n<p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span style=\"letter-spacing: 0.02px; font-size: small;\"><br /></span><span style=\"font-size: small; letter-spacing: 0.02px;\">In such 6TiSCH networks each node follows a schedule that tells the node exactly when to transmit and when to receive. Unlike traditional CSMA/CA networks (e.g., WiFi) nodes do not have listen whole the time and can save a lot of power consumption. Managing the different transmit and receive slots in such a schedule is done by a scheduling function. Many of these scheduling functions already exist, but their performance in such a dynamic context as a cycling event is hardly tested. Your task in this internship/thesis would be (i) to do a literature study of possible candidate scheduling functions, (ii) improve upon an already existing one or invent a new scheduling function, tailored to this cycling context, (iii) scientifically test its performance and compare it to already existing scheduling functions in a simulator or in real hardware. So the goal of this thesis/internship is to deliver a scheduling function that is specifically tailored for this context that outperforms other already existing scheduling functions.</span></p>\r\n<p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span style=\"font-size: small; letter-spacing: 0.02px;\">[1] https://www.iminds.be/nl/projecten/conamo</span></p>\r\n<!--EndFragment-->');
insert into document (documentID, lang, content) values (default, engels, 'Security on an interconnected embedded Linux device','<p>Embedded Linux offers tremendous advantages to device manufacturers. The community support, portability and flexibility make it the feature-rich OS that can easily be deployed. &nbsp;The growing population of connected devices together with the increasing knowledge/tools of cyber-attacks makes the open source OS and attractive and easy target.</p>\r\n<p><span style=\"letter-spacing: 0.02px;\">Establishing a sound security policy/strategy for a system of connected Linux devices is these days an integral part of the embedded system design.</span></p>\r\n<p><strong>Research</strong></p>\r\n<p><span style=\"letter-spacing: 0.02px;\">Identifying potential strategies and technologies that can be implemented on an embedded eco-system and determining their strengths and weaknesses. Examples of potential strategies/technologies can be:</span></p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li><span style=\"letter-spacing: 0.02px;\">secure boot (implementing a chain of trust)</span></li>\r\n<li><span style=\"letter-spacing: 0.02px;\">encrypting firmware and protecting the update process</span></li>\r\n<li><span style=\"letter-spacing: 0.02px;\">storing encryption keys in a secure fashion</span></li>\r\n<li><span style=\"letter-spacing: 0.02px;\">hardware locking, protection against cloning</span></li>\r\n<li><span style=\"letter-spacing: 0.02px;\">secure licensing system</span></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p><strong>Development</strong></p>\r\n<p><span style=\"letter-spacing: 0.02px;\">Based on the findings in the research part:</span></p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li><span style=\"letter-spacing: 0.02px;\">Develop an integrated security strategy for a network of embedded devices.</span></li>\r\n<li><span style=\"letter-spacing: 0.02px;\">Select and implement the optimal communication protocols based on the wanted degree of security.</span></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p><strong>Inofrmation about the company</strong></p>\r\n<p>Araani is a young dynamic company specialized in Video Analytics for People, Process and Property protection.&nbsp;<span style=\"letter-spacing: 0.02px;\">We develop innovative state-of-the-art products for the niche markets of chemical plants, process industry and recycling.&nbsp;</span><span style=\"letter-spacing: 0.02px;\">To achieve this, we highly invest in our people to stay on top of new technology.</span></p>');
insert into document (documentID, lang, content) values (default, engels, '3D-model based on image fusion of LiDAR and Video camera mounted on a drone','<p><span style=\"letter-spacing: 0.02px;\">LiDAR technology is already widespread in agriculture, archaeology and the military sector, but used to be considered to be too expensive for industrial environments.&nbsp;</span><span style=\"letter-spacing: 0.02px;\">However, nowadays LiDAR systems are becoming more affordable, and the goal of this thesis is to evaluate how accurate they can be used in outdoor environments.&nbsp;</span></p>\r\n<p><span style=\"letter-spacing: 0.02px;\">Combined with corresponding video of the site, the depth information retrieved from the LiDAR can be mapped to the visual information of the video.&nbsp;</span><span style=\"letter-spacing: 0.02px;\">Mounting this set-up on a drone, should make it possible to create a 3D-model of the scene.&nbsp;</span></p>\r\n<p><strong>Research</strong></p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li><span style=\"letter-spacing: 0.02px;\">Literature study of LiDAR technology</span></li>\r\n<li><span style=\"letter-spacing: 0.02px;\">\"Mapping\" of LiDAR and video-images to a 3D-model of the scene</span></li>\r\n<li><span style=\"letter-spacing: 0.02px;\">Accuracy of LiDAR in outdoor environments:&nbsp;</span></li>\r\n<li><span style=\"letter-spacing: 0.02px;\">Impact of outdoor conditions (rain, sun, snow, other...) on the performance of the LiDAR</span></li>\r\n<li><span style=\"letter-spacing: 0.02px;\">Distance of objects vs. accuracy: maximal range</span></li>\r\n<li><span style=\"letter-spacing: 0.02px;\">Minimum required stability on the drone</span></li>\r\n<li><span style=\"letter-spacing: 0.02px;\">Impact of the material of the objects on the accuracy (reflectance,...)</span></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p><strong>Development</strong></p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li><span style=\"letter-spacing: 0.02px;\">Based on the results of the research phase, develop an algorithm that can reconstruct a 3D-scene of an industrial site.</span></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p><strong>About the company</strong></p>\r\n<p>Araani is a young dynamic company specialized in Video Analytics for People, Process and Property protection.&nbsp;<span style=\"letter-spacing: 0.02px;\">We develop innovative state-of-the-art products for the niche markets of chemical plants, process industry and recycling.&nbsp;</span><span style=\"letter-spacing: 0.02px;\">To achieve this, we highly invest in our people to stay on top of new technology.</span></p>');
insert into document (documentID, lang, content) values (default, engels, 'Develop an anomaly detection algorithm and implement it on an GPU-platform','<p><span style=\"letter-spacing: 0.02px;\">At present, machine learning and deep learning algorithms are commonly used in a variety of applications, from Google Analytics in social media, Machine Vision up to Predictive Maintenance and numerous other applications. Libraries with Big Data analytics are both open source and under commercial license available, and hardware manufacturers are promoting AI-libraries with SDK\'s for their embedded boards.&nbsp;</span></p>\r\n<p>The intention of this thesis is to develop an algorithm for anomaly detection, deploy it on an embedded GPU-platform and compare performance to existing libraries.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p><strong><span style=\"letter-spacing: 0.02px;\">Research</span></strong></p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li><span style=\"letter-spacing: 0.02px;\">Literature study of algorithms for anomaly detection&nbsp;</span></li>\r\n<li><span style=\"letter-spacing: 0.02px;\">Comparative study of existing state-of-the-art algorithms and libraries&nbsp;</span></li>\r\n<li><span style=\"letter-spacing: 0.02px;\">Make a comparative study of embedded GPU-platforms&nbsp;</span></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p><strong><span style=\"letter-spacing: 0.02px;\">Development</span></strong></p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li><span style=\"letter-spacing: 0.02px;\">Development of an algorithm for anomaly detection&nbsp;</span></li>\r\n<li><span style=\"letter-spacing: 0.02px;\">Implementation on a GPU-platform&nbsp;</span></li>\r\n<li><span style=\"letter-spacing: 0.02px;\">Comparison of performance between different libraries and own algorithm&nbsp;</span></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p><strong><span style=\"letter-spacing: 0.02px;\">About the company</span></strong></p>\r\n<p><span style=\"letter-spacing: 0.02px;\">Araani is a young dynamic company specialized in Video Analytics for People, Process and Property protection. We develop innovative state-of-the-art products for the niche markets of chemical plants, process industry and recycling.&nbsp;</span><span style=\"letter-spacing: 0.02px;\">To achieve this, we highly invest in our people to stay on top of new technology.</span></p>');
insert into document (documentID, lang, content) values (default, engels, 'Explore innovative approaches to data-sharing in the mobile access network','<p><strong style=\"letter-spacing: 0.02px;\"><span style=\"letter-spacing: 0.02px;\">Research</span></strong></p>\r\n<p><span style=\"letter-spacing: 0.02px;\">There is a great potential of using proven and scalable data distribution techniques to enable and support distributed resource management and self-organisation in the RAN. The scope of the proposed project is to take an existing product platform and add data distribution capabilities using 3rd party commercial software, and then to explore the potential improvements in network capacity which can be obtained through data sharing.</span></p>\r\n<p><span style=\"letter-spacing: 0.02px;\"><br /></span></p>\r\n<p><strong><span style=\"letter-spacing: 0.02px;\">About the company</span></strong></p>\r\n<p>Accelleran is pioneering a disruptive approach to the delivery of cost-effective, carrier and mission-critical grade LTE TDD and FDD Small Cells through its focus on software quality and partnerships with volume manufacturers. We provide urban, enterprise, rural and remote 4G Small Cells for Fixed Wireless and Mobile access, enabling from sparse coverage-constrained to capacity-constrained ultra-dense HetNet environments. &nbsp;</p>');
insert into document (documentID, lang, content) values (default, engels, 'Bluetooth Low Energy (BLE) Indoor localization');
insert into document (documentID, lang, content) values (default, engels, 'Wireless SDN based management framework on newer code base','<p><span style=\"font-family: CMR10; font-size: 10pt; letter-spacing: 0.02px;\">Software defined networking (SDN) is a popular paradigm to manage a wired network. It allows to administrate the network centrally through a controller and can increase performance significantly as there is an overall view present. This paradigm moved from wired networks to wireless networks as well. 5G- EmPOWER is one such platform that is able to utilise SDN in wireless networks.</span></p>\r\n<div class=\"page\" title=\"Page 1\">\r\n<div class=\"layoutArea\">\r\n<p class=\"column\"><span style=\"font-size: 10.000000pt; font-family: \'CMR10\';\">5G-EmPOWER makes use of several technologies and platforms itself. One of these platforms is one of the most popular alternative open source firmwares for embedded devices such as residential gateways and routers, OpenWrt. Although popular, most developers switched to a fork called LEDE. It is important to keep underlying platforms up to date, therefore the goal of this thesis will be a port of the 5G-EmPOWER part relying on OpenWrt to LEDE. Included as well is finding an easy way to maintain and update LEDE in 5G-EmPOWER.&nbsp;</span></p>\r\n</div>\r\n</div>');
insert into document (documentID, lang, content) values (default, engels, 'Increasing reliability in distributed SDN controller for wireless networks','<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<div class=\"page\" title=\"Page 1\">\r\n<div class=\"layoutArea\">\r\n<div class=\"column\">\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size: 10.000000pt; font-family: \'CMR10\';\">Software defined networking (SDN) is a popular paradigm to manage a wired network. It allows to administrate the network centrally through a controller and can increase performance significantly as there is an overall view present. This paradigm moved from wired networks to wireless networks as well. 5G- EmPOWER is one such platform that is able to utilise SDN in wireless networks. </span></p>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size: 10.000000pt; font-family: \'CMR10\';\">5G-EmPOWER was designed with a single controller in mind, but extended to be working distributed as well. This allows for scalability, but fault tolerance is not included yet. The goal of this thesis is to include fault tolerance and increase reliability in general. As 5G-EmPOWER was not designed with distribution in mind, this means that underlying functionality in 5G-EmPOWER has to be changed as well.&nbsp;</span></p>\r\n</div>\r\n</div>\r\n</div>');
insert into document (documentID, lang, content) values (default, engels, 'Distributed VR application using indoor wireless localization');
insert into document (documentID, lang, content) values (default, engels, 'WiFi HaLow implementation in Time-Annotated Instruction Set Computer','<p class=\"MsoNormal\">The Internet of Things (IoT) consists of millions of power constrained devices addressable over the Internet. However, existing low power wireless network technologies either are incapable of long range transmission (e.g., ZigBee, Bluetooth Low Energy) or support limited throughput (e.g., LoRaWAN, Sigfox, DASH-7). Aiming to address this gap, the new IEEE 802.11ah standard, marketed as Wi-Fi HaLow, was finished in early 2017 supporting connectivity among many power-constrained stations deployed over a wide area. HaLow supports up to 8000 nodes connected to a single access point, operates in the unlicensed sub-1Ghz frequency bands, and provides communications over distances up to 1 km, while maintaining a data rate of over 150 Kbps, offering a greater reach and high throughput for battery-powered sensors.</p>\r\n<p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span style=\"letter-spacing: 0.02px;\">Since HaLow is a quite new wireless technology, there is currently no hardware available. Our group is the first to have implemented HaLow in simulation and make it available as open source for other researchers to experiment with </span><a style=\"letter-spacing: 0.02px;\" href=\"https://github.com/MOSAIC-UA/802.11ah-ns3\">https://github.com/MOSAIC-UA/802.11ah-ns3</a><span class=\"MsoHyperlink\" style=\"letter-spacing: 0.02px;\">.</span></p>\r\n<p class=\"MsoNormal\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p class=\"MsoNormal\">As the next step, to apply the HaLow technology to real-life IoT networks, we plan to implement HaLow in real hardware based on TAISC (Time-Annotated Instruction Set Computer). TAISC is a cross-platform MAC protocol compiler and execution engine, which offers an abstraction for hardware independent MAC protocol design and management. <span style=\"mso-spacerun: yes;\">&nbsp;</span>Different from today&rsquo;s MAC protocols which cannot be upgraded after deployment since their implementations are typically written in hardware specific code, TAISC allows describing MAC protocols in a platform independent language (consisting of a radio platform independent instruction set), followed by a straightforward compilation step, yielding dedicated binary code, optimized for specific radio chips. More information can be found in <a href=\"http://www.wishful-project.eu/taisc\">http://www.wishful-project.eu/taisc</a>.</p>\r\n<p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span style=\"letter-spacing: 0.02px;\">The goal of this project is to implement some features of HaLow in TAISC, and evaluate its performance in real IoT scenarios. It will give you the opportunity to work with a radically new wireless technology, and gain in-depth knowledge about the inner-workings of Wi-Fi protocols.</span></p>\r\n<p class=\"MsoNormal\">&nbsp;</p>');
insert into document (documentID, lang, content) values (default, engels, 'Generate and use a large-scale data-set for IoT experiments','<p class=\"MsoNormal\" style=\"mso-margin-top-alt: auto; mso-margin-bottom-alt: auto; text-align: justify; background: white;\"><strong><span style=\"font-size: 9.0pt; font-family: Verdana; mso-bidi-font-family: \'Times New Roman\'; color: black;\">Context</span></strong></p>\r\n<p class=\"MsoNormal\" style=\"mso-margin-top-alt: auto; mso-margin-bottom-alt: auto; text-align: justify; background: white;\"><span style=\"font-size: 9.0pt; font-family: Verdana; mso-bidi-font-family: \'Times New Roman\'; color: black;\">The Internet of things (IoT) paradigm brings a infinite number of new possibilities by connecting small and embedded devices to the Internet. One of the challenges behind these technologies is how to control and coordinate them under dynamics environments such as a shared wireless spectrum. By learning their transmission patterns, application behavior and use of the spectrum, it would be possible to improve the co-existence of different devices under the same shared environment.</span></p>\r\n<p class=\"MsoNormal\" style=\"mso-margin-top-alt: auto; mso-margin-bottom-alt: auto; text-align: justify; background: white;\"><strong><span style=\"font-size: 9.0pt; font-family: Verdana; mso-bidi-font-family: \'Times New Roman\'; color: black;\">Goal</span></strong></p>\r\n<p class=\"MsoNormal\" style=\"mso-margin-top-alt: auto; mso-margin-bottom-alt: auto; text-align: justify; background: white;\"><span style=\"font-size: 9.0pt; font-family: Verdana; mso-bidi-font-family: \'Times New Roman\'; color: black;\">Define, implement and test several IoT use cases in a real wireless test-bed and perform several machine learning task on the generated data set.&nbsp;</span></p>\r\n<p class=\"MsoNormal\" style=\"mso-margin-top-alt: auto; mso-margin-bottom-alt: auto; text-align: justify; background: white;\"><span style=\"font-size: 9.0pt; font-family: Verdana; mso-bidi-font-family: \'Times New Roman\'; color: black;\"><strong>Research</strong></span></p>\r\n<p class=\"MsoNormal\" style=\"text-align: justify; text-justify: inter-ideograph;\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n<ul type=\"disc\">\r\n<li class=\"MsoNormal\" style=\"color: black; mso-margin-top-alt: auto; mso-margin-bottom-alt: auto; mso-list: l0 level1 lfo1; tab-stops: list 36.0pt; background: white;\"><span style=\"font-size: 9.0pt; font-family: Verdana; mso-fareast-font-family: \'Times New Roman\'; mso-bidi-font-family: \'Times New Roman\';\">Literature study of wireless technologies for the IoT</span></li>\r\n<li class=\"MsoNormal\" style=\"color: black; mso-margin-top-alt: auto; mso-margin-bottom-alt: auto; mso-list: l0 level1 lfo1; tab-stops: list 36.0pt; background: white;\"><span style=\"font-size: 9.0pt; font-family: Verdana; mso-fareast-font-family: \'Times New Roman\'; mso-bidi-font-family: \'Times New Roman\';\">Literature study of supervised and unsupervised machine learning (ML) algorithms&nbsp;</span></li>\r\n<li class=\"MsoNormal\" style=\"color: black; mso-margin-top-alt: auto; mso-margin-bottom-alt: auto; mso-list: l0 level1 lfo1; tab-stops: list 36.0pt; background: white;\"><span style=\"font-size: 9.0pt; font-family: Verdana; mso-fareast-font-family: \'Times New Roman\'; mso-bidi-font-family: \'Times New Roman\';\">Define and implement several IoT use cases in a real wireless test-bed.</span></li>\r\n<li class=\"MsoNormal\" style=\"color: black; mso-margin-top-alt: auto; mso-margin-bottom-alt: auto; mso-list: l0 level1 lfo1; tab-stops: list 36.0pt; background: white;\"><span style=\"font-size: 9.0pt; font-family: Verdana; mso-fareast-font-family: \'Times New Roman\'; mso-bidi-font-family: \'Times New Roman\';\">Generate a large-scale data set of IoT traffic (application/transport layer), device behavior (connectivity) and spectrum access (physical layer raw data).&nbsp;</span></li>\r\n<li class=\"MsoNormal\" style=\"color: black; mso-margin-top-alt: auto; mso-margin-bottom-alt: auto; mso-list: l0 level1 lfo1; tab-stops: list 36.0pt; background: white;\"><span style=\"font-size: 9.0pt; font-family: Verdana; mso-fareast-font-family: \'Times New Roman\'; mso-bidi-font-family: \'Times New Roman\';\">Implement and test several machine learning algorithms for network traffic and device behavior prediction, and scheduling of the network access.</span></li>\r\n<li class=\"MsoNormal\" style=\"color: black; mso-margin-top-alt: auto; mso-margin-bottom-alt: auto; mso-list: l0 level1 lfo1; tab-stops: list 36.0pt; background: white;\"><span style=\"font-size: 9.0pt; font-family: Verdana; mso-fareast-font-family: \'Times New Roman\'; mso-bidi-font-family: \'Times New Roman\';\">Evaluate and compare the proposed solution with other well-known approaches.</span></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p class=\"MsoNormal\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p class=\"MsoNormal\" style=\"text-align: justify; text-justify: inter-ideograph;\">&nbsp;</p>');
insert into document (documentID, lang, content) values (default, engels, 'Using block-chain to extend some cloud system funtionalities','<p style=\"background: white;\"><strong><span style=\"font-size: 9.0pt; font-family: Verdana; color: black;\">Context</span></strong></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;<span style=\"font-family: Verdana; font-size: 9pt; letter-spacing: 0.02px;\">A blockchain is a distributed database that stores a list of ordered records called blocks. Each block contains a time-stamp and a link to the previous block. Once these blocks are recorded, their data cannot be altered. The&nbsp;blockchain database is managed autonomously by a combination of a&nbsp;peer-to-peer network and a distributed timestamping server. Therefore, blockchains are a excellent tool to record transactions between two parties efficiently and in a verifiable, distributed and permanent way. In addition, the blockchain itself can also be programmed to execute transactions automatically.</span><span class=\"apple-converted-space\" style=\"font-family: Verdana; font-size: 9pt; letter-spacing: 0.02px;\">&nbsp;</span></p>\r\n<p style=\"background: white; font-variant-caps: normal; orphans: auto; text-align: start; widows: auto; -webkit-text-size-adjust: auto; -webkit-text-stroke-width: 0px; word-spacing: 0px;\"><span style=\"letter-spacing: 0.02px;\">As the cloud computing architecture includes several modules that requires accounting and traceability (e.g. user and activity management, billing system, transaction processing, etc.), the blockchain technology could be a good option to provide such capabilities.&nbsp;</span></p>\r\n<p><strong style=\"letter-spacing: 0.02px;\"><span style=\"letter-spacing: 0.02px;\">Goal</span></strong></p>\r\n<p><span style=\"letter-spacing: 0.02px;\">Desing and implement a set of functionalities of the cloud computing architecture by using a blockchain data base.&nbsp;</span></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;<strong style=\"letter-spacing: 0.02px;\"><span style=\"letter-spacing: 0.02px;\">Research&nbsp;</span></strong></p>\r\n<ul type=\"disc\">\r\n<li class=\"MsoNormal\" style=\"color: black; mso-margin-top-alt: auto; mso-margin-bottom-alt: auto; mso-list: l0 level1 lfo1; tab-stops: list 36.0pt; background: white;\"><span style=\"font-size: 9.0pt; font-family: Verdana; mso-fareast-font-family: \'Times New Roman\'; mso-bidi-font-family: \'Times New Roman\';\">Literature study of cloud computing architecture</span></li>\r\n<li class=\"MsoNormal\" style=\"color: black; mso-margin-top-alt: auto; mso-margin-bottom-alt: auto; mso-list: l0 level1 lfo1; tab-stops: list 36.0pt; background: white;\"><span style=\"font-size: 9.0pt; font-family: Verdana; mso-fareast-font-family: \'Times New Roman\'; mso-bidi-font-family: \'Times New Roman\';\">Literature study of blockchain technology</span></li>\r\n<li class=\"MsoNormal\" style=\"color: black; mso-margin-top-alt: auto; mso-margin-bottom-alt: auto; mso-list: l0 level1 lfo1; tab-stops: list 36.0pt; background: white;\"><span style=\"font-size: 9.0pt; font-family: Verdana; mso-fareast-font-family: \'Times New Roman\'; mso-bidi-font-family: \'Times New Roman\';\">Define, design and implement several <span style=\"background: white;\">functionalities of the cloud computing architecture using blockchain technology. </span></span></li>\r\n<li class=\"MsoNormal\" style=\"color: black; mso-margin-top-alt: auto; mso-margin-bottom-alt: auto; mso-list: l0 level1 lfo1; tab-stops: list 36.0pt; background: white;\"><span style=\"font-size: 9.0pt; font-family: Verdana; mso-fareast-font-family: \'Times New Roman\'; mso-bidi-font-family: \'Times New Roman\';\">Evaluate and compare the proposed solution with other well-known approaches.</span></li>\r\n</ul>');
insert into document (documentID, lang, content) values (default, engels, 'New test set for interaction graphs and evaluation of an algorithm','<p><span style=\"letter-spacing: 0.02px;\">Recently the study of so-called interaction graphs, which are graphs in which over time interactions take place, gained a lot of attention in the research community. Examples of such interaction graphs include social networks in which people can post and react to messages, or financial networks in which one party can transfer money to another. Several methods for mining patterns in such networks have been proposed, for instance for searching influential nodes in the network based on the interactions. For the experimental evaluation of these methods usually a number of benchmark datasets from the SNAP repository (https://snap.stanford.edu/snap/) are used. We would like, however, to create new datasets and test existing algorithms on these new datasets. One potential candidate for such a new test dataset could be Reddit (huge set of posts and comments is available for download), or other popular public blogs having archives available.</span></p>\r\n<p>The goal of this assignment is to obtain and process one of these archives and produce multiple training sets from in the format used by the influence maximization algorithms to be tested. For this purpose, the following steps will have to be taken:</p>\r\n<p>- obtain the corpus</p>\r\n<p>- analyze the structure of the corpus</p>\r\n<p>- write a parser</p>\r\n<p>- generate statistics of the data (number of occurrences of keywords, most popular topics, etc)</p>\r\n<p>- generate test sets in the format required for the algorithms to be tested</p>\r\n<p>Once the new test collection is generated, an existing algorithms has to be evaluated and the result of this assessment needs to be cross-checked with already published benchmarking results. The algorithm that has to be analyzed on the new dataset is described in:</p>\r\n<p>Rohit Kumar, Toon Calders: Information Propagation in Interaction Networks. EDBT 2017: 270-281</p>\r\n<p>It concerns the identification of influential nodes in an interaction network based on the notion of an information channel.</p>');
insert into document (documentID, lang, content) values (default, engels, 'Influence propagation in Location-based Social Networks: add influence propagation algo\'s to demo','<p><span style=\"letter-spacing: 0.02px;\">The recent popularity of social networks with geo-tagged activities, so-called location-based social networks (LBSN), resulted in several information propagation and influence maximization mechanisms for applications such as word of mouth marketing (WOMM), and out-of-home marketing (OOH). In order to illustrate our newly developed influence maximization algorithms a demo has been developed called IMaxer (see https://youtu.be/hkj6aAfhYkk), a general and unified system IMaxer that provides a complete pipeline of models and algorithms for influence maximization. IMaxer allows to select and transform the required data from raw LBSN datasets. It provides a unified model that utilizes interactions of nodes in LBSN, i.e., users and locations, for capturing diverse types of information propagations. On the basis of these interactions, influential nodes are found. Finally, IMaxer allows to simulate and visualize the influence spread of the influential nodes.&nbsp;</span></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>The demo, however, is currently in an incomplete state in the sense that only a few existing influence-maximization mechanisms have been implemented. The goal of this assignment is to extend the existing demo (implemented in Java) in the following way:</p>\r\n<p>- add two existing influence maximization algorithms that select the most influential nodes in the network, being:</p>\r\n<p>* (weighted) &nbsp;independent cascade (IC) model</p>\r\n<p>* Linear threshold model</p>\r\n<p>For a description of these models, see:</p>\r\n<p>Shakarian, P., Bhatnagar, A., Aleali, A., Shaabani, E., &amp; Guo, R. (2015). The Independent Cascade and Linear Threshold Models. In Diffusion in Social Networks (pp. 35-48). Springer International Publishing.</p>\r\n<p>- extend the tool with an evaluation dashboard in which a scientifically appropriate experiment to compare different influence maximization algorithms empirically.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>supervisor: Toon Calders</p>');
insert into document (documentID, lang, content) values (default, engels, 'Influence propagation in Location-based Social Networks: improve simulator and interactive browser','<p><span style=\"letter-spacing: 0.02px;\">The recent popularity of social networks with geo-tagged activities, so-called location-based social networks (LBSN), resulted in several information propagation and influence maximization mechanisms for applications such as word of mouth marketing (WOMM), and out-of-home marketing (OOH). In order to illustrate our newly developed influence maximization algorithms a demo has been developed called IMaxer (see https://youtu.be/hkj6aAfhYkk), a general and unified system IMaxer that provides a complete pipeline of models and algorithms for influence maximization. IMaxer allows to select and transform the required data from raw LBSN datasets. It provides a unified model that utilizes interactions of nodes in LBSN, i.e., users and locations, for capturing diverse types of information propagations. On the basis of these interactions, influential nodes are found. Finally, IMaxer allows to simulate and visualize the influence spread of the influential nodes.&nbsp;</span></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>The demo, however, is currently in an incomplete state in the sense that only a few existing influence-maximization mechanisms have been implemented. The goal of this assignment is to extend the existing demo (implemented in Java) in the following way:</p>\r\n<p>- Evaluate and improve the simulation of the influence spread in the demonstrator; base yourself on techniques as described in:</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp; &nbsp; Tang, Youze, Xiaokui Xiao, and Yanchen Shi. \"Influence maximization: Near-optimal time complexity meets practical efficiency.\" Proceedings of the 2014 ACM SIGMOD international conference on Management of data. ACM, 2014.</p>\r\n<p>- Add an interactive component to the tool which allows to browse the result of the influence maximization and to reuse these results in a new influence maximization operation.</p>\r\n<p>Supervisor: Toon Calders</p>');
insert into document (documentID, lang, content) values (default, engels, 'Analyzing electron microscopic images','<p><span style=\"letter-spacing: 0.02px;\">Electron energy loss spectroscopy (EELS) is a technique used to detecting the elemental components of a material. In the physics department a new technique has been developed that can be used to detect deformations and strain in metals based on EELS. As a result high-resolution images are produced which consist of many equally-sized and overlapping circular shapes of different intensities. The goal of this assignment is to find and apply an appropriate combination of image processing and machine learning techniques to analyze these figures and to extract the exact positions of the circular shapes and their relative distances. For this purpose several properties of the images will have to be combined such as the regularity of the positions of the shapes, physical properties of the distribution and the intensity of the shapes and how they interfere, symmetries in the image and regularities in the configuration of the shapes which allows to pool distance measurements in order to reach a highly accurate estimate. Next to the quality of the image recognition, also the runtime performance will be an essential component to optimize.</span></p>');
insert into document (documentID, lang, content) values (default, engels, 'Discrimination-aware data mining: explaining seemingly discriminatory models ','<p><span style=\"letter-spacing: 0.02px;\">This topic is situated in the area of discrimination-aware data mining, also sometimes called fairness-aware data mining. For an introduction into the subject, see for instance:</span></p>\r\n<p>Calders, Toon, and Sicco Verwer. \"Three naive Bayes approaches for discrimination-free classification.\" Data Mining and Knowledge Discovery 21.2 (2010): 277-292.</p>\r\n<p>Custers, B. H. M., et al. \"Discrimination and Privacy in the Information Society, volume 3 of Studies in Applied Philosophy, Epistemology and Rational Ethics.\" (2013).</p>\r\n<p>https://www.dropbox.com/s/zdr3ul46pjndjxy/EGC%20Fairness-Aware%20Data%20Mining.pdf?dl=0</p>\r\n<p>In this area the following problem is studied: given a protected group and a target variable; is it possible to learn a classification model which accurately predicts the target without disadvantaging the protected group? Consider for instance a dataset containing salaries of people for different jobs, years of seniority, eduction, etc. In this dataset there could be traces of a historical gender gap for salaries. A classifier directly trained on this dataset may pickup this bias and as a result systematically assign lower wages to females in the dataset. If, subsequently, the predictions are used for generating a salary proposal for job applicants, the company using this predictor may be accused of illegal gender discrimination.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>Most works in this area have concentrated on either finding proof of discrimination in datasets on the one hand, or learning models that do not discriminate. No existing work, however, considers verifying mined models and finding explanations for discriminations. An example of such an explanation could be, for instance, Simpson\'s paradox (see, e.g., https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Simpson%27s_paradox ; US Berkeley gender case), or the presence of another attribute (such as for instance number of hours worked) correlated with the sensitive attribute which explains the differences in prediction. The goal of this thesis subject is to develop a method that can find such explanations; given a model of which the predictions correlate with a sensitive attribute, find potential explanations.</p>');
insert into document (documentID, lang, content) values (default, engels, 'Cycle detection in interaction graphs','<p>Recently the study of so-called interaction graphs, which are graphs in which over time interactions take place, gained a lot of attention in the research community. Examples of such interaction graphs include social networks in which people can post and react to messages, or financial networks in which one party can transfer money to another. Several methods for mining patterns in such networks have been proposed, for instance for searching influential nodes in the network based on the interactions. One recent work of ours uses the notion of an information channel, which basically is a path in the graph for this purpose:</p>\r\n<p>Rohit Kumar, Toon Calders: Information Propagation in Interaction Networks. EDBT 2017: 270-281</p>\r\n<p>In order to find the number of nodes connected via information channels probabilistic sketching techniques are used to efficiently find approximate solutions. In this thesis topic the goal is to develop a similar method, but now for finding cycles in interaction data. Consider for instance a financial transactions network; a cycle in such network would be a sequence of payments chronological in time of the form: A pays B, B pays C, C pays A. Detecting such cycles could be important to identify fraud. A straightforward solution in which we keep track incrementally for every node which other nodes it can reach is clearly to memory- and time-consuming. Hence an appropriate data structure to approximate cycles will have to be selected and used in a yet-to-be-developed algorithm.</p>');
insert into document (documentID, lang, content) values (default, engels, 'Identifying top-influencers in a financial network','<p>Recently the study of so-called interaction graphs, which is a graph in which over time interactions take place, gained a lot of attention in the research community. Several methods for mining patterns in such networks were proposed, for instance for searching influential nodes in the network based on the interactions. This thesis topic concerns a case study in which payment data between persons will be used to find influencers to target with a marketing campaign. Via a colleague we have access to a real-life data set of 21 million transactions by 1.2 million customers of a major European bank, see:</p>\r\n<p>David Martens, Foster J. Provost, Jessica Clark, and Enric Junqu&eacute; de Fortuny. Mining massive ne-grained behavior data to improve predictive analytics. MIS Quarterly, 40(4):869&ndash;888, 2016.</p>\r\n<p>In previous research such data was used to create links between persons if they made a payment to the same merchant, relational algorithms were applied on the resulting network to predict which persons would be interested in a pension fund product and a long term deposit account. However, the timing of payments was never taken into account. This dataset will be very valuable to find the top-K influencers within the interaction network. These would be the ones to send an advertising offer to. Additionally, we also have 289 other variables describing these customers, from socio-demographics to product usage. This will make for a very interesting analysis of how persons involved in the same pattern (influencer, information diffusion paths, etc) are alike in these 289 other variables.</p>\r\n<p>Promotor: Toon Calders</p>');
insert into document (documentID, lang, content) values (default, engels, 'Handwritten text recognition using machine learning','<p><span style=\"letter-spacing: 0.02px;\">Through a past project we have good contacts with the \"Brabants Historisch Informatie Centrum\"; an institute maintaining and making accessible to the public large amounts of historical documents such as birth, marriage, and death certificates, memories of succession, draft lists, etc. A major problem in making these data available is that they have been recorded hand-written in books. These books are being digitized, which means scanned and stored electronically. Subsequently, volunteers read the texts and create an index (they extract type of certificate, dates, places, people involved). This is a very time-consuming and error-prone process that could easily be improved using automatic tools. The goal of this thesis is the development of tools to render volunteers more efficient. The ultimate, but likely too ambitious goal would be to develop an automatic tool that reads the handwritten texts, extracts all information from it, and enters it into the database. More realistic targets to be considered are the following: - recognize and crop the fields in documents that contain names</span></p>\r\n<p>- given a field with limited options (male/female, age, profession), learn a classifier (for instance based on deep learning) to recognize the contents of this field</p>\r\n<p>A very positive aspect of this assignment is the presence of a lot of labeled data. See for instance: http://www.bhic.nl/onderzoeken/stamboom ; se extended search, and look up certificates of city \"Grave\": https://www.bhic.nl/memorix/genealogy/search?serviceUrl=%2Fgenealogie%2Fq%2Fzoekwijze%2Fs%2Fq%2Fplaats_all_t%2FGrave%3Fapikey%3D0ea60280-55ad-11e2-bcfd-0800200c9a66%26template%3Dxhtml%26form%3Dpersonen%26zoeken%3DStart%2Bzoeken</p>\r\n<p>There you can see several examples of indexed records with the aforementioned scans. However, connecting the names identified by the volunteers with the right part of the scans may still prove the be quite challenging. As can be seen from this description, this assignment is very challenging and exploratory in nature.&nbsp;</p>');
insert into document (documentID, lang, content) values (default, engels, 'Sketch based algorithms: Experimental validation');
insert into document (documentID, lang, content) values (default, engels, 'Design and implementation of a SDN/IoT solution');
insert into document (documentID, lang, content) values (default, engels, 'Profile guided fuzz-testing on large scale applications [Industrial Partner]','<p>Thesis in collaboration with OM Partners NV.</p>\r\n<p>1) Background</p>\r\n<p>Fuzz testing is a testing strategy that can be used to find subtle bugs like the famous Heart bleat bug. The strategy is quite simple: feed the program with semi-random input with as goal to trigger crashes. Nowadays, it is extended with other types of bugs like race conditions, memory overrides and &nbsp;undefined behavior by combining it with tools like Valgrind, Thread sanitizer &hellip; Given the increasing popularity of tooling in C++, it&rsquo;s clear that tools to find bugs are becoming more popular. For fuzz testing, the examples include csmith, AFL, libFuzzer. Google for example recently found 1000 open source bugs.</p>\r\n<p>The challenge with fuzz-testing is the generation of the input. Without an intelligent feed-generator, it mostly generates invalid inputs which are blocked early on, resulting in low code coverage. The existing approaches where applied on small scale libraries and applications.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>2) Assignment</p>\r\n<p>The goal of this thesis would be to design a fuzz testing strategy that is applicable on an industrial application. This includes challenges like evaluating the existing approaches and refining them to the new context. For example: For libFuzzer, a separate executable with a custom conversion function should be written each test case. The conversion function transforms the fuzz data to input for the application. It is clear that this approach does not scale for industrial applications.</p>\r\n<p>The context of the industrial application would be that of OM Partners. At OM Partners we have a large codebase with a combination of isolated generic data structures and algorithms, supporting GUI code and scripting support till very domain specific algorithms which require a variety of correlated inputs and several preconditions.</p>');
insert into document (documentID, lang, content) values (default, engels, 'Design a VR acoustic room in Unity for testing 3D audio ','<p>[Thesis in collaboration with the Active Perception Lab - https://www.uantwerpen.be/en/rg/engineering-management/research-teams/active-perception-la/ ]</p>\r\n<div>1. Context</div>\r\n<p>Virtual and augmented reality are currently booming, but the focus has been mainly on the visual aspect, despite the widespread recognition of the importance of 3D audio for increased immersion. However, in order to find its way to the general public, 3D audio technology needs to clear one major hurdle, a problem that has been around for the past 20 years: it needs personalization to work well, because everyone&rsquo;s ear and head shape are unique. Ideally, one&rsquo;s unique way of hearing the world in 3D (encoded in the so-called head-<span style=\"letter-spacing: 0.02px;\">related transfer function or HRTF) is measured in a sophisticated laboratory, which is not feasible on a large scale.</span></p>\r\n<p>2. Project</p>\r\n<p>In the Active Perception Lab, we have developed a method to determine the HRTF in a home environment. A problem is to investigate the quality of the measured HRTFs, since nowadays sound engines do not allow uploading your personal HRTF. For this reason, we are ourselves building a VR test environment (Unity based), which provides this possibility. In this project, you will improve the realism of the virtual test environment in our laboratory. You will design a virtual room in which multiple independent sound sources, each having their own frequency dependent radiation pattern, can be positioned/oriented and simulate all the relevant acoustics in real-time. You will consider the direct path, first order reflections on the walls, floor and ceiling, and include distance attenuation. The user will be able to walk in the room and experience this room through his own ears (i.e. using his own HRTF).</p>');
insert into document (documentID, lang, content) values (default, engels, 'Deep learning for mass spectra identification validation');
insert into document (documentID, lang, content) values (default, engels, 'Empirical Study on Cross-Project Code Clones','<h2>Introduction</h2>\r\n<p><span style=\"letter-spacing: 0.02px;\">Fragments of code which are exactly the same as or similar to each other are called code clones. These clones can appear unintentionally throughout software evolution due to several reasons, such as the use of design patterns, frameworks, and similar API&rsquo;s. Generally, they are investigated on a project level, looking into their cause, their impact on development and methods to remove them. In this study, however, we want to investigate code clones that appear in multiple projects. Code clone patterns that appear in multiple projects can indicate a possibility to extend the standard library or even the language itself.</span></p>\r\n<p><span style=\"letter-spacing: 0.02px;\">The goal of this research project is to identify cross-project code clones in order to find gaps in the language standard library.</span></p>\r\n<h2><span style=\"letter-spacing: 0.02px;\">Details</span></h2>\r\n<p><span style=\"letter-spacing: 0.02px;\">In this research project, the student has to perform a large-scale data mining experiment in order to find cross-project clones. During the development of the research project, the student will improve his/her knowledge of:</span></p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li><span style=\"letter-spacing: 0.02px;\">Code Clone Detection</span></li>\r\n<li><span style=\"letter-spacing: 0.02px;\">The BOA repository (A Language and Infrastructure for Analyzing Ultra-Large Scale Software Repositories) [ <a href=\"http://boa.cs.iastate.edu%20\" target=\"_blank\">http://boa.cs.iastate.edu </a>]</span></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<h2><span style=\"letter-spacing: 0.02px;\">Requirements</span></h2>\r\n<p><span style=\"letter-spacing: 0.02px;\">The skills required for this research project are:</span></p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li><span style=\"letter-spacing: 0.02px;\">&nbsp;Good programming skills.</span></li>\r\n<li><span style=\"letter-spacing: 0.02px;\">&nbsp;Prior knowledge on or experience with code clones would be useful.</span></li>\r\n</ul>');
insert into document (documentID, lang, content) values (default, engels, 'Using Bioinformatics Techniques for Code Clone Detection');
insert into document (documentID, lang, content) values (default, engels, 'Life science multi-label graph classification');
insert into document (documentID, lang, content) values (default, engels, 'Subgraph visualisation tool with 3d.js','<p>Various tools exist to find the common subgraphs within a database of graphs. The goal of this project will be to create a tool with the 3d.js framework that can visualize the output of such tools, to show the subgraphs, and, if possible, to visualize the presence or absence of the subgraph within the original graph sets.</p>');
insert into document (documentID, lang, content) values (default, engels, 'Viral protein life-cycle prediction');
insert into document (documentID, lang, content) values (default, engels, 'TCR sequence data mining','<p>Recently it has become possible to characterize the DNA sequence of a large population of immune cells (T-cells) from blood. This has resulted in the creation of large databases containing T-cell information collected from various biological experiments.</p>\r\n<p>Not many data mining initiatives are active on this data source as it is still very new, yet these techniques are very promising. The goal of this project will be to analyze a large subset of T-cell data from a public resource using state-of-the-art data mining techniques.</p>');
insert into document (documentID, lang, content) values (default, engels, 'Predicting protein-protein interactions between pathogens and their hosts','<p id=\"docs-internal-guid-77faee1d-e773-80d7-6995-b719d35b5489\" style=\"line-height: 1.38; margin-top: 0pt; margin-bottom: 0pt; text-align: justify;\" dir=\"ltr\"><span style=\"font-size: 11pt; font-family: Arial; color: #000000; background-color: transparent; font-weight: 400; font-style: normal; font-variant: normal; text-decoration: none; vertical-align: baseline;\">At the molecular level pathogens interact with their host via protein-protein interactions. These molecular interactions govern the different stages of infection, disease progression and represent a constant arms-race between the host and the pathogen, which tries to evade and manipulate the molecular machinery of the host. Understanding protein-protein interactions is crucial for gaining insight into diseases and ultimately treating them. </span></p>\r\n<p style=\"line-height: 1.38; margin-top: 0pt; margin-bottom: 0pt; text-align: justify;\" dir=\"ltr\"><span style=\"font-size: 11pt; font-family: Arial; color: #000000; background-color: transparent; font-weight: 400; font-style: normal; font-variant: normal; text-decoration: none; vertical-align: baseline;\"><br /></span></p>\r\n<p style=\"line-height: 1.38; margin-top: 0pt; margin-bottom: 0pt; text-align: justify;\" dir=\"ltr\"><span style=\"font-size: 11pt; font-family: Arial; color: #000000; background-color: transparent; font-weight: 400; font-style: normal; font-variant: normal; text-decoration: none; vertical-align: baseline;\">In this project the student will attempt to build a machine learning model to predict whether two given proteins will interact. Depending on the time and interest of the student, several different avenues could be explored, e.g. relying on previously published research and text mining to train the model or utilising sequence information and additional biological features to build a classifier.</span></p>');
insert into document (documentID, lang, content) values (default, engels, 'Deep learning applied to graph drawing and network visualisation');
insert into document (documentID, lang, content) values (default, engels, 'Reverse Engineer Google Wi-Fi','<p>Google Wi-Fi is a new product from Google. It&rsquo;s a home Wi-Fi system that aims to provide reliable Wi-Fi coverage in every corner of your home. It basically replaces your home router. The main idea is that you can have multiple Google Wi-Fi boxes, that then seamlessly interconnect and in that way extend the Wi-Fi signal coverage in your home. Additionally, it has a set of interesting features, such as seamless mobility, network assisted channel selection, etc.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>Google advertises that Google Wi-Fi is capable of a lot of interesting features (such as mesh, channel selection, handovers, band steering, etc.), however, there are no technical details on how it actually accomplishes these features.&nbsp;<span style=\"letter-spacing: 0.02px;\">As a student, you will get access to the Google Wi-Fi product and your goal is to reverse engineer it, in order to explain how the different features of Google Wi-Fi are implemented and accomplished.</span></p>\r\n<p><span style=\"letter-spacing: 0.02px;\"><br /></span></p>\r\n<div>For more detailed information, please visit the document:</div>\r\n<div>https://docs.google.com/document/d/1YlECRAGD0zOanzFizUbqiNHIZwrYzmMXOnSrieISLck/edit?usp=sharing</div>');
insert into document (documentID, lang, content) values (default, engels, 'Implementation of a controller to manage heterogeneous networks','<p>LAN are employed by a plethora of heterogeneous consumer devices, equipped with the ability to connect to the Internet using a variety of different wireless network technologies.&nbsp;<span style=\"letter-spacing: 0.02px;\">Existing solutions and the lower layers of the OSI stack are unfit to cope with this heterogeneity.&nbsp;</span><span style=\"letter-spacing: 0.02px;\">For instance, dynamical inter-technology switching is user- or application-based. Therefore, we have proposed a novel virtual MAC solution that&nbsp;</span><span style=\"letter-spacing: 0.02px;\">introduces capabilities such as packet-level dynamic and intelligent handovers (both inter- and intra-technology), load balancing, replication, and scheduling.&nbsp;</span><span style=\"letter-spacing: 0.02px;\">However, to manage all the virtual MACs across the network a controller is needed.</span></p>\r\n<p>The goal of this internship is to implement this controller. Key features that have to be implemented are an efficient storage of gathered monitoring information, the communication with existing SDN controllers, and the distribution of controllers. These features have to be implemented while taking into account multiple processes and threads and using Python 3.</p>');
insert into document (documentID, lang, content) values (default, engels, 'Interactive raw pattern mining','<p class=\"p1\">Pattern mining is a discipline in data mining that aims to extract knowledge from data in&nbsp;<span style=\"letter-spacing: 0.02px;\">the form of patterns. An example pattern is an association of elements. Such a pattern&nbsp;</span><span style=\"letter-spacing: 0.02px;\">shows which combination elements show a positive/negative correlation to one another.&nbsp;</span><span style=\"letter-spacing: 0.02px;\">Another type of pattern are association rules. Such patterns can define a probability that&nbsp;</span><span style=\"letter-spacing: 0.02px;\">if some elements occur, there is a x% change that some other elements will also occur.</span><span style=\"letter-spacing: 0.02px;\">&nbsp;</span></p>\r\n<p class=\"p1\">SNIPER is a web based tool for interactive pattern discovery. Patterns that can be found&nbsp;<span style=\"letter-spacing: 0.02px;\">using SNIPER are associations, association rules and exceptional models. In order to find&nbsp;</span><span style=\"letter-spacing: 0.02px;\">such patterns a transactional data set has transformed to a binary data set. In this process&nbsp;</span><span style=\"letter-spacing: 0.02px;\">numerical attributes are converted to binary data by splitting the data in intervals, also&nbsp;</span><span style=\"letter-spacing: 0.02px;\">called discretization. The choice of a solid discretization for a given attribute is often a&nbsp;</span><span style=\"letter-spacing: 0.02px;\">challenging, yet, very important task in the knowledge discovery process. That is, a bad&nbsp;</span><span style=\"letter-spacing: 0.02px;\">discretization may completely hide a pattern from the data.</span></p>\r\n<p class=\"p2\"><span style=\"letter-spacing: 0.02px;\">One of the main features in SNIPER is the best pattern extension. This features interactively&nbsp;</span><span style=\"letter-spacing: 0.02px;\">shows the element that maximizes the quality of a pattern when adding a single element.&nbsp;</span><span style=\"letter-spacing: 0.02px;\">In the current implementation of SNIPER, the elements consist of discretized elements&nbsp;</span><span style=\"letter-spacing: 0.02px;\">from the data. In this project you explore the possibility to aid interactive pattern discovery&nbsp;</span><span style=\"letter-spacing: 0.02px;\">without prior discretization of the data, rather we want to take on a similar approach to ID3&nbsp;</span><span style=\"letter-spacing: 0.02px;\">and support on-the-fly discretization of data when interactively constructing patterns. To&nbsp;</span><span style=\"letter-spacing: 0.02px;\">this end you will study different discretization techniques and incorporate a novel on-the-fly&nbsp;</span><span style=\"letter-spacing: 0.02px;\">discretization mechanism in SNIPER.</span></p>\r\n<p class=\"p2\"><span style=\"letter-spacing: 0.02px;\">Internship Tasks:</span><span style=\"letter-spacing: 0.02px;\">&nbsp;</span></p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>study discretization techniques</li>\r\n<li>research novel technique for on-the-fly discretization</li>\r\n<li>implement novel technique in SNIPER</li>\r\n<li>present your findings in head-to-head discussions</li>\r\n<li>write an academic report on your findings</li>\r\n</ul>');
insert into document (documentID, lang, content) values (default, engels, 'Predicting user behaviour','<p class=\"p1\"><span style=\"letter-spacing: 0.02px;\">Pattern mining is a discipline in data mining that aims to extract knowledge from data in&nbsp;</span><span style=\"letter-spacing: 0.02px;\">the form of patterns. An example pattern is an association of elements. Such a pattern&nbsp;</span><span style=\"letter-spacing: 0.02px;\">shows which combination elements show a positive/negative correlation to one another.&nbsp;</span><span style=\"letter-spacing: 0.02px;\">Another type of pattern are association rules. Such patterns can define a probability that&nbsp;</span><span style=\"letter-spacing: 0.02px;\">if some elements occur, there is a x% change that some other elements will also occur.</span></p>\r\n<p class=\"p2\"><span style=\"letter-spacing: 0.02px;\">SNIPER is a web based tool for interactive pattern discovery. The main idea is to integrate&nbsp;</span><span style=\"letter-spacing: 0.02px;\">the user deeply into the process of finding interesting patterns because she excels in&nbsp;</span><span style=\"letter-spacing: 0.02px;\">distinguishing interesting from non-interesting patterns. Patterns that can be found using&nbsp;</span><span style=\"letter-spacing: 0.02px;\">SNIPER are associations, association rules and exceptional models. The main aim of our&nbsp;</span><span style=\"letter-spacing: 0.02px;\">tool is being a highly interactive. Therefore, every user action or input should result in&nbsp;</span><span style=\"letter-spacing: 0.02px;\">quick response times and low latency. Depending on the data however some actions&nbsp;</span><span style=\"letter-spacing: 0.02px;\">can have a long execution time, decreasing the interactivity.</span></p>\r\n<p class=\"p2\"><span style=\"letter-spacing: 0.02px;\">In this internships your task is to study techniques for analysing user behaviour and&nbsp;</span><span style=\"letter-spacing: 0.02px;\">predicting what a user will do next in order to prefetch or start precomputing information&nbsp;</span><span style=\"letter-spacing: 0.02px;\">that will be requested later during the search process.</span></p>\r\n<p class=\"p2\"><span style=\"letter-spacing: 0.02px;\">Internship Tasks:</span></p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>study user behaviour techniques</li>\r\n<li>research novel technique for detecting what a user will click next</li>\r\n<li>implement novel technique in SNIPER</li>\r\n<li>present your findings in head-to-head discussions</li>\r\n<li>write an academic report on your findings</li>\r\n</ul>');
insert into document (documentID, lang, content) values (default, engels, 'Creating resilient networks using machine learning ','<p>Nowadays, large scale networks (e.g. cloud data centers) can generate a huge amount of data related to network management. In general, only a small part of this data is processed and used for the network administrator to detect network failures or, in the worst case, it is not used at all. One way to use this data is in reactive algorithms: once a failure is detected, the algorithm performs an operation to recover the network in short time. But what if we use all the data to predict failures before they happen?</p>\r\n<p>This thesis has 3 main goals: 1) write a state-of-the-art of techniques to predict failures in networks. 2) design and implement a Deep Learning algorithm to predict the network failures based on historical network management data. 3) evaluate and compare its results against other well-known techniques for failure detection in networks.</p>');
insert into document (documentID, lang, content) values (default, engels, 'Evaluating and comparing state-of-art reinforcement learning algorithms','<p>In the last 20 years, several reinforcement learning algorithms have been proposed. However, most of the work done to compare and evaluate them is completely qualitative or include just a few algorithms. In real test scenarios, different aspects such as the state and action space, convergence time, reward function, etc., would be useful for selecting the right algorithm.</p>\r\n<p><span lang=\"EN-US\">This thesis has 3 main goals:</span></p>\r\n<p><span lang=\"EN-US\">1)&nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;</span><span lang=\"EN-US\">Write a state-of-art of reinforcement learning algorithms.</span></p>\r\n<p><span lang=\"EN-US\">2)&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</span><span lang=\"EN-US\">Design and implement a framework to evaluate and compare reinforcement learning&nbsp;algorithms.</span></p>\r\n<p><span lang=\"EN-US\">3)Implement several reinforcement learning algorithms and evaluate them using the&nbsp;framework implemented in 2).&nbsp;</span></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>');
insert into document (documentID, lang, content) values (default, engels, 'Policy-based TSCH scheduling','<p><span lang=\"EN-GB\">In recent years, the number of sensors connected&nbsp;</span><span lang=\"EN-GB\">to the Internet has increased tremendously. These sensors typically connect to Internet via Wireless Sensor Networks (WSNs). WSNs are often deployed in industrial areas, for predictive maintenance and remote monitoring services. Two key challenges related to the deployment of WSNs in these environments are 1) the power-constrained nature of the connected devices/sensors and 2) the high interference levels encountered.</span>&nbsp;<span lang=\"EN-US\">To overcome these issues, WSNs often employ&nbsp;</span><span lang=\"EN-GB\">Time-Slotted Channel Hopping (TSCH), for two reasons</span><span lang=\"EN-US\">. First, channel hopping effectively&nbsp;</span><span lang=\"EN-GB\">increases the link reliability and minimizes the effects of external interference and/or multi-path fading, by randomizing the frequency channel on which a packet is transmitted. Second, a time-synchronized schedule specifies in which slots the nodes transmit and receive packets. This schedule reduces energy consumption by avoiding collisions and by enabling radios only when arriving packets are expected. An open research question is how to effectively generate a transmission schedule in a distributed way.</span></p>\r\n<p align=\"center\"><img src=\"https://student.idlab.uantwerpen.be/~gdaneels/6PSchedule_towc_cropped.jpg\" alt=\"Example of simple TSCH schedule.\" width=\"520\" height=\"204\" /></p>\r\n<p>In this research project, we will exploit the fact that WSN applications are characterized by the periodical transmission of sensor data.&nbsp; State-of-the art TSCH scheduling approaches typically do not exploit this periodic behavior. By only activating time TSCH time slots at the exact moment sensor traffic is expected, using a &ldquo;periodical, daisy-chained reservation&rdquo; from the originating node towards a network sink, transmitting data becomes highly efficient, avoids wasting energy and achieves low latencies. Scheduling of such &ldquo;periodical reservations&rdquo; in large sensor networks among hundreds of nodes is complex as scheduling of one flow impacts the scheduling possibilities of the other flows. Moreover, the scheduling must be performed by the sensor nodes in a distributed way, where the messaging overhead is kept to an absolute minimum.&nbsp; The goal of this thesis is twofold 1) to research if enforcing scheduling policies on sensor nodes can improve network performance 2) implement your schedule policy solution in the state-of-the-art TSCH simulator. This thesis allows you to be creative in the development of algorithms and provides you with the satisfaction to see your algorithms&ldquo; come to live&rdquo; in a real-world context.</p>');
insert into document (documentID, lang, content) values (default, engels, 'TSCH scheduling in industrial areas','<p><span lang=\"EN-GB\">Predictive maintenance, remote monitoring of machinery, real-time communication between employees, etc. are all crucial for efficient operation and management of large industrial sites. To this end, wireless connectivity is nowadays almost ubiquitously present. However, many&nbsp;challenging&nbsp;indoor industrial areas still lack coverage, often due to the presence of large blocking metal constructions&nbsp;such as ship compartments, remote control rooms of factories and individual stacked containers in large storage areas. These metal constructions contribute to&nbsp;increased levels of multi-path interference&nbsp;which troubles wireless communication. Connecting these areas is crucial to be able to provide critical industrial services and act upon emergency situations in a timely manner.</span></p>\r\n<p><span lang=\"EN-GB\"><span lang=\"EN-GB\">To tackle the challenges of indoor industrial areas, a&nbsp;IEEE 802.15.4e Time-Slotted Channel Hopping (TSCH)&nbsp;network can be employed. In such TSCH multi-hop networks each node follows a power-efficient schedule that tells the node exactly when to transmit/receive and on which frequency channel. Managing the different TX/RX slots in such a schedule is done by a scheduling function.</span>&nbsp;</span></p>\r\n<p><span style=\"letter-spacing: 0.02px;\" lang=\"EN-GB\">Many of such scheduling functions already exist, but none support the stringent QoS requirements for an indoor industrial setting (while meeting strict duty cycling EU regulations). Your tasks will be to 1) look into existing and promising TSCH scheduling functions that can provide the necessary QoS and 2) investigate different ideas (e.g., varying the time slot length to support different MCS schemes) to extend TSCH to cope with the problematic industrial interference.&nbsp;&nbsp;Therefore, the&nbsp;goal of this thesis is to research a new scheduling function that provides the necessary QoS while enduring the challenging industrial multi-path interference</span><span style=\"letter-spacing: 0.02px;\" lang=\"EN-GB\">. This thesis will give you the opportunity to immersive yourself in cutting-edge, power-constrained wireless networking research.</span></p>');
insert into document (documentID, lang, content) values (default, engels, 'Optimizing 6TiSCH performance in the sub-1GHz band','<p>The Internet-of-Things revolution is based upon the premise of having a plethora of everyday devices being online and sharing information over the Internet. Many of those devices are sensors, such as temperature sensors, humidity sensors, gyroscopes or cameras. However, the range of the radios attached to these sensors often only function in the 2.4 GHz frequency band, resulting in a limited connectivity range. This implies that more nodes have to be deployed to hop the sensor data across the network which is 1) more energy-intensive (which has to be avoided in a power-constrained network) setting and 2) driving up the deployment and maintainability costs. In order to tackle these challenges, the connectivity range should be increased as much as possible. A favorable solution is to communicate in the sub-1GHz frequency band.</p>\r\n<p>The goal of the thesis/internship is to study and develop different possibilities to improve the performance of the 6TiSCH network stack in the sub-1GHZ frequency band.6TiSCH is the key technology to enable the integration of IPv6 with the Time-Slotted Channel Hopping (TSCH) IEEE 802.15.4 MAC layer mode. Using a time-slotted schedule and randomizing the channels in which data is transmitted, TSCH enables low-power operation and high-reliable links in industrial (sensor) networks. Recently, a working sub-1GHz implementation was developed to increase the range of 6TiSCH networks and thus further refines the effectiveness of these networks.</p>\r\n<p>However, that implementation was only the first step and needs improvement. Possibilities are enabling multi-channel hopping in the 868 MHz band and adding IEEE 802.15.4g headers. This will be implemented and tested through a set of field tests in outdoors environments. Using those results, a comparison will be done in order to choose the hardware and software configuration that results in longer connectivity distances.</p>\r\n<p>Hardware and low-level software skills are highly recommended.</p>');
insert into document (documentID, lang, content) values (default, engels, 'Implementation and evaluation of 60GHz handovers','<p><span lang=\"EN-US\">To meet the growing demand for increased traffic over wireless technologies, different new Wi-Fi standards have been proposed and these technologies are beginning to become available for the pubic. One of these technologies is 60 GHz Wi-Fi (802.11ad). This technology operates in a much higher frequency then the traditional WI-Fi (2.4 and 5 GHz band) and allows to transmit very high volumes of data (like video streams). Due to the fact that multiple directed antennas are being used, the technology lacks mobility. If a user device is receiving a beam from the AP, it will lose connectivity as it moves outside of the small range of the beam. These specific characteristics urge the need for algorithms that, for instance, decide when to send a beam to a device or when to use this new technology instead of the traditional Wi-Fi</span>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p><span lang=\"EN-US\">The goal of this thesis is the implementation and evaluation of the 60GHz standard in the NS-3 simulator. Currently an unofficial implementation exists, but this implementation is unstable and not complete. Therefore, this implementation needs to be improved or a new implementation can be made from scratch. A main focus during this thesis will be on the performance of handovers between 2.4 and 5 GHz Wi-Fi (ac/n) and the 60 GHz Wi-Fi. This is a non-trivial problem because of the limited mobility supported by the 60 GHz technology.&nbsp;</span></p>');
insert into document (documentID, lang, content) values (default, engels, 'Optimizing the energy efficiency of Wi-Fi HaLow for the IoT','<p><span lang=\"EN-US\">Traditional Wi-Fi is not very suited for the Internet of Things (IoT), as it has a short range, is not very energy efficient, and only supports a dozen devices per access point. Aiming to address this gap, the new IEEE 802.11ah standard, marketed as Wi-Fi HaLow, was finished in early 2017 supporting connectivity of up to 8000 power-constrained stations to a single access point with a range of up to 1 km. Since HaLow is quite a new wireless technology, companies are still working on the implementation of the hardware and currently doing research based on network simulation to decide the best hardware-design choices.</span></p>\r\n<p><span lang=\"EN-US\">Our group is the first to have implemented HaLow in simulation and made it available as open source for other researchers to experiment with. However, there&rsquo;re still some important features missing, such as TWT (Target Wake up Time). TWT allows stations that rarely transmit data to reduce power consumption by letting them to sleep for hours, days or even years between transmissions. The goal of this project is to implement the TWT feature in our open source HaLow module based on the ns-3 network simulator. For a master thesis, the implementation can be further used to design an optimization algorithm that manages TWT in combination with other energy efficiency features. This project will give you the opportunity to work with a radically new wireless technology and gain in-depth knowledge about the inner-workings of Wi-Fi protocol);
insert into document (documentID, lang, content) values (default, engels, 'Hierarchical Sequence Memory','<p><span lang=\"EN-US\">In artificial intelligence, the ability to recognize and predict temporal sequences is an important building block. Current state-of-the-art systems typically use some variant of an LSTM (Long Short Term Memory) neural network. Based on new insights in the human neocortex, Hierarchical Temporal Memory (HTM) is claimed as an alternative with better overall performance.<br />However, there have been very few independent assessments of the properties and capabilities of HTM, as well as thorough and objective experimental comparisons with LSTM networks.</span></p>\r\n<p><span lang=\"EN-US\">The thesis consists of 2 parts:</span></p>\r\n<p><span lang=\"EN-US\">(1)&nbsp;&nbsp;</span><span lang=\"EN-US\">a theoretical analysis of the main properties of HTM, and possible definition of extensions or variants</span></p>\r\n<p><span lang=\"EN-US\">(2)&nbsp;&nbsp;</span><span lang=\"EN-US\">an experimental comparison of HTM and LSTM models, in a selected use case</span></p>\r\n<p><span lang=\"EN-US\">Starting from an in-depth literature study of HTM, the thesis will require a mathematical analysis of its learning and generalization properties, possibly own extensions and implementation, and the use of existing HTM and LSTM SW implementations.</span></p>');
insert into document (documentID, lang, content) values (default, engels, 'Multi-technology and multi-technique wireless indoor localization');
insert into document (documentID, lang, content) values (default, engels, 'Enabling SDN capabilities in heterogeneous 6LoWPAN networks','<p><span lang=\"EN-US\">Fine-grain control is a concept that is becoming predominant in most of the network solutions in order to efficiently provide QoS in dynamic and large scale modern computing environments, optimizing flows and adjusting the resources to the instantaneous demand.</span></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p><span lang=\"EN-US\">However this is difficult to achieve in low power networks due to they are highly resource constrained. Current solutions point towards SDN (Software Defined Networks) however applying SDN in IoT network is challenging. One of the most promising approaches to tackle this is Fibbing.</span></p>\r\n<p><span lang=\"EN-US\"><span lang=\"EN-US\">The goal of the thesis/internship is to study and design different possibilities for, in a Fibbing-based architecture, communicate the network controller with different types of IoT networks such as 6TiSCH, DASH7, LTE, Sigfox, Lora. The design will be done according the requirements of a high-interference and noisy environment and for supporting heterogeneous links, differentiating QoS and providing a lightweight SDN-based solution.</span>&nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;</span></p>');
insert into document (documentID, lang, content) values (default, engels, 'Optimizing mobile networks for IoT devices using NB-IoT','<p><span lang=\"EN-US\">Several low-power wide area networks (LPWAN) exist using both licensed and unlicensed spectrum. 3GPP (telecommunications standard development organizations) has proposed a new radio technology standard Narrow-band IoT (NB-IoT) that has been developed to enable a wide range of IoT devices and things to be connected using the same long-term evolution (LTE) system used by smartphones today. The battery life and data transfer latency are the major concerns for these applications. IoT sensors mostly remain in sleep mode to save battery (no data exchange) and for data transfer they need to connect with the base station (wake-up state), which consumes battery.</span>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p><span lang=\"EN-US\">The goal of this work is to develop new mechanism for data transfer directly in the sleep mode, i.e. without changing the sensor state. The proposed solution should be implemented in the ns-3 network simulator. Moreover, as we are collaborating with Orange on this topic, validation can be done with real hardware using the Orange NB-IoT network. In case this topic is chosen as an internship, focus can be on the implementation and validation of our previously developed schemes, while for a master thesis further optimization and research can be done to improve them.</span></p>\r\n<p><span lang=\"EN-US\">About us: We are closely working with telecom operator Orange who provides us with NB-IoT enabled base-station access.</span></p>\r\n<p><span lang=\"EN-US\">Gain: This project will give you the opportunity to gain in-depth knowledge about the NB-IoT technology, LTE protocols, NS-3 Simulator, and research-based work.</span></p>\r\n<p><span lang=\"EN-US\">Expectation: C++ knowledge, NS3 simulator (plus)</span></p>');
insert into document (documentID, lang, content) values (default, engels, 'Optimizing 6LoWPAN networks','<p><span lang=\"EN-US\">Fine-grain control is a concept that is becoming predominant in most of the network solutions in order to efficiently provide QoS in dynamic and large scale modern computing environments, optimizing flows and adjusting the resources to the instantaneous demand.</span></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p><span lang=\"EN-US\">However this is difficult to achieve in low power networks due to they are highly resource constrained. Current solutions point towards SDN (Software Defined Networks) however applying SDN in IoT network is challenging.</span></p>\r\n<p><span lang=\"EN-US\"><span lang=\"EN-US\">The goal of the thesis/internship is to study and implement algorithms that find the optimal configuration for accomplishing a set of policies in a given IoT network using the Fibbing principles. For this, a set of input information will be given from a monitoring tool and different heuristics or exact algorithms will be studied and implemented in order to give the optimal configuration for providing the required QoS.</span>&nbsp; &nbsp;</span></p>');
insert into document (documentID, lang, content) values (default, engels, 'Predicting latency in heavily interfered wireless networks','<p><span lang=\"EN-US\">Wireless networks, especially IEEE 802.11, are used in a plethora of scenarios, ranging from small home networks to large-scale events like conferences and festivals. Particularly, in scenarios with a high number of stations, interference may decline the performance significantly. However, interference is not only caused by other IEEE 802.11 stations, as non-IEEE 802.11 sources, such as microwaves, screens or Radio Frequency (RF) equipment, generate interference as well, especially if they are not well shielded. This leads to high latency, which in turn leads to a bad user experience as Quality of Service requirements cannot be guaranteed anymore.</span>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p><span lang=\"EN-US\">To tackle this issue, predicting the latency for the near-term future and for different interfering sources is of utmost importance. In this thesis, you will research and implement several machine learning algorithms to predict latency under different conditions. The goal is to reach a high enough precision to use the prediction in dynamic network planning.</span>&nbsp;&nbsp;</p>');
insert into document (documentID, lang, content) values (default, engels, 'Distributed SDN controller for heterogeneous wireless networks','<p><span lang=\"EN-US\">Networks consist of a variety of heterogonous devices, wireless and wired, with multiple technologies. Currently, each technology and type of device is either managed by its own framework or not managed at all. To enable advanced functionality, for example utilizing multiple technologies at once, a more holistic approach is necessary that can combine monitoring information from different technologies and enables a complete overview over the network.&nbsp;</span></p>\r\n<p><span lang=\"EN-US\">A new type of distributed SDN controller that manages an arbitrary number of technologies and devices can fully utilize the capacity of the network. Therefore, you will research and implement techniques for communication, data storage, reliability, and availability. The goal is a full implementation of a distributed SDN controller that can manage multiple technologies.</span>&nbsp;&nbsp;</p>');
insert into document (documentID, lang, content) values (default, engels, 'Target Propagation for Deep Neural Networks','<p><span lang=\"EN-US\">Deep neural networks have achieved great successes, mostly relying on back-propagation (BP) as the mechanism for learning connection weights. However, the lack of biological plausibility and some computational aspects have triggered investigations in other learning mechanisms for deep neural networks. A promising and notable class of proposals are target-propagation methods (TP, DTP, SDTP).<br />However, first (partial) results indicate that while SDTP is competitive with BP for medium size networks, TP performs worse than BP for larger networks. Clear understanding of TP-methods is still lacking, and only limited experiments have been performed.</span></p>\r\n<p><span lang=\"EN-US\">The thesis will compare TP and BP learning mechanisms for deep neural network on theoretical and experimental basis:</span></p>\r\n<p><span lang=\"EN-US\">1)&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</span><span lang=\"EN-US\">Crisply list the assumptions, properties, and operational aspects of BP and TP for adapting connection weights</span></p>\r\n<p><span lang=\"EN-US\">2)&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</span><span lang=\"EN-US\">Analyse type of learning problems, network architectures, or computational characteristics where target-propagation mechanisms could work better.</span></p>\r\n<p><span lang=\"EN-US\">3)&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</span><span lang=\"EN-US\">Possibly define an own TP variant for specific problems or architectures</span></p>\r\n<p><span lang=\"EN-US\">Run experiments to verify the assessments of (1) &ndash; (3) above.</span></p>');
insert into document (documentID, lang, content) values (default, engels, 'Modelling a fibbing-based API for 6LoWPAN networks','<p><span lang=\"EN-US\">Fine-grain control is a concept that is becoming predominant in most of the network solutions in order to efficiently provide QoS in dynamic and large scale modern computing environments, optimizing flows and adjusting the resources to the instantaneous demand.</span></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p><span lang=\"EN-US\">However this is difficult to achieve in low power networks due to they are highly resource constrained. Current solutions point towards SDN (Software Defined Networks) however applying SDN in IoT network is challenging. One of the most promising approaches to tackle this is Fibbing.</span></p>\r\n<p><span lang=\"EN-US\"><span lang=\"EN-US\">The goal of the thesis/internship is to study different possibilities for, in a Fibbing-based architecture, communicate the controller with the operator nodes. According to these studies, an interface will be implemented in both the controller and the operator nodes in order to perform the required actions and primitives in the network issued by the controller in programmable and flexible way.</span>&nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;</span></p>');
insert into document (documentID, lang, content) values (default, engels, 'Design and implement YANG/COMI models for 6LoWPAN networks','<p><span lang=\"EN-US\">Fine-grain control is a concept that is becoming predominant in most of the network solutions in order to efficiently provide QoS in dynamic and large scale modern computing environments, optimizing flows and adjusting the resources to the instantaneous demand.</span></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p><span lang=\"EN-US\">However this is difficult to achieve in low power networks due to they are highly resource constrained. Current solutions point towards SDN (Software Defined Networks) however applying SDN in IoT network is challenging.</span></p>\r\n<p><span lang=\"EN-US\">The goal of the thesis/internship is to study the different existing implementation of YANG/COMI for 6LoWPAN networks and implement new possible modules for gather network information in the different planes (routing, scheduling, phy). This would include how to share rank information in RPL, schedules in the 6top layer of 6Tisch and the neighbor relation between nodes in the physical layer.&nbsp;</span></p>');
insert into document (documentID, lang, content) values (default, engels, 'Creating resilient networks using machine learning - location prediction');
insert into document (documentID, lang, content) values (default, engels, 'Multipath TCP in NS-3 network simulator','<p><span lang=\"EN-US\">Multipath TCP (MPTCP) is a TCP extension that enables the transmission and reception of data concurrently over multiple network interfaces. Multiple regular TCP connections, denoted as subflows, are combined into a single MPTCP connection, while each subflow can follow a different path. As it is being used by industry, it is highly relevant for multi-technology wireless research. However, the most advanced network simulator NS-3 currently has no official implementation of MTPCP. Some implementations have been developed by individual research, however only for older versions of the NS-3 network simulator.</span></p>\r\n<p><span lang=\"EN-US\">The goal of this thesis is the implementation and evaluation of MPTCP in the latest version of the NS-3 simulator. It is possible to start from an existing older implementation. Furthermore, NS-3 coding guidelines need to be respected to allow for a possible future integration with the official code, and portability to newer versions needs to be supported. Additional features from the MPTCP standard can also be considered for implementation and evaluated afterwards.</span>&nbsp;&nbsp;</p>');
insert into document (documentID, lang, content) values (default, engels, 'Implementation of ORCHESTRA in NS-3 network simulator','<p><span lang=\"EN-US\">Modern connected devices are equipped with the ability to connect to the Internet using a variety of different wireless network technologies. Current network management solutions fail to provide a fine-grained, coordinated, and transparent answer to this heterogeneity, while the lower layers of the OSI stack simply ignore it by providing full separation of layers. To address this, the IDLAB research group proposed the ORCHESTRA framework to manage these networks. While a prototype implementation for research exists internally for the NS-3 network simulator, this version is not suited for public availability.</span>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p><span lang=\"EN-US\">The goal of this thesis is the implementation and evaluation of the ORCHESTRA framework in the latest version of the NS-3 simulator. This implementation should start from scratch, be as efficient and extendable as possible, with the coding guidelines of NS-3 in mind.<br />Focus should also be on supporting as much as possible communication technologies as possible (e.g., not only Wi-Fi but also LTE or other technologies implemented in NS-3). Furthermore, it should be possible to setup different types of networks or use-cases (e.g., LANs, Backhaul networks, or smart city networks).</span>&nbsp;&nbsp;</p>');
insert into document (documentID, lang, content) values (default, engels, 'Flexible auto-encoder for semi-supervised deep learning','<p><span lang=\"EN-US\">Deep Neural Networks have produced impressive results in cases where they can be trained in supervised mode using huge amount of labeled training data, but in practical applications labeled data often is scarce.&nbsp; Therefore, semi-supervised learning (using unlabeled data together with limited labeled data) is a longstanding challenge in machine learning.<br />One approach to this problem is to first learn a general internal representation of the data via an auto-encoder, and in a second step use this internal representation to train on the labeled data.&nbsp;</span><span style=\"letter-spacing: 0.02px;\">The way in which the type of auto-encoder and constraints imposed on the internal influence the overall result is an open area for research.&nbsp;</span></p>\r\n<p><span lang=\"EN-US\">The thesis will consist of:</span></p>\r\n<p><span lang=\"EN-US\">-&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</span><span lang=\"EN-US\">definition of the semi-supervised learning problem and benchmark criteria</span></p>\r\n<p><span lang=\"EN-US\">-&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</span><span lang=\"EN-US\">in-depth study of the general principles of auto-encoders,&nbsp;</span></p>\r\n<p><span lang=\"EN-US\">-&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</span><span lang=\"EN-US\">selection of the most promising variants of auto-encoders for semi-supervised learning and construction of a flexible implementation for easy comparison,&nbsp;</span></p>\r\n<p><span lang=\"EN-US\"><span lang=\"EN-US\">-experimentally compare auto-encoders on the defined benchmark</span>&nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;<br /></span></p>');
insert into document (documentID, lang, content) values (default, engels, 'Efficient Generative Adversarial Nets (GANs)','<p><span lang=\"EN-US\">In the field of deep neural networks, GANs have recently emerged as powerful generative models and are mostly known for generating realistic and sharp looking images. However, the generator-discriminator paradigm can also be used in other settings (e.g. in semi-supervised learning).&nbsp;<br />The computational aspects of GANs are an important aspect for future low-power implementations and have not been investigated in a systematic way.</span></p>\r\n<p><span lang=\"EN-US\">The thesis will consist of:</span></p>\r\n<p><span lang=\"EN-US\">-&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</span><span lang=\"EN-US\">in-depth study of the general principles of GANs,&nbsp;</span></p>\r\n<p><span lang=\"EN-US\">-&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</span><span lang=\"EN-US\">selection of the most promising variants w.r.t. computational efficiency (and optionally construct a new variant),&nbsp;</span></p>\r\n<p><span lang=\"EN-US\">-&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</span><span lang=\"EN-US\">definition and evaluation of stable training procedures,&nbsp;</span></p>\r\n<p><span lang=\"EN-US\">-experimentally compare the GANs on the defined benchmark&nbsp;</span></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>');
insert into document (documentID, lang, content) values (default, engels, 'Advanced NFC communication with nurse call devices ','<p><span lang=\"EN-US\">Televic Healthcare (THC) offers professional communication systems within the care sector for nurse call, intercom, access control, patient entertainment and care registration. Typically many devices need to be installed and configured. Recent mobile phones have an NFC interface which allows them to communicate via NFC to such devices. However in practice, major issues still appear to have a reliable communication link especially with small devices. In thesis we want to optimize the NFC communication and range between a smartphone and devices.</span></p>\r\n<p><span lang=\"EN-US\">The thesis includes the following tasks:</span></p>\r\n<p><span lang=\"EN-US\"><strong>Study part</strong></span></p>\r\n<p><span lang=\"EN-US\">o&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</span><span lang=\"EN-US\">Study of the NFC protocol and its alternatives</span></p>\r\n<p><span lang=\"EN-US\">o&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</span><span lang=\"EN-US\">Evaluate the standard and see which protocol features are supported on smartphones</span></p>\r\n<p><span lang=\"EN-US\">o&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</span><span lang=\"EN-US\">Survey of the available NFC chips and NFC antennas&nbsp;</span></p>\r\n<p><span lang=\"EN-US\"><strong>Hardware part</strong></span></p>\r\n<p><span lang=\"EN-US\">o&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</span><span lang=\"EN-US\">Investigation of the optimal NFC antenna and chipset to communicate with a smartphone</span></p>\r\n<p><span lang=\"EN-US\">o&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</span><span lang=\"EN-US\">Propose a solution for the alignment issue</span></p>\r\n<p><span lang=\"EN-US\">o&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</span><span lang=\"EN-US\">How to automatically tune the antenna depending on the type of smartphone</span></p>\r\n<p><span lang=\"EN-US\">o&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</span><span lang=\"EN-US\">How to mitigate the effect of closeby electronics</span></p>\r\n<p><span lang=\"EN-US\">o&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</span><span lang=\"EN-US\">Propose the most optimal design for a nurse call device taking into account mechanical constraints</span></p>\r\n<p><span lang=\"EN-US\"><strong>Embedded software part</strong></span></p>\r\n<p><span lang=\"EN-US\">o&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</span><span lang=\"EN-US\">Evaluate the most appropriate settings for different applications going from reading out device statistics to uploading a binary file</span></p>\r\n<p><span style=\"text-indent: -18pt; letter-spacing: 0.02px;\">o</span><span style=\"text-indent: -18pt; letter-spacing: 0.02px;\">&nbsp; &nbsp;</span><span style=\"text-indent: -18pt; letter-spacing: 0.02px;\">Building a demonstrator for a diagnostics application</span><span style=\"text-indent: -18pt; letter-spacing: 0.02px; font-family: Calibri, sans-serif; font-size: 12pt;\">&nbsp;</span></p>');
insert into document (documentID, lang, content) values (default, engels, 'IoT sensor network for passenger counting on trains','<p><span lang=\"EN-US\">Gathering and processing relevant data from a train&rsquo;s on-board systems can significantly increase the passenger user experience while allowing the train operator to optimize its operations. The sensors that collect such data need to comply to stringent safety and reliability requirements, while the total cost of ownership should be minimized. A typical use case is counting the passengers that board or alight a car and indicate which seats are occupied in a car while avoiding false positives.</span></p>\r\n<p><span lang=\"EN-US\">Make and evaluate a Proof of Concept of a low-cost, robust and scalable on-board seat occupancy and passenger counting system.</span></p>\r\n<p><span lang=\"EN-US\">&nbsp;</span></p>\r\n<p><span lang=\"EN-US\">Design challenges:</span></p>\r\n<p><span lang=\"EN-US\">&middot;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</span><span lang=\"EN-US\">Stringent security and safety requirements for railway applications</span></p>\r\n<p><span lang=\"EN-US\">&middot;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</span><span lang=\"EN-US\">Moving environment with changing train configurations (e.g. adding or removing cars) require a self-organizing and self-optimizing network</span></p>\r\n<p><span lang=\"EN-US\">&middot;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</span><span lang=\"EN-US\">Single system to handle both many sensors/low data rate and fewer sensors/higher data rate ad hoc events</span></p>\r\n<p><span lang=\"EN-US\">&middot;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</span><span lang=\"EN-US\">Define IoT protocol classification KPIs and make a shortlist of relevant IoT protocols for railway (with pros and cons). Select an appropriate protocol for the specific use case</span></p>\r\n<p><span lang=\"EN-US\">&middot;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</span><span lang=\"EN-US\">Select an appropriate sensor technology for the use case</span></p>\r\n<p><span lang=\"EN-US\">&middot;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</span><span lang=\"EN-US\">Design and build a Proof of Concept. Validate and characterize the system, explain deltas observed vs. expected behavior</span></p>\r\n<p><span lang=\"EN-US\">&middot;&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;Make a list of recommendations for further improvement&nbsp;</span></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>');
insert into document (documentID, lang, content) values (default, engels, 'Secure BLE connectivity for patient monitoring system ','<p><span lang=\"EN-US\">Reliable alarming and monitoring of patients is fundamental in today&rsquo;s healthcare system. Televic Healthcare (THC) offers professional communication systems within the care sector for nurse call, intercom, access control, patient entertainment and care registration. In its next generation nurse call system, THC wants to develop new terminals that act as a gateway for other devices in the room. Those devices are proprietary nurse call units as well as commercially available sensors that will connect on a wired or wireless fashion to this terminal.</span></p>\r\n<p><span lang=\"EN-US\">In this thesis, you will investigated what it takes to interface to a medical device/telemetry device using BLE. The following challenges need to be tackled:&nbsp;</span></p>\r\n<p><span lang=\"EN-US\">&middot;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</span><span lang=\"EN-US\">Connectivity over BLE&nbsp;</span><span lang=\"EN-US\"></span></p>\r\n<p><span lang=\"EN-US\">&middot;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</span><span lang=\"EN-US\">Study of device drivers needed&nbsp;</span><span lang=\"EN-US\"></span></p>\r\n<p><span lang=\"EN-US\">&middot;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</span><span lang=\"EN-US\">Onboarding the device&nbsp;</span><span lang=\"EN-US\"></span></p>\r\n<p><span lang=\"EN-US\">&middot;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</span><span lang=\"EN-US\">Making a device abstraction in order to use the data in an application&nbsp;</span><span lang=\"EN-US\"></span></p>\r\n<p><span lang=\"EN-US\">&middot;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</span><span lang=\"EN-US\">Finally an assessment in need of the privacy, security and other regulations</span></p>\r\n<p><span lang=\"EN-US\">The purpose is to make a demonstrator where the device is interfaced with an embedded platform. Additionally, a demo application to monitor and manage the device needs to be implemented to proof the feasibility of your solution.&nbsp;</span></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>');
insert into document (documentID, lang, content) values (default, engels, 'Linking Identity Server 4 to External Authentication services ','<p><span lang=\"EN-US\">Televic Education makes use of Identity Server (https://identityserver.github.io/Documentation/) for authenticating users to their products. Many customers already have their own Authentication Service. Televic Education already provides a way of linking their IdentityServer to an on premise AD FS server.</span>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p><span style=\"letter-spacing: 0.02px;\" lang=\"EN-US\">This thesis consists of 2 parts. First is upgrading the existing Identity Server 3 implementation to Identity Server 4 which is .NET Core.</span><span style=\"letter-spacing: 0.02px;\" lang=\"EN-US\"></span><span style=\"letter-spacing: 0.02px;\" lang=\"EN-US\">The second part will be investigating and implementing a generic way of defining links to customers. Examples of these Customer Authentication services are OAuth 2.0, OpenIdConnect,...&nbsp;</span><span style=\"letter-spacing: 0.02px;\" lang=\"EN-US\"></span><span style=\"letter-spacing: 0.02px;\">&nbsp;</span><span style=\"letter-spacing: 0.02px;\">&nbsp;</span></p>');
insert into document (documentID, lang, content) values (default, engels, 'Wireless but reliable connectivity for nurse call ','<p><span lang=\"EN-US\">Reliable alarming and monitoring of patients is fundamental in today&rsquo;s healthcare system. Televic Healthcare (THC) offers professional communication systems within the care sector for nurse call, intercom, access control, patient entertainment and care registration. Especially for renovation markets, it makes sense to also offer wireless connectivity as putting new cabling is often difficult. In this way it becomes possible that customers can install the latest and future version of the nurse call system.&nbsp;</span></p>\r\n<p><span lang=\"EN-US\">In this thesis, you will investigate WiFi mesh technology for communication between room terminals. Mesh technology is preferred in order not to depend on the present standard WiFi network and for the potential enhanced reliability. The fundamental challenge to solve is how reliability/QoS can be achieved. The following tasks are included:&nbsp;</span></p>\r\n<ul type=\"disc\">\r\n<li><span lang=\"EN-US\">Study of the standard&nbsp;</span><span lang=\"EN-US\"></span></li>\r\n<li><span lang=\"EN-US\">Selection of the most suited routing protocol&nbsp;</span><span lang=\"EN-US\"></span></li>\r\n<li><span lang=\"EN-US\">Simulation of the performance&nbsp;</span><span lang=\"EN-US\"></span></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p><span lang=\"EN-US\">o&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</span><span lang=\"EN-US\">Focus on routing, reliability, latency, scalability, QoS&nbsp;</span></p>\r\n<ul type=\"disc\">\r\n<li><span lang=\"EN-US\">Implementation (PoC) on an embedded platform</span></li>\r\n<ul type=\"circle\">\r\n<li><span lang=\"EN-US\">Platform selection</span></li>\r\n<li><span lang=\"EN-US\">Linux or C/C++ coding&nbsp;</span><span lang=\"EN-US\"></span></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<li><span lang=\"EN-US\">Study how to make a bridge to a in room BLE network where call units are connected to&nbsp;</span><span lang=\"EN-US\"></span></li>\r\n</ul>');
insert into document (documentID, lang, content) values (default, engels, 'CityLab and The Things Network','<p><span lang=\"EN-GB\">LoRaWAN is a promising LPWAN technology in unlicensed bands, which everyone can set up with a network server and basestations. Lots of solutions exist, each with different features, which makes choosing the best solution hard.&nbsp;</span></p>\r\n<p><span style=\"letter-spacing: 0.02px;\">The idea of this thesis is to compare (hands-on) the current LoRa network in City of Things, a solution provided by The Things Network (a free alternative) and the current City of Things LoRa clients. Focus is on flexibility and network management aspects.&nbsp;</span><span style=\"letter-spacing: 0.02px;\">This thesis starts from a hands-on comparison, with a small literature study, including a small proof of concept.</span></p>\r\n<!--EndFragment-->');
insert into document (documentID, lang, content) values (default, engels, 'Octa OTA update via NB-IoT/Cat-M1','<p><span lang=\"EN-GB\">In the past, IoT devices had to rely on very limited bandwidth to send their data or to control their behavior. With the arrival of NB-IoT this changed, as suddenly there is plenty of bandwidth to also push remote firmware updates. The problem is how to realize in the practice, without tradeoffs in terms of reliability or speed.</span></p>\r\n<p><span lang=\"EN-GB\">In this work the student will start from an existing NB-IoT chip integrated in the Octa hardware platform built and operated by IDLab. On top of this, the student will explore possible approaches to securely remotely update the firmware. One proof of concept will have to be developed completely.&nbsp;</span></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>');
insert into document (documentID, lang, content) values (default, engels, 'CityLab does Orchestra','<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p><span lang=\"EN-GB\">CityLab, the IDLab smart city testbed, supports a variety of technologies to connect sensors and to connect to other gateways. The choice for which wireless protocol is the best is depending on time varying characteristics such as interference.</span></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span lang=\"EN-GB\">CityLab, the IDLab smart city testbed, supports a variety of technologies to connect sensors and to connect to other gateways. The choice for which wireless protocol is the best is depending on time varying characteristics such as interference.</span></p>');
insert into document (documentID, lang, content) values (default, engels, 'CityLab learns','<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p><span lang=\"EN-GB\">CityLab, the IDLab smart city testbed, supports a variety of technologies to connect sensors and to connect to other gateways. The choice for which wireless protocol is the best is depending on time varying characteristics such as interference.</span></p>\r\n<p><span lang=\"EN-GB\"><span lang=\"EN-GB\">The goal of this thesis is to implement and validate learning techniques to manage the network between the CityLab gateways, e.g. to cope with time-varying interference or to support the best prediction of background interference. This would result in a small proof of concept where for prolonged periods of time data would have to be sent over multiple CityLab gateways, e.g. in the direction south-north. Performance and feasibility can then be checked.</span>&nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;</span></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>');
insert into document (documentID, lang, content) values (default, engels, 'CityLab5G','<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p><span lang=\"EN-GB\">In future 5G networks the concept of network slicing allows offering a differentiated service depending on the application requirements. To enable this, an orchestrator is necessary.</span></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span lang=\"EN-GB\">This thesis will implement a very basic network orchestrator, based on local 5G network VIM implementation. A proof of concept will be designed, where on-the-fly network services can be instantiated.</span></p>\r\n<p class=\"MsoNormal\">&nbsp;</p>');
insert into document (documentID, lang, content) values (default, engels, 'CityLabCl','<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>CityLab is built on top of EmuLab and jFED, tools which enable extensive remote testbed management on top of FreeBSD. However, little tools exist to validate changes in either FreeBSD packages/ports or EmuLab and jFed.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p><span style=\"letter-spacing: 0.02px;\" lang=\"EN-GB\">This thesis will design and implement a continuous integration pipeline, where continuously a setup of all CityLab EmuLab components can be run. This can then used to validate upcoming changes on an emulated testbed including servers and gateways. This result could then contribute to the European Fed4FIRE+ project.</span><span style=\"letter-spacing: 0.02px;\">&nbsp; &nbsp;</span><span style=\"letter-spacing: 0.02px;\">&nbsp;</span></p>');
insert into document (documentID, lang, content) values (default, engels, 'D7 hardware on OpenWSN','<p><span lang=\"EN-GB\">CityLab gateways support a variety of network protocols, including WiFi, BLE and sub-GHz protocols. For the latter, only the OSS-7 stack is available. However, for Zigbee the OpenMote hardware supports OpenWSN which could also support the current sub-GHz hardware.</span>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>This project starts with a basic port of OpenWSN to the sub-GHz hardware in the CityLab gateways, aiming to transfer capabilities of this bigger project to the gateways. The student will develop a proof of concept where existing OpenWSN demo code is ported to the new hardware. &nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>');
insert into document (documentID, lang, content) values (default, engels, 'Deep learning to classify data flows in Wi-Fi and LTE networks','<p><span style=\"font-family: Calibri, sans-serif; font-size: small;\">Spectrum scarcity is a phenomenon that we will face more and more in the near future. Different networks need to learn each other\'s needs and behavior. To evaluate other networks and make decisions, observation of other network\'s spectrum usage is really important. Recognizing flows and classifying them in different quality of service classes is necessary to check if networks have critical flows that cannot be interrupted. The goal of the thesis is twofold: 1) create a labeled dataset in which a lot of different flow types are captured. This could be from real devices in a testbed or via simulation software like MATLAB. 2) create and evaluate different deep neural networks to classify the captured data set.</span></p>');
insert into document (documentID, lang, content) values (default, engels, 'Create a RL agent for flow scheduling in an MF-TDMA network','<p>In current networks, nodes need to handle a lot of different flow with different quality of service requirements. Optimizing all these flows is a hard problem and can be very dynamic. Different flows require different strategies, some need to have a high throughput, others need to have a small latency. A lot of actions could be taken: which data packets need to be send in which order, is more bandwidth required,etc.. The goal of this topic is to create and evaluate a RL agent to handle all these actions for different flow mandates. To do this some other milestones need to be reached. 1) Set up an environment where the RL agent could play the game. 2) Collect and simulate data to use during the game. 3) Create and evaluate different strategies with the state-of-the-art.</p>');
insert into document (documentID, lang, content) values (default, engels, 'Enabling battery-less IoT devices','<p><span lang=\"EN-GB\">Traditionally batteries have been one of the main enablers to realise the vision of a global Internet of Things (IoT). They are convenient and ubiquitous. However, it is becoming clear that batteries are incompatible with a sustainable IoT. Batteries are expensive, bulky and hazardous. Replacing and disposing of billions or trillions of dead batteries per year will be costly and irresponsible. Battery maintenance is a major contributing factor to the operational costs of IoT deployments and inhibits the further upscaling of IoT and sensor networks. We can wait for batteries to improve, but we have no evidence that they will overcome these challenges in the foreseeable future. Instead, we propose to leave batteries behind and design systems that depend on harvested energy, store small amounts of energy in capacitors, and operate effectively in the face of frequent power outages. With these tiny intermittently powered computers, we can gather data in hard to reach places, maintenance free, for decades.</span></p>\r\n<p><span lang=\"EN-US\">Energy harvesting is one of the key challenges in batteryless communication. Currently, there are several ways to harvest energy. For example, photovoltaic, thermal, vibration and RF based. However, there are no benchmarks to compare and test which harvesting method performs best for wireless sensor network (WSN) communication and internet-of-things applications. The goal of this work is to integrate the energy harvesting methods with existing WSN technologies (e.g. LoRa) and compare the results in terms of energy drained/dissipated and network performance for different harvesting schemes. On the other hand, another (possibly additional) goal can be to develop energy harvesting prediction models to improve the performance of whole WSN or to schedule more efficiently tasks.</span>&nbsp; &nbsp;</p>');
insert into document (documentID, lang, content) values (default, engels, 'Nanoscale communications for wirelessly programmable robotic materials','<p><span lang=\"EN-US\">Traditional communication methods have limited capacity, spectrum and large requirements of antenna size to satisfy the increasing demand for higher speed wireless communication. This makes them unsuitable for communication at the nanoscale, where devices are smaller than a speck of dust. A variety of nanoscale applications are being investigated, such as intra-body monitoring of molecule concentrations, interconnection of tiny nanoscale robots, or the design of novel programmable materials (e.g., artificial sensory robot skin). Terahertz (THz) Band (0.1&ndash;10 THz) communication can alleviate the spectrum scarcity, capacity and antenna size limitations of traditional wireless systems and can enable new applications both in classical networking domains as well as in nanoscale communication paradigms.</span></p>\r\n<p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span lang=\"EN-US\">In this work, we will specifically investigate the performance of some existing modulation schemes for THz communication for use in programmable robotic materials (e.g., artificial skin or muscles), which are embedded with nanoscale sensors and actuators. The different methods will be evaluated and compared using existing analytical models. Moreover, the student will implement these models in Nano-Sim, an ns-3 based simulator for THz nanoscale communications. In case of master thesis, the results can be leveraged to propose further optimizations to these schemes in order to improve their performance. This topic will allow you to work on an emerging technology with a wide range of long-term and futuristic applications.</span></p>');
insert into document (documentID, lang, content) values (default, engels, 'Managing flexible multimodal IoT devices','<p><span lang=\"EN-US\">Low Power Wide Area (LPWA) networks have the ability to offer affordable connectivity to low-power IoT devices spread in large geographical areas. A lot of LPWA technologies have been developed in order to make this possible, such as LoRa, NB-IoT and Wi-Fi Halow.&nbsp;</span></p>\r\n<p><span lang=\"EN-US\">These technologies, however, have some trade-offs. LoRa offers a range up to 15km, but only has a throughput of a few kilobits per second. NB-IoT has a slightly higher data rate up to 250 kbps, but requires an expensive subscription with sim card. Finally, Wi-Fi HaLow has a shorter range of up to 1 km, but supports data rates up to nearly 8 Mbps. Combining these technologies into a single IoT device, would allow the device to leverage the advantages of all technologies, and switch to the one that is most suitable in its current context.</span></p>\r\n<p><span lang=\"EN-US\"><span lang=\"EN-US\">As a first step towards combining these technologies, their performance (in terms of scalability, range, throughput, energy consumption) needs to be compared in detail. As implementations of all 3 technologies are available in the ns-3 network simulator, ns-3 will be used to run various scenarios and compare performance. Moreover, small scale tests can be performed using real hardware as a benchmark for accuracy. If this topic is selected for a master thesis, the comparative results can be further used to develop a handover algorithm that selects the right technology under the right circumstances. This project will give you the opportunity to work with several state of the art low-power wireless IoT technologies and gain in-depth knowledge about the inner-workings of these networking protocols.</span>&nbsp;</span></p>');
insert into document (documentID, lang, content) values (default, engels, 'Over-the-air firmware updates for IoT devices over cellular networks','<p><span lang=\"EN-US\">3GPP (telecommunications standard development organizations) has proposed a new radio technology standard named as Narrow-band IoT (NB-IoT) that has been developed to enable a wide range of IoT devices and things to be connected using the long-term evolution (LTE) network already used by smartphones. The data rate used for NB-IoT is very low and IoT devices have very limited battery capacity, which makes it difficult to send large amounts of downlink data to the sensors. Therefore, over-the-air firmware updating is a challenge.</span>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p><span lang=\"EN-US\">The student can work on exploring different existing methods and propose a new mechanism for firmware update in NB-IoT. It is also needed to measure different parameters (e.g. expected battery consumption) which can be calculated by implementing the proposal on a real device.</span></p>\r\n<p><span lang=\"EN-US\">About us: We are closely working with telecom operator Orange who provide us the NB-IoT enabled base-station access and NB-IoT end-devices.</span></p>\r\n<p><span lang=\"EN-US\">Gain: This project will give you the opportunity to gain in-depth knowledge about the NB-IoT technology, over-the-air firmware updates, hardware interfaces, and research-based work.</span></p>');
insert into document (documentID, lang, content) values (default, engels, 'MAC protocol analysis on IEEE 802.11 networks','<p><span lang=\"EN-US\">A wide variety of wireless MAC protocol implementations have been proposed, especially because of the rise of the Internet of Things (IoT). These protocols are usually optimized for specific scenarios and application-layer requirements and their diverse traffic demand are rarely considered in their design (e.g., sensitivity to packet loss, jitter, and latency requirements for massive, ultra-reliable, and extremely low latency wireless applications). However, the evolution of the Software-Defined Radios (SDR)s and the Software-Defined Networking (SDN) paradigm enabled to perform on-the-fly software reconfigurations with high performance and high versatility on the entire Medium Access Control (MAC) layer. However, the impact of changing those protocols can be crucial. Therefore, remains a challenge to estimate and associate which performance metrics are affected by MAC protocol configurations.</span>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p><span lang=\"EN-US\">To provide a solution to identify and correlate MAC-specific configurations/parameters or different versions of the protocol with network performance metrics such as delay, jitter, and latency. In addition, to identify patterns on other networks transmissions in order to adapt and cooperate if possible. The solution should be able to estimate the impact of MAC parameter configurations by making use of a Machine Learning (ML) algorithm, for instance. In this way, being able to provide insights into management systems to cope with Quality of Service (QoS) requirements on such networks.</span>&nbsp; &nbsp;</p>');
insert into document (documentID, lang, content) values (default, engels, 'Implementation of Next Generation Interfaces for 5G system functional split','<p><span lang=\"EN-US\">The new 5G architecture proposes the virtualization the different radio layers, proposing new protocols to fulfil the communication that traditionally is embedded in a chip. Splitting and virtualizing the radio functions provide a new degree of flexibility for the next generation of the Radio Access Network. New technologies such as Software Defined Radio allow now the implementation of the radio functionalities on general purpose hardware instead of traditional radio-oriented hardware (FPGA) providing a fully reprogrammable platform.</span>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p><span lang=\"EN-US\">The goal is to implement the transport protocols between different radio layers (PHY-&gt; MAC, MAC -&gt; RLC, RLC -&gt; PDCP) extending a open-source eNB implementation written in C/C++.&nbsp;</span></p>\r\n<p><span lang=\"EN-US\">Later, the student will assess a performance evaluation of this new approach.</span></p>');
insert into document (documentID, lang, content) values (default, engels, 'Distributed Hierarchical Temporal Memory in NuPIC','<p><span lang=\"EN-US\">Due to increases in available computational power, artificial intelligence and machine learning are currently being used to solve problems in a large array of fields. One implementation of machine learning that has largely remained under the radar is the Hierarchical Temporal Memory (HTM), a spatially and temporally aware machine algorithm attempting to mimic the workings of the human brain. Analysis of its reference implementation in the NuPIC framework shows that the algorithm runs as a single-core application, severely limiting how much and how quickly it can learn. As progress in computational power is currently focused on multicore, manycore and cloud computing architectures, improving performance will require design and implementation effort.</span>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p><span lang=\"EN-US\">The goal of this internship is to extend the HTM implementation in the NuPIC framework to work distributed across multiple cores or even machines. This could include:</span></p>\r\n<p><span lang=\"EN-US\">&middot;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</span><span lang=\"EN-US\">Parallelizing the non-temporal components and merging their learned info across instances</span></p>\r\n<p><span lang=\"EN-US\">&middot;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</span><span lang=\"EN-US\">Distributing the different components, each with their own performance requirements, across heterogeneous machines (e.g., local and cloud)</span></p>\r\n<p><span lang=\"EN-US\">Once distribution is achieved, you will evaluate its runtime efficiency and gauge the impact of any changes to the algorithm on accuracy using existing applications of HTM (e.g., sequence prediction).</span></p>');
insert into document (documentID, lang, content) values (default, engels, 'Developing and Evaluating a Behaviour Based Code Coverage Metric','<h2>Introduction</h2>\r\n<p>Code coverage is a metric used to describe the degree to which the source code of a program is executed when a particular test suite runs. It is used by developers to determine if their test suite has adequately tested their production code. However, the coverage metric does not take into account what actually has been verified in the test. A test can simply call production code without checking the system using assertions. This can skew the perception of how good a test suite is.</p>\r\n<p>The goal of this research project is to improve the test coverage metrics by utilising the &nbsp;test behaviour [1], and showing this improvement in a comparative study.</p>\r\n<h2>Details</h2>\r\n<p>In this research project, the student develops a new code coverage metric based on the test behaviour. This metric should then be evaluated in a comparative study against existing code coverage metrics. During the development of the research project, the student will improve his/her knowledge of:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li><span style=\"letter-spacing: 0.02px;\">&nbsp; &nbsp; Code coverage metrics</span></li>\r\n<li><span style=\"letter-spacing: 0.02px;\">&nbsp; &nbsp; Test behaviour</span></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<h2>Requirements</h2>\r\n<p>The skills required for this research project are:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li><span style=\"letter-spacing: 0.02px;\">&nbsp; &nbsp; Good programming skills.</span></li>\r\n<li><span style=\"letter-spacing: 0.02px;\">&nbsp; &nbsp; Prior knowledge on or experience with code coverage metrics would be useful.</span></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<h2>Related work</h2>\r\n<p>[1] B. van Bladel and S. Demeyer. Test refactoring: a research agenda. In Post-proceedings of the Tenth Seminar on Advanced Techniques and Tools for Software Evolution. CEUR, 2017</p>');
insert into document (documentID, lang, content) values (default, engels, 'Behaviour Based Control Systems for (Semi-)Autonomous Drone Flight','<p class=\"MsoNormal\" style=\"background-image: initial; background-position: initial; background-size: initial; background-repeat: initial; background-attachment: initial; background-origin: initial; background-clip: initial;\"><span style=\"font-size: 9pt; font-family: Verdana, sans-serif;\" lang=\"EN-GB\">[Thesis in collaboration with the Active Perception Lab -&nbsp;</span><span lang=\"NL\"><a href=\"https://www.uantwerpen.be/en/rg/engineering-management/research-teams/active-perception-la/\"><strong><span style=\"font-size: 9pt; font-family: Verdana, sans-serif;\" lang=\"EN-GB\">https://www.uantwerpen.be/en/rg/engineering-management/research-teams/active-perception-la/</span></strong></a></span><span style=\"font-size: 9pt; font-family: Verdana, sans-serif;\" lang=\"EN-GB\">&nbsp;]</span></p>\r\n<p class=\"MsoNormal\" style=\"background-image: initial; background-position: initial; background-size: initial; background-repeat: initial; background-attachment: initial; background-origin: initial; background-clip: initial;\"><span style=\"font-size: 9pt; font-family: Verdana, sans-serif;\" lang=\"EN-GB\">1. Context</span></p>\r\n<p class=\"MsoNormal\" style=\"background-image: initial; background-position: initial; background-size: initial; background-repeat: initial; background-attachment: initial; background-origin: initial; background-clip: initial;\"><span style=\"font-size: 9pt; font-family: Verdana, sans-serif;\" lang=\"EN-GB\">Real world applications for drones are becoming more widespread.&nbsp; To act in the real world such drones have to react autonomously to rapidly and unpredictably changing environments.&nbsp; Providing such real-time response capability requires drone manufacturers to look into portable sensing technologies.&nbsp; In addition, to react appropriately on the information provided by the sensors an intelligent control system has to run on the drone.</span></p>\r\n<p class=\"MsoNormal\" style=\"background-image: initial; background-position: initial; background-size: initial; background-repeat: initial; background-attachment: initial; background-origin: initial; background-clip: initial;\"><span style=\"font-size: 9pt; font-family: Verdana, sans-serif;\" lang=\"EN-GB\">2. Project</span></p>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size: 9pt; font-family: Verdana, sans-serif;\" lang=\"EN-GB\">In the literature on autonomous robots a number of intelligent control systems have been proposed.&nbsp; After a thorough study of the subset of so-called behaviour based control systems you will implement the selected scheme on a raspberry pi so that it supports real-time sensor driven control of the drone.&nbsp; &nbsp;The sensor system, consisting of the biomimetic sonar developed in the lab, will be integrated into the controller to provide basic obstacle avoidance capability. Note that the controller should smoothly integrate user commands for the motors with the (possibly overriding) motor commands from the autonomous behaviours. &nbsp;If time permits the collected sonar snapshots will be integrated into a view-based map of an indoor environment.</span></p>');
insert into document (documentID, lang, content) values (default, engels, 'data mining en machine learning  op classificaties door citizen scientists','<p>Because of the language of most of the available material, a good knowledge of Dutch is required.</p>\r\n<p><span style=\"letter-spacing: 0.02px;\">Deze beschrijving betreft meerdere mogelijke onderwerpen die, afhankelijk van de focus en diepgang, kunnen gekozen worden voor Onderzoeks stage of thesis.</span></p>\r\n<p>Een uitgebreide beschrijving vind je op:&nbsp;https://www.dropbox.com/s/p4pba28e5a26afg/Thesisvoorstel-RMZ.doc?dl=0</p>\r\n<p>supervisor: Toon Calders</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>');
insert into document (documentID, lang, content) values (default, engels, 'Data Generator for Anomaly Detection in Business Processes','<p class=\"MsoPlainText\"><span style=\"letter-spacing: 0.02px;\">The biggest challenge nowadays when building anomaly detection systems for business processes is the lack of sufficient real world and high quality synthetic data for testing the performance of these systems. We want to create a tool that is able to generate realistic looking multi-dimensional data including realistic types of anomalies, based on given business processes. Rather than introducing random values in random places. Next we want to use this tool in order to test our own method and compare it to existing methods.</span></p>\r\n<p class=\"MsoPlainText\"><span style=\"letter-spacing: 0.02px;\">Promotor: Toon Calders<br />Supervisor: Stephen Pauwels</span></p>');
insert into document (documentID, lang, content) values (default, engels, 'NodeBox OpenGL draw performance','<p>Research question: can we improve the draw performance of NodeBox by porting it to OpenGL?</p>\r\n<p>NodeBox is an open-source application that lets you create 2D visuals (static, animated or interactive) using Python programming code and export them as a PDF or a QuickTime movie. NodeBox is free and well-documented.</p>\r\n<p>NodeBox is currently written as a Mac OS X application, using the Quartz graphics API. Multiple ports exists, for example to Qt in Linux. It is our belief that a port to OpenGL can improve performance. OpenGL provides a set of modern API\'s related to vertex arrays, Vertex Buffer Objects, etc. The project would study the impact of each of these features on the performance, while keeping the current NodeBox drawing API intact.</p>\r\n<p>http://nodebox.net/ http://www.cityinabottle.org/nodebox/</p>');
insert into document (documentID, lang, content) values (default, engels, 'NodeBox 2: parallelization');
insert into document (documentID, lang, content) values (default, engels, 'Energy consumption modeling in OpenWSN: An open source protocol stack for the Internet of Things ','<p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span style=\"text-align: justify; letter-spacing: 0.02px;\">The Internet-of-Things revolution is based upon the premise of having a plethora of everyday devices being online and sharing information over the Internet. Many of those devices are sensors, such as temperature sensors, humidity sensors, gyroscopes or cameras. These sensors generate huge datasets that can be used to improve our knowledge of the environment and the environment itself.<br /></span><span style=\"letter-spacing: 0.02px; text-align: justify;\"><br />However, one of the biggest challenges of these sensors is their energy-efficiency: you do not want to be the person that has to replace the batteries of hundreds of sensors every week. A state of the art sensor device, running on a simple AA battery, can run for many years using extremely optimized wireless communications protocols.<br /></span><span style=\"letter-spacing: 0.02px; text-align: justify;\"><br />One such widely used protocol is IEEE802.15.4e, which is implemented in the OpenWSN project. It contains both firmware for real hardware (e.g., OpenMote) as well as a network simulator. Many people conducting research into Internet-of-Things are using the OpenWSN software to evaluate their research. Ironically, at this moment the OpenWSN simulator does not support any energy consumption models. The goal of this internship is to implement the energy consumption model proposed in [1] in the OpenWSN project. This would allow researchers to evaluate the energy efficiency of their work in the OpenWSN simulator.<br /><br /></span><span style=\"letter-spacing: 0.02px; text-align: justify;\">In this internship, you will be programming in Python and C directly into the MAC layer of the IEEE802.15.4e protocol stack. You will have the opportunity to implement the energy model into the simulator and also validate your results and perform measurements with real OpenMote hardware. The ultimate goal is to integrate your code into an official OpenWSN release, allowing you to contribute to a widely used piece of open source software.<br /></span><span style=\"text-align: justify; letter-spacing: 0.02px;\"><br />[1] Vilajosana, Xavier, et al. \"A realistic energy consumption model for TSCH networks.\"&nbsp;</span><em style=\"text-align: justify; letter-spacing: 0.02px;\">Sensors Journal, IEEE</em><span style=\"text-align: justify; letter-spacing: 0.02px;\">&nbsp;14.2 (2014): 482-489.</span></p>\r\n<p class=\"MsoNormal\">&nbsp;</p>');
insert into document (documentID, lang, content) values (default, engels, 'Visual exploration of log files','<p class=\"MsoPlainText\"><span style=\"letter-spacing: 0.02px;\">The execution of business processes is often recorded as a list of events in a log file or business process management tool. This log contains the activity that was performed, the timestamp when it was performed, the person who performed it, the document(s) used, ...&nbsp; All this data is stored in a multi-variate log file. These log files both contain a temporal aspect and a multi-dimensional one.</span></p>\r\n<p class=\"MsoPlainText\">The goal of this project is to implement a tool that allows users to visually explore these log files, where the user should both be able to explore the temporal aspect as well as the the multi-dimensional aspect. These visuals are based on a model, called eDBN (extended Dynamic Bayesian Network), developed in our research group, that scores events and their attributes. Your task is to extend the new chart types that were proposed in our research, make them interactive, and create a user-friendly visual environment that allows users to interactively explore the data using the measures derived from our eDBN model.</p>\r\n<p class=\"MsoPlainText\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n<table id=\"project-connections\" style=\"color: #000000; font-size: 12px; letter-spacing: 0.02px;\">\r\n<tbody>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td>Promoter(s)</td>\r\n<td>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Toon Calders</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td>Supervisor(s)</td>\r\n<td>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Stephen Pauwels</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>');
insert into document (documentID, lang, content) values (default, engels, 'Reducing noise of mutation testing a.k.a ranking mutants according to their importance','<h2>Introduction</h2>\r\n<p>Mutation testing is the state-of-the-art technique for assessing the fault-detection capacity of a test suite. It deliberately injects faults in the code base to verify if the test suite can detect them. However, developers can be overwhelmed by the sheer amount of survived mutants (undetected faults). This can make it especially difficult for the developers to write extra tests where it would matters most.</p>\r\n<p>The goal of this thesis is to reduce the amount of noise that is reported to the developer by analysing which mutants are the most important. The criteria for ranking mutants to an importance factor can include the place, coverage, and impact of the mutants. The best way to report all undetected mutants and their ranking should be investigated. This can involve grouping mutants together based on location and/or similarity.</p>\r\n<h2>Details</h2>\r\n<p><span style=\"letter-spacing: 0.02px;\">In this thesis, the student has to:</span></p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li><span style=\"letter-spacing: 0.02px;\">Create a tool for ranking/classification of mutant importance</span></li>\r\n<li>Create a visualisation for the reports/important mutants</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<h2>Requirements</h2>\r\n<p>The skills required for the Master Thesis are:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Good programming skills (better if she/he knows Java/Python)</li>\r\n<li>Prior knowledge about software testing, code coverage etc.&nbsp;would be useful.</li>\r\n</ul>');
insert into document (documentID, lang, content) values (default, engels, 'Automatic test expansion for mutation testing','<h2>Introduction</h2>\r\n<p>Mutation testing is the state-of-the-art technique for assessing the fault-detection capacity of a test suite. It deliberately injects faults in the code base to verify if the test suite can detect them. Additional tests for undetected mutants can be automatically generated using test generation tools. However, the maintainability of these tests is questionable as it is possible that these tests are improved duplicates of existing tests.</p>\r\n<p>The goal of this internship is to investigate whether expanding existing tests, without altering their original goal, can be used as a developer aid to easily and quickly improve the quality of the test suite (i.e. detecting more mutants). E.g., the tool detects that an additional assert statement in a specific test would detect a survived mutant. The tool would then suggest this addition to the developer (showing the test, the addition, and the mutant). If the developers agrees that the assert is in line with the test&rsquo;s goal, he can allow the tool to add the assert statement.</p>\r\n<h2>Details</h2>\r\n<p><span style=\"letter-spacing: 0.02px;\">In this internship, the student has to:</span></p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li><span style=\"letter-spacing: 0.02px;\">Create a tool to aid developers with expanding/improving existing tests to detect previously undetected mutants (e.g. Y/N suggestions)</span></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<h2>Requirements</h2>\r\n<p>The skills required for the&nbsp;internship&nbsp;are:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Good programming skills (better if she/he knows Java/Python)</li>\r\n<li>Prior knowledge about software testing, code coverage etc. would be useful.</li>\r\n<li>Knowledge about IDE plug-ins can be useful, as this could optionally be part of the tool</li>\r\n</ul>');
insert into document (documentID, lang, content) values (default, engels, 'Multilingual Embeddings in NLP models','<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p class=\"MsoNormal\">Current NLP tasks like classification require starting from scratch in every language. Labeled datasets have to exist in every language. A lot of progress has been made in generating multilingual embeddings that can be reused across multiple languages. This would allow models to be trained on one language and then applied to another language. Another application would be to jointly learn an NLP task from multilingual data, increasing the total number of labelled examples. In this internship, you will benchmark and compare the performance of standard NLP tasks by using multilingual embeddings vs monolingual embeddings. You will work together with the Faktion NLU-team, consisting of 8 seasoned NLP experts.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p class=\"MsoNormal\">Expected outcomes:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Benchmark results that compare the use of multilingual embeddings vs monolingual embeddings</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p>Skills Required:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Some programming experiences in any Python R, Javascript or Java is required</li>\r\n<li>Native speaker of Dutch or English</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p>About Faktion:</p>\r\n<p>We are an applied artiicial intelligence engineering service provide, with headquarters in Antwerp (Belgium). Our in-depth knowlegde of artificial intelligence, conversational agents, and an array of emerging technologies make us the first choice for companies with a vision and budget. Faktion has built Chatlayer.ai, the conversation management system for building chatbots in use at most major Belgian companies.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>');
insert into document (documentID, lang, content) values (default, engels, 'Expression Generation for Chatbot NLP\'s','<p><span style=\"letter-spacing: 0.02px;\">Chatbot NLP&rsquo;s rely on</span><span style=\"mso-spacerun: yes;\">&nbsp;</span><span style=\"letter-spacing: 0.02px;\">expressions</span><span style=\"mso-spacerun: yes;\">&nbsp;</span><span style=\"letter-spacing: 0.02px;\">(sometimes called</span><span style=\"mso-spacerun: yes;\">&nbsp;</span><span style=\"letter-spacing: 0.02px;\">utterances ) to train the recognition of intents.</span><span style=\"mso-spacerun: yes;\">&nbsp;</span><span style=\"letter-spacing: 0.02px;\">Little is known about how these expressions should be generated. For example, should they contain typo&rsquo;s, dialect, punctuation, proper casing? Should they contain &ldquo;generic filler text&rdquo; like</span><span style=\"mso-spacerun: yes;\">&nbsp; </span><span style=\"letter-spacing: 0.02px;\">&ldquo;I have question about ... can you help me with that&rdquo;</span><span style=\"mso-spacerun: yes;\">&nbsp;</span><span style=\"letter-spacing: 0.02px;\">? Do you need every combination of synonyms, or just every synonym once? In this research, you will look at the driving factors for generating good, high-quality expressions for chatbots.</span></p>\r\n<p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span style=\"letter-spacing: 0.02px;\">Expected outcomes:</span></p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Guidelines for creating expressions</li>\r\n<li>Objective data to support the guidelines</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span style=\"font-size: x-small;\">Skills required:</span></p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Some programming experience in any Python R, Javascript or Java is recommended</li>\r\n<li>Native speaker of Dutch or English</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span style=\"font-size: x-small;\">About Faktion XYZ:</span></p>\r\n<p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span style=\"font-size: x-small;\">We are an applied artificial intelligence engineering service provider, with headquarters in Antwerp (Belgium). Our in-depth knowledge of artificial intelligence, conversational agents, and an array of emerging technologies makes us the first choice for companies with a vision and budget. Faktion has built Chatbot.ai, the conversation management system for building chatbots in use at most major Belgian companies.</span></p>');
insert into document (documentID, lang, content) values (default, engels, 'Messaging Broker C++','<p><span style=\"letter-spacing: 0.02px;\">OM Partners is a software and consulting company focused on Supply Chain Planning. As a company we have but one mission: to optimize our customer&rsquo;s supply chain. We pride ourselves on developing innovative Advanced Planning Systems (APS) that meet and exceed expectations. Our customer base includes leading companies in different industries, such as ArcelorMittal, BASF, Dow, Johnson &amp; Johnson, Michelin, Shaw, Procter &amp; Gamble and Smurfit Kappa. The OMP software development group consists of almost 100 software engineers spread across our offices in Belgium (Antwerp(HQ) , Gent and Waver), Ukraine(Lviv) and the USA (Atlanta). Respect, team spirit and creativity are the cornerstones of our working culture.</span></p>\r\n<p class=\"MsoNormal\"><strong>Keywords</strong>:</p>\r\n<p class=\"MsoNormal\">MessageBrokers (Kafka, RabbitMg), event based architectures, C++</p>\r\n<p class=\"MsoNormal\"><strong>Abstract</strong>:</p>\r\n<p class=\"MsoNormal\">In distributed systems there are often many-to many communications between services (aka the publish-subscribe model). In such settings messaging brokers play a fundamental role.</p>\r\n<p class=\"MsoNormal\">Many different messaging broker systems exist nowadays (Qpid, RabbitMQ, Kafka, ActiveMQ,&hellip;) all with their strength and weaknesses.</p>\r\n<p class=\"MsoNormal\">In this research project the goal would be:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Evaluate the different brokers against each other towards performance, reliability, security , protocol support (AMQP,MQTT,STOMP,&hellip;),general feature set and client language support.</li>\r\n<li>Implement message broker integration into OMP ecosystem&nbsp;</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p><strong><span style=\"letter-spacing: 0.02px;\">Expected Work:</span></strong></p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Obtain in-depth knowledge on Message brokers</li>\r\n<li>Evaluate the different available Message brokers</li>\r\n<li>Integration of Message broker into OMP ecosystem (e.g. log/event monitoring over OMP services, Usage of message broker in integration context)</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p><span style=\"text-decoration: underline; font-size: small;\"><strong>Relevent links:</strong></span></p>\r\n<p class=\"MsoNormal\"><a href=\"https://kafka.apache.org/\">https://kafka.apache.org/</a></p>\r\n<p class=\"MsoNormal\"><a href=\"https://www.rabbitmq.com/\">https://www.rabbitmq.com/</a></p>\r\n<p class=\"MsoNormal\"><a href=\"http://activemq.apache.org/\">http://activemq.apache.org/</a></p>\r\n<p class=\"MsoNormal\"><a style=\"font-size: 11pt; letter-spacing: 0.02px;\" href=\"https://qpid.apache.org/\">https://qpid.apache.org/</a></p>');
